INSERT INTO `ProgramaPPT` (`Identificador`, `NombreIngles`, `MensajeIngles`, `MensajeSocialIngles`, `IntroduccionIngles`, `DescripcionIngles`, `IncluyeIngles`, `MasInformacionIngles`, `FAQIngles`, `Enlace`, `IdDestino`, `DestinosIngles`, `IdActividad`, `IdTipo`, `Precio`, `Duracion`, `DuracionIngles`, `Dificultad`, `EsPortada`, `OrdenPortada`, `CodigoWeTravel`, `CantidadImagenes`, `IdCategoria`) VALUES
(1, 'Late Morning departure Rainbow Mountain Tour', 'Experience the Rainbow Mountain Tour like never before with our unique approach. Our journey begins at 8:00 am as we embark on a scenic 2.5-hour drive. Upon reaching the trailhead, you’ll discover a tranquil setting with no other groups in sight. It’s just us, surrounded by breathtaking mountain vistas.', 'By booking this tour, your are planting 1 tree at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'Explore the enchanting Rainbow Mountain, Situated at an impressive altitude of 5,200 meters, this natural wonder lies over 100 kilometers from Cusco', '<p>Explore the enchanting Rainbow Mountain, Situated at an impressive   altitude of 5,200 meters, this natural wonder lies over 100 kilometers   from Cusco.</p>\n<p>Join our carefully crafted day tour to experience this renowned   destination without the bustling crowds. Departing at 08:00 am, rather   than the 3 am, you&rsquo;ll enjoy the breathtaking vistas in peace, free from   the usual tourist crowds. With a small and intimate group, you can savor   unobstructed views and gain insights into this extraordinary landscape   from our knowledgeable guide.</p>', '<p>Unlike everyone, we will pick you up at your hotel around 8:15 a.m. to start this incredible <strong>Rainbow Mountain tour</strong> in the afternoon. </p>\n<p>We calmly drive around 2 hours towards   the restaurant where we will stop for toilets, then, we will continue   our journey to the trailhead, where the starting point of the hike is.<br>\n  Beginning at 4.800 m.a.s.l, heading to the top -by horse or walking- one can see a truly impressive view of a glacier. </p>\n<p>At the very top, you will find yourself at 5.030 m.a.s.l, and a 360&ordm; colorful view of the andes that you will never, <em>ever</em>, forget we will have around 30 &ndash; 40 minutes in the top. </p>\n<p>While you enjoy the amazing views, our   guide will offer you a nice hot coca tea, the advantage of doing the   Rainbow Mountain Tour with us it is that you will be almost&nbsp; the only   ones at the top, no one else will be there since big groups goes very   early, and for the time that we arrive everyone is gone.</p>\n<p>When we are back on the bus, we will   go to a nice restaurant with vegetarian options in Cusipata, and after   that we go back to Cusco city and drop you off at your hotel.</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Duration:&nbsp;</strong>11 Hours</li>\n  <li><strong>Start time: </strong>08:00&nbsp;a.m.</li>\n  <li><strong>End time: </strong>18:30&nbsp;p.m.</li>\n  <li><strong>Maximum elevation point:&nbsp;</strong>5036 masl (Viewpoint)</li>\n  <li><strong>Difficulty:&nbsp;</strong>Medium, Difficult</li>\n</ul>', '<h3>What to bring the rainbow mountain tour day.</h3>\n<p>Please take note of these recommendations to do the Rainbow Mountain Tour.</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>PASSPORT OR IDENTITY DOCUMENT</strong>&nbsp;(VERY IMPORTANT)</li>\n  <li><strong>Hat or cap for the sun:</strong> Very important for the walk, radiation is stronger on the rainbow mountain tour.</li>\n  <li><strong>Sunglasses:</strong>&nbsp;Highly recommended.</li>\n  <li><strong>Sunscreen:</strong>&nbsp;The radiation in the mountains is stronger, use&nbsp;sunscreen every day.</li>\n  <li><strong>Waterproof jacket or windbreaker</strong>&nbsp;(if it is light much better)</li>\n  <li><strong>Gloves:</strong> Especially for when you are on the the Rainbow Mountain Viewpoint, because there it is very windy and cold.</li>\n  <li><strong>Bottle of water or CAMELBAK.</strong>&nbsp; double the regular dose of water you drink normally.</li>\n  <li><strong>Shoe with</strong> a <strong>good grip:</strong>&nbsp;If you have trekking shoe is much better</li>\n  <li><strong>Personal medication pills:</strong> Do not forget to take your personal medication, most importantly the ones you take daily.</li>\n  <li><strong>Others you consider necessary.</strong> However, remember that this is an ADVENTURE walk!</li>\n  <li><strong>Above all, a lot of desire to have fun, enjoy nature and learn about&nbsp;the local culture</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Altitude sickness</h3>\n<p>As soon as the people reserve the trip to Peru, specifically to   Cusco, they begin to wonder about altitude sickness. High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.</p>\n<p>In our rainbow mountain tour in the afternoon we will always have   oxygen tank and first aid kit, our guides all well trained to assist you   in case you have any altitude sympthom.</p>\n<p>For farther information about altitude sickness please read our article <a href=\"http://www.pptoursperu.com/en/altitud-sickness/\" target=\"_blank\">HERE.</a></p>\n<h3>Weather</h3>\n<p>The weather in he Rainbow Mountain is unpredictable. Dry season in   Cusco is from April through October, but this does not prevent the rain   from falling in June or the sun coming out in December, just be prepared   for any weather.</p>\n<p>Make sure you have adequate clothing that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho and waterproof gloves.</p>\n<p>Also be prepared for a very cold day in the rainbow mountain tour, once in the top, it will be cold and windy.</p>\n<h3>Arriving to Cusco</h3>\n<p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU, LC PERU&nbsp;to choose according to your preference.</p>\n<p>Expect&nbsp;flight delays or cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of   Cusco, tends to be difficult to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can   paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.</p>\n<h3>Travel insurance</h3>\n<p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying travel   insurance. Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.</p>\n<p>There are many insurance companies depending on your country of   origin and at different prices according to your time of stay, take some   time to review them and hire the one that best suits you. However, this   is an excellent way to protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>\n<h3>Community</h3>\n<p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our community.&nbsp;This   is&nbsp;the&nbsp;main&nbsp;objective&nbsp;for our company.&nbsp;We are working&nbsp;directly with the   villages to help them meet the needs of their families.&nbsp;We support the   children of the villages by giving them&nbsp;school supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and   clothes.</p>\n<p>PPT offers constant training for all our team. We are a family born   in the Andes and we want to work with them and for them. In adition, we   plant a tree for every booking we receive from our customers, so thank   you for suppurting this wonderful project. </p>', '', 'rainbow-mountain', 1, 'Cusco, Vinicunca', 0, 0, 79.00, 1, 'Full day', 2, 1, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"19548823\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=19548823\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 16, 2),
(2, 'Inca Trail Collection', 'This is a tour that requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend making the reservation in advance, once you make your reservation will be confirmed as long as there is availability of space for the date that you select, please make sure to check the availability of spaces for Inca trail 4 days.', 'By booking this tour your are planting 1 tree at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'The 5 days Inca Trail is done by the same route as the classic 4 days, instead, it is done slower, enjoying more time during the walk and visiting places on the route.', '<p>The <strong>5 days&nbsp;Inca&nbsp;Trail</strong> is done by the same route as the   classic 4 days, instead, it is done slower, enjoying more time during   the walk and visiting places on the route.</p> <p>This option is perfect&nbsp;for   families with children&nbsp;or people who want to walk at their own pace and   slowly, this option also allows you to walk out of crowded schedules so   you can enjoy the hike much better.&nbsp;The last night you sleep&nbsp;in a hotel   in&nbsp;<strong>Machu Picchu</strong>&nbsp;Pueblo.</p>', '  <h3>What Our Inca Trail Collection Hike Includes</h3>   <ul>     <li>&nbsp;<strong>Professional Guide</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;We have the best selection of   guides, all graduated from the national university of&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;and grown   up in this region with a deep love and passion for teaching our   culture.&nbsp;They are fun but professional and will make sure you are safe   and happy.</li>     <li>&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Tourist transport.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We use clean and new   vehicles for all our services, with professional drivers that will   guarantee you a safe trip. Our drivers are constantly trained in prudent   driving and customer service.&nbsp;The transport will be from Cusco to   Soraypampa and from Ollantaytambo to Cusco at the end of our trek.</li>     <li>&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>Pick up from the hotel.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Our service includes   pick up from your&nbsp;hotel&nbsp;to start the tour, pick up time will be   confirmed according to the location of your hotel, at the end of the   tour we will also leave you back at your hotel.&nbsp;(Our service does not   include pick up from&nbsp;AIRBNB&nbsp;type houses&nbsp;because many do not have a clear   name or address), in that case we will coordinate a place and time to   pick up.</li>     <li><strong>Snacks</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; beside the breakfast, we will provide you   snacks every morning so that you can take you along the way. We will   also provide snack bags that are made of cloth, we are very careful with   the environment so we try not to take anything plastic to the route and   if we do, we bring it back.</li>     <li>&nbsp;<strong>Train Tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;The train ticket included is the   Inca Rail the Voyager service, however, on the way you can make an Up   Grade to a 360 &deg; train that has windows on the roof to enjoy the   beautiful views on the road.&nbsp;This has an additional cost of $.&nbsp;$&nbsp;65&nbsp;per   person&nbsp;up to Poroy&nbsp;and is subject to availability. Poroy station is 30   minutes out of Cusco, we will still include the transfer to your hotel.</li>     <li><strong>Bus tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; It is 25 minutes from the Town to Machu Picchu and 25 minutes from Machu Picchu to the town.</li>     <li><strong>Inca Trail Entrance Tickets:</strong> We will get the Inca   trail entrance tickets and provide you, this will be given to you in the   beginning of the hike, as well as we will get the entrance for our   crew.</li>     <li><strong>Entrance to Machu Picchu.</strong>&nbsp;We take care of providing   you with the entrance ticket to Machu Picchu and this will be giving to   you on the day of the tour, by your guide.</li>     <li><strong>Porters:</strong>&nbsp;We include a personal porter, who is   responsible for carrying your travel bag with your personal items.&nbsp;There   is no additional fee for this.&nbsp;The night before we will give you your   duffel bag so that it is filled with the things you will need for the   trek.&nbsp;You will not have access to your duffle bag until you arrive at   your campsite at first night.</li>     <li><strong>Hotel:</strong>&nbsp;Alternative&nbsp;excursions end at Machu Picchu   Pueblo.&nbsp;The last night is spent in a hotel in the village, instead of   camping.&nbsp;This 3-star hotel is included in the cost of the trek and is   based on a shared room.&nbsp;If you want to improve your hotel or prefer a   single room, you will have an additional cost.</li>     <li><strong>Camping equipment:</strong>&nbsp;In Peru Private Tours we have   the best equipment.&nbsp;We use a 4 people tent only between 2 people so you   will have more space to put your belongings inside your tent during the   night.&nbsp;You will have a large tent&nbsp;to enjoy your meals as well as chairs   and table.</li>     <li><strong>Food:</strong>&nbsp;5 breakfasts (the last included in the hotel)   4 lunches and 4 dinners, all prepared by our professional walking   chef.&nbsp;Our professional chefs&nbsp;prepare delicious meals that many previous   hikers have commented on.&nbsp;We honor all dietary restrictions.&nbsp;Be sure to   remind your tour guide about any food restrictions at the beginning of   your walk (Breafing time).&nbsp;The food is typically served family   style.&nbsp;You will enjoy breakfast, lunch and dinner every day of the&nbsp;trek,   with a delicious happy hour every afternoon before dinner.&nbsp;You will   also be provided with a snack every morning, so that you can enjoy the   walk.&nbsp;Your last&nbsp;meal with your chef will be&nbsp;breakfast on day four&nbsp;since   lunch and dinner will be at a restaurant.&nbsp;Lunch on the last day&nbsp;(day   05)&nbsp;is not included.</li>     <li><strong>Water:</strong>&nbsp;from your first lunch until your last   breakfast,&nbsp;PPT&nbsp;will provide you with all the necessary water.&nbsp;This water   will be boiled, filtered and then cooled, before distribution.&nbsp;You must   supply your own bottles of water or camelback.&nbsp;We recommend carrying   around 3L.&nbsp;We will fill our waters at every meal.</li>     <li>&nbsp;<strong>First aid:</strong>&nbsp;each of our guides has received   training in first aid from a doctor.&nbsp;We hold mandatory training sessions   every February, to which all the guides must attend.&nbsp;Your tour guide   will always have a first aid kit for basic medical problems (traveler&rsquo;s   diarrhea, cuts, scratches, etc.) and oxygen tank.&nbsp;We will get you out of   the way as quickly and comfortably as possible if necessary, and we   will make sure you go directly to a clinic to receive treatment.</li>     <li>&nbsp;<strong>Extras:</strong>&nbsp;We believe that it is the attention to   small details that differentiates us from other travel companies.&nbsp;Each   hiker receives a small pillow for sleeping, a sponge mats to isolate   (Matra), a backpack covers to protect your belongings during the trek, a   rain poncho and a waterproof plastic bags to put your belongings before   placing them in the duffle bag. We will work hard to create your best   vacations.</li>     <li><strong>Private transfer from Ollantaytambo to Cusco.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;   Upon arrival at the Ollantaytambo train station our staff will be   waiting for you with a van only for our group to transfer you to   your&nbsp;hotel in Cusco or Sacred Valley.</li>     <li>&nbsp;<strong>Permanent Assistance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We want all the activities   you do in our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so you   will always have an&nbsp;assigned&nbsp;personal assistant&nbsp;who will be in constant   communication with you.</li>   </ul>   <h3>What Our Inca Trail Collection Hike Doesn`t Include</h3>   <p>All travelers need a sleeping bag on adventure routes, do not forget   to bring your own.&nbsp;The walking sticks and air mattresses are optional   and serve to provide greater comfort during the walk.&nbsp;If you do not want   to bring any camping gear you can always rent from our office.</p>   <p><strong>Sleeping bag&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $.&nbsp;20 usd per person</strong></p>   <p><strong>Air Matras&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $.&nbsp;20 usd per person</strong></p>   <p><strong>Walking sticks (pair)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $.&nbsp;USD 15 per person</strong></p>   <ul>     <li><strong>headlamps:</strong> it&nbsp;is strongly recommended to bring a   head lamp for the evenings.&nbsp;There will be no lights on the camping sites   and it will be difficult to get to your dining tent or bathroom tent   without one.&nbsp;Hand lanterns are acceptable, if you do not have a head   lamp, but it makes some tasks difficult.</li>     <li><strong>Huayna Picchu</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;Huayna Picchu is the mountain that   is seen behind Machu Picchu in the classic photos, to go up this   mountain you need to buy an additional entrance and it has a cost of   $.&nbsp;35 dollars per person, however,&nbsp;this entrance must be requested at   the time of your reservation and it will be confirmed according to   availability of spaces as they only allow 200 people.</li>     <li><strong>Flights.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;Flying to Cusco can be   complicated.&nbsp;Delays occur frequently especially between October to March   and it is not uncommon for flights to be canceled.&nbsp;Make sure you arrive   in the city at least two days before the start date of your trek to   Machu Picchu.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;is the most reliable airline.&nbsp;Avianca and Peruvian   Airlines&nbsp;are also acceptable companies.&nbsp;You will not return from your   tour on the last day until around 8 pm So make sure your flight is not   the day of the Machu Picchu Tour, rather the next day.</li>     <li><strong>Tips</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Tips are always appreciated and should be   based entirely on your level of satisfaction.&nbsp;Although it may not be   usual for you, it has considerable importance to the people who will   assist you during your trek.</li>     <li><strong>Travel insurance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; To protect your travel   investment, we recommend the purchase&nbsp;a travel insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel   insurance before leaving home is highly recommended and very   easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending on your country of   origin and at different prices according to your time of stay, take some   time to review them and hire the one that best suits you.&nbsp;This is an   excellent way to protect yourself while visiting&nbsp;Peru.</li>   </ul>', '  <h3>Breafing (Previous Information)</h3>   <p>All information sessions are held in our office at 06:00 PM the night   before your trek.&nbsp;If you cannot assist to this talk please contact our   office staff to serve you better.</p>   <h3>Duffle Bags</h3>   <p>You will receive your duffle bag at the information session.&nbsp;These   bags are to put your belongings inside it, these will be carried by the   porters and will be returned to you each evening at the   campsite.&nbsp;However, beside from these bags, you should carry a small   backpack where you will carry everything you need during the trek.</p>   <p>Each duffle bag must have a maximum weight of 7kg.&nbsp;4kg will be for   your clothes and other personal items, the other 3kg will be for our   logistics, such as your sleeping bag and pad, if you have your own   sleeping bag and mat these must be included in the 7 kilos.</p>   <h3>Arrive in Cusco</h3>   <p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline options.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.latam.com/en_us/\">LATAM</a>&nbsp;tends   to be the most expensive, but it has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also   have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU, LC PERU&nbsp;to choose according to your   preference.&nbsp;Expect&nbsp;flight delays or cancellations,&nbsp;due to the   high&nbsp;altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult to land&nbsp;so that on rainy   days you can paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.&nbsp;Bus tours&nbsp;are always available and   although the journey may be long, especially from&nbsp;Lima,&nbsp;Peru buses&nbsp;are   well maintained and are comfortable.&nbsp;This option is recommended if you   come from a city closer to&nbsp;Cusco like Puno or Arequipa.&nbsp;Buses from Lima   will take around 20 hours to arrive to Cusco.</p>   <h3>Pick Up from The Hotels.</h3>   <p>We pick up all our clients from the hotel for all tours.&nbsp;While your   hotel is in the center of the city of Cusco, we will coordinate this   pick up&nbsp;with the&nbsp;guide at the information session.&nbsp;Pick-up&nbsp;times&nbsp;may   vary between 20 and 30&nbsp;minutes depending on traffic conditions and   hotel&nbsp;locations.</p>   <p>Cusco is an ancient city with cobblestone streets and very narrow   corridors.&nbsp;Very small hotels and Air BNBs are often located on streets   that cars cannot pass through.&nbsp;They are also usually located on the side   of the hill, with long and steep climbs to the property, difficult to   maneuver with luggage.&nbsp;We recommend that you do not&nbsp;stay in one of these   places and try to find places where there is easy access to carry your   bags.</p>   <h3>Leaving Machu Picchu requires a lot of logistics,&nbsp;but&nbsp;everything&nbsp;is&nbsp;included in your journey.</h3>   <p>From Machu Picchu&nbsp;Ruins&nbsp;to&nbsp;Machu Picchu Pueblo, you&nbsp;will take a   25-minute bus.&nbsp;The&nbsp;buses are in order of arrival and you can take any of   those in turn.</p>   <p>From Machu Picchu Pueblo,&nbsp;you will take a&nbsp;train&nbsp;to&nbsp;Ollantaytambo or   Poroy&nbsp;station.&nbsp;Your guide will give you your train tickets.&nbsp;Make sure   you get to the platform 30 minutes ahead of time.</p>   <ul>     <li><strong>The train from Aguas Calientes to Ollantaytambo is 2 hours.</strong></li>     <li><strong>The train from Aguas Calientes to Poroy is 3.5 hours.</strong></li>   </ul>   <p>Once you arrive at the train station, look&nbsp;for our staff with a PPT sign.&nbsp;He&nbsp;will take you to the Plaza San Francisco, Cusco.</p>   <ul>     <li><strong>The trip on&nbsp;the van&nbsp;from Ollantaytambo to Plaza de San Francisco is 2 hours</strong></li>     <li><strong>Travel by&nbsp;van&nbsp;from Poroy to&nbsp;San Francisco Plaza is&nbsp;30 minutes</strong></li>   </ul>   <p>Once you arrive at the Plaza San Francisco&nbsp;our staff will be waiting   for you to separate you and send in pre-paid taxis to your respective   hotels.</p>   <h3>Entrance fees to Machu Picchu</h3>   <p>Machu Picchu now has two&nbsp;hours&nbsp;to visit: morning or afternoon.&nbsp;Your   ticket will be&nbsp;for a single&nbsp;entry,&nbsp;in the morning, once your time is   done, the&nbsp;guards will ask&nbsp;you&nbsp;to&nbsp;leave.</p>   <p><strong>Morning turn: 6AM &ndash; 12PM</strong></p>   <p><strong>Afternoon turn: 12PM &ndash; 5:30 PM</strong></p>   <p><strong>NOTE:</strong>&nbsp;If you have tickets to&nbsp;climb to Huayna Picchu   or Machu Picchu Mountain, you will have additional time until 2:30   PM.&nbsp;And you can re-enter for a single time as long as it is within the   time of re-entry (05 hours from the first entry)</p>   <p>If you want&nbsp;to&nbsp;spend all day at Machu Picchu, we can add a ticket&nbsp;for   the&nbsp;afternoon&nbsp;group&nbsp;to your reservation for $ 50 per person.</p>   <h3>Huayna Picchu / Machu Picchu Mountain</h3>   <p>Machu Picchu is more beautiful when viewed from above, so it is very   popular to hike one of the mountains next to the ruins after your guided   tour.</p>   <p>Huayna Picchu is the most popular and must be booked in advance &hellip; it   sells very fast.&nbsp;This hike takes approximately&nbsp;50&nbsp;minutes to the top   and&nbsp;40&nbsp;minutes downhill to the bottom.&nbsp;There are 2 schedules or groups   to enter this mountain.&nbsp;The first group&nbsp;is 8-p am and&nbsp;the second&nbsp;is 10   am to 11 am.&nbsp;Again, this refers to when you can start your hike and   normally we reserve the second&nbsp;option&nbsp;so you can first enjoy your tour   with your guide&nbsp;in Machu Picchu.&nbsp;This walk will be&nbsp;done&nbsp;on your own, but   your guide will show you where to start.</p>   <p>The Machu Picchu mountain is a little longer and less popular.&nbsp;It   takes&nbsp;2&nbsp;hours to reach the top&nbsp;and 1.5&nbsp;hours to reach the bottom.&nbsp;There   are also 2 visiting hours: from 7-8 am and from 9 am to 10 am and we   usually buy&nbsp;for the second group.</p>   <h3>Health Concerns</h3>   <p>It is important that you be honest with your guide about any health   problems you may suffer.&nbsp;Although the guides are not medical   professionals, they are trained in first aid.&nbsp;We also work with a clinic   in Cusco that can help our team.</p>   <p>You are responsible for evaluating if a trek is suitable for you.&nbsp;You   should consult your doctor to confirm your physical condition to travel   and participate in any planned activity.&nbsp;You should seek advice from   your doctor about vaccinations and medical precautions.&nbsp;Peru Private   Tours will&nbsp;not provide medical advice.&nbsp;It is your responsibility to   assess the risks and requirements of each aspect of the Tour based on   your own circumstances, limitations, fitness level and medical   requirements.</p>   <p>If during the trek you get sick of extreme altitude or any other   illness that not allows you to continuing with the journey, but you want   to visit Machu Picchu by train, we will work with you to coordinate   this trip.&nbsp;This will be a new trip and may involve additional costs.&nbsp;We   will use as much of the logistics purchased from the original route to   keep rates low.</p>   <p>If you experience problems while walking and cannot continue, a   porter will escort you to the nearest road and wait while a car comes to   pick you up and take you to the nearest health clinic.</p>   <h3>Group trips</h3>   <p>Group tours are made up of different types of people, with different   walking skills and ages.&nbsp;By accepting a group trip, you understand that   some people may be slower or faster than you.&nbsp;Everyone can make their   own pace for the walk, the guide will work through the group to spend   time with everyone.&nbsp;Groups can request some modifications to the tour   and&nbsp;the&nbsp;guide will work with everyone to make the best decision for the   group.</p>   <h3>Strikes</h3>   <p>Unfortunately, strikes are very common in Peru and can cause many   interruptions in our Tours.&nbsp;Roads are often blocked, trains stopped.&nbsp;We   will do everything possible to operate your Tour, even before the&nbsp;start   date.&nbsp;Some tours may&nbsp;be canceled under these circumstances.&nbsp;Our   Operations Department will coordinate with you in this situation.&nbsp;Your   safety is always our main concern and will determine how we decide.</p>   <h3>Lost Items</h3>   <p>You are responsible for your personal items throughout the Tour.&nbsp;Be   diligent about where&nbsp;you&nbsp;leave your stuff and remember&nbsp;to&nbsp;remove all   items from our vans,&nbsp;tents, restaurant, etc.&nbsp;Do not leave anything   involuntary while walking.&nbsp;Other hikers or teams can pick it up without   knowing to whom it belongs.</p>   <h3>Weather</h3>   <p>The climate in Cusco and Machu Picchu&nbsp;is unpredictable.&nbsp;In general,   the dry season in&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is from April to October, but this does not   prevent the rain from falling in June or the sun coming out in December,   just prepare for any weather condition.&nbsp;No matter which month you take   the hike or excursion, or which tour you are on, make sure you have   adequate clothing that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho and   waterproof gloves.</p>   <p>Also be prepared for&nbsp;four seasons in a day.&nbsp;Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a warm jacket.</p>   <h3>Altitude sickness</h3>   <p>As soon as the&nbsp;people reserve the trip to&nbsp;Peru, specifically   to&nbsp;Cusco, they begin to wonder about&nbsp;altitude sickness.&nbsp;High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.&nbsp;For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least&nbsp;amount of oxygen in the air.</p>   <p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p>   <p>For farther info about altitude sicknes <a href=\"http://www.pptoursperu.com/altitud-sickness-in-cusco/\">CLIC HERE</a></p>   <h3>Travel insurance</h3>   <p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying&nbsp;travel   insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending   on your country of origin and at different prices&nbsp;according to your time   of stay, take some time to review them and hire the one that best suits   you.&nbsp;This is an excellent way to&nbsp;protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>   <h3>Community</h3>   <p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our   community. We are working&nbsp;directly with the villages to help them meet   the needs of their families.&nbsp;We support the children of the villages by   giving them&nbsp;school supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and clothes.</p>   <p>We buy all our food from farmers and local markets and serve the   freshest ingredients.&nbsp;We offer&nbsp;constant training&nbsp;for all our team:   guides, porters, chefs and drivers.&nbsp;We are a family born in the Andes   and we want to work with them and for them.&nbsp;That is why once&nbsp;a year we   bring our porters and their families to&nbsp;Machu&nbsp;Picchu.&nbsp;We want our team   to know the world wonder, since they work tirelessly at the doors of   this place without ever visiting it and&nbsp;showing them this place is our   greatest honor.</p>', '', 'inca-trail-collection', 1, '', 0, 0, 89.00, 1, '5 days 4 nights', 2, 0, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"40900079\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=40900079\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 7, 3),
(3, 'Huchuy Qosqo with Machu Picchu', 'This is a tour that requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend making the reservation in advance, once you make your reservation will be confirmed as long as there is availability of space for the date that you select, please make sure to check the availability of spaces for Inca trail 4 days', 'By booking this tour your are planting 1 tree at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'It is an excellent option of trekking for those who want outdoor activities but do not have much time, this fantastic option of 2 days combined with Machu Picchu is something unique and wonderful', '<p>Huchuy Qosqo Trek&nbsp;It is an excellent option of trekking   for those who want outdoor activities but do not have much time, this   fantastic option of 2 days combined with Machu Picchu is something   unique and wonderful, in the tour we will enjoy beautiful views of   hills, valleys, lagoons, flora and fauna, canyons and the archaeological   center of&nbsp;Huchuy Qosqo.</p> <p>In addition, it is not an   overcrowded route so you can enjoy your walk being the only one in the   mountains. Combining this walk with the visit to Machu Picchu is a   fantastic alternative.</p>', '<h2>What our Machu Picchu Hikes Includes</h2> <ul>   <li><strong>Professional Guide</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;We have the best selection of   guides, all graduated from the national university of&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;and grown up   in this region with a deep love and passion for teaching their   culture.&nbsp;They are fun but professional and will make sure you are safe   and happy.</li>   <li><strong>Tourist transport.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We use clean and new vehicles   for all our services, with professional drivers that will guarantee you a   safe trip. Our drivers are constantly trained in prudent driving and   customer service.&nbsp;The transport will be from Cusco to Soraypampa and   from Ollantaytambo to Cusco at the end of our tour.</li>   <li><strong>Pick up from the hotel.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Our service includes   picking up your&nbsp;hotel&nbsp;to start the tour, pick up time will be confirmed   according to the location of your hotel, at the end of the tour we will   also leave you back at your hotel.&nbsp;(Our service does not include pick up   from&nbsp;AIRBNB&nbsp;type houses&nbsp;because many do not have a clear name or   address), in that case we will coordinate a place and time to pick up.</li>   <li><strong>Meals.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;1 breakfast (the second day), 02 lunches   and 01 dinners all prepared by our professional chef. The last day   dinner is not included.&nbsp;We honor all dietary restrictions. Be sure to   remind your tour guide of any food restrictions at the beginning of your   walk. The food is typically served family style. You will enjoy   breakfast, lunch and dinner every day of the walk, along with an hour of   tea and snacks. You will also be provided with a snack every morning,   so that you can enjoy the walk.</li>   <li>&nbsp;<strong>Train Tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;The train ticket included on the   service is&nbsp;on Inca Rail the Voyager, however,&nbsp;you can make an Up Grade   to&nbsp;360 &ordm;&nbsp;that has windows on the roof to enjoy the beautiful views on   the road.&nbsp;This has a cost addition&nbsp;to $.&nbsp;69 dollars per person, only the   one-way.</li>   <li><strong>Bus tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; It is 25 minutes from the Town to Machu Picchu and 25 minutes from Machu Picchu to the town.</li>   <li><strong>Entrance to Machu Picchu.</strong>&nbsp;We take care of providing   you with the entrance ticket to Machu Picchu and this will be delivered   to you on the day of the tour, by your guide.</li>   <li><strong>Porters:</strong>&nbsp;We include a personal porter, who is   responsible for carrying your travel bag with your personal items.&nbsp;There   is no additional fee for this.&nbsp;The night before the start of the walk   we will give you your duffel bag to fill with the things you will need   for the walk.&nbsp;You will not have access to your duffle bag until you   arrive at your campsite at night of the first day.</li>   <li>&nbsp;<strong>Camping equipment:</strong>&nbsp;In Peru Private Tours we have   the best equipment.&nbsp;We use a tent for 4 people only between 2 people so   you will have more space to put your belongings inside your tent during   the night.&nbsp;You will have a large dining tent to enjoy your meals as well   as chairs and table.</li>   <li><strong>Water:</strong>&nbsp;from your first lunch until your last   breakfast, PPT will provide you with all the necessary water.&nbsp;This water   will be boiled, filtered and then cooled, before distribution.&nbsp;You must   supply your own bottles of water or camelback.&nbsp;We recommend carrying   around 3L.&nbsp;We will fill our waters at every meal.</li>   <li><strong>First aid:</strong>&nbsp;each of our guides has received training   in first aid from a doctor. We hold mandatory training sessions every   February, to which all the guides must attend. Your tour guide will   always have a first aid kit for basic medical problems (traveler&rsquo;s   diarrhea, cuts, scratches, etc.) and oxygen. We will get you out of the   way as quickly and comfortably as possible, if necessary, and we will   make sure you go directly to a clinic to receive treatment.</li>   <li>&nbsp;<strong>Extras:</strong>&nbsp;We believe that it is the attention to   small details that differentiates us from other travel companies.&nbsp;Each   hiker receives a small pillow to sleep, a sponge mattress to isolate   (Matra), a backpack covers to protect your belongings during the walk, a   rain poncho, a cloth bag to carry your snacks and a waterproof bag to   put your belongings before placing them in the duffle bag.&nbsp;We will work   hard to create your best vacations.</li>   <li><strong>Private</strong> <strong>transfer from Ollantaytambo to Cusco.&nbsp;</strong>&ndash;   Upon arrival at the Ollantaytambo train station our staff will be   waiting for you with a van only for our group to transfer you back to   your&nbsp;hotel in Cusco&nbsp;or Sacred Valley.</li>   <li><strong>Permanent Assistance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We want all the activities   you do in our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so you   will always have an&nbsp;assigned&nbsp;personal assistant&nbsp;who will be in constant   communication with you.</li> </ul> <h3>What Our Machu Picchu Hikes Doesn`t Include.</h3> <p>All travelers need a sleeping bag on the adventure routes, do not   forget to bring your own.&nbsp;The walking sticks and air mattresses are   optional and serve to provide greater comfort during the walk.&nbsp;If you do   not want to bring any camping gear you can always rent from our office.</p> <p><strong>Sleeping bag or sleeping: $.&nbsp;10&nbsp;usd per person&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p> <p><strong>Air Matras: $.&nbsp;10&nbsp;usd per person&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p> <p><strong>Walking sticks (01 pair): $.&nbsp;8&nbsp;usd per person&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p> <ul>   <li><strong>Huayna Picchu or Machu Picchu Mountain.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;On this   hike we will visit Machu Picchu in the afternoon, which is why there is   no option to visit Huayna Picchu or Machu Picchu Mountain, unless you   want to stay an extra night in Machu Picchu Pueblo and visit the next   day, however, this can generate extra hotel costs and entrance tickets.</li>   <li><strong>Flights.</strong> &ndash;&nbsp;Flying to Cusco can be complicated.   Delays occur frequently especially between October to March and it is   not uncommon for flights to be canceled. Make sure you arrive in the   city at least two days before the start date of your Tour to Machu   Picchu.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;is the most   reliable airline.&nbsp;Avianca and Peruvian Airlines&nbsp;are also acceptable   companies. You will not return from your tour on the last day until   around 22 pm So make sure your flight is not the day of the Machu Picchu   Tour, rather the next day.</li>   <li><strong>Tips</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Tips are always appreciated and should be   based entirely on your level of satisfaction.&nbsp;Although it may not be   usual for you, it has considerable importance for the people who will   assist you during your trips.</li>   <li><strong>Travel insurance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; To protect your travel   investment, we recommend to purchase&nbsp;a travel insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel   insurance before leaving home is highly recommended and very easy.&nbsp;There   are many insurance companies depending on your country of origin and at   different prices according to your time of stay, take some time to   review them and hire the one that best suits you.&nbsp;This is an excellent   way to protect yourself while visiting&nbsp;Peru.</li> </ul>', '<h3>Breafing (Previous Information)</h3>   <p>All information sessions are held in our office at 06:00 PM the night   before your trek.&nbsp;If you cannot assist to this talk please contact our   office staff to serve you better.</p>   <h3>Arriving to Cusco</h3>   <p>The airport in Cusco&nbsp;is currently&nbsp;quite small and only for domestic   flights, so all international travelers by plane must disembark   in&nbsp;Lima&nbsp;and go through Customs.&nbsp;Even if your flight to&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is the same   day by the same airline, you must pick up your bags in Lima and then   register them again.</p>   <p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline   options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it   has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU,   LC PERU&nbsp;to choose according to your preference.&nbsp;Expect&nbsp;flight delays or   cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult   to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.&nbsp;Bus   tours&nbsp;are always available and although the journey may be long,   especially from&nbsp;Lima,&nbsp;Peru buses&nbsp;are well maintained and are   comfortable.&nbsp;This option is recommended if you come from a city closer   to&nbsp;Cusco like Puno or Arequipa.&nbsp;Buses from Lima will take around 20   hours to arrive to Cusco.</p>   <h3>Pick Up from The Hotels.</h3>   <p>We pick up all our clients from the hotel for all tours.&nbsp;While your   hotel is in the center of the city of Cusco, we will coordinate this   pick up&nbsp;with the&nbsp;guide at the information session.&nbsp;Pick-up&nbsp;times&nbsp;may   vary between 20 and 30&nbsp;minutes depending on traffic conditions and   hotel&nbsp;locations.</p>   <p>Cusco is an ancient city with cobblestone streets and very narrow   corridors.&nbsp;Very small hotels and Air BNBs are often located on streets   that cars cannot pass through.&nbsp;They are also usually located on the side   of the hill, with long and steep climbs to the property, difficult to   maneuver with luggage.&nbsp;We recommend that you do not&nbsp;stay in one of these   places and try to find places where there is easy access to carry your   bags.</p>   <h3>Health Concerns</h3>   <p>It is important that you be honest with your guide about any health problems you may suffer.</p>   <p>You should seek advice from your doctor about vaccinations and   medical precautions.&nbsp;Peru Private Tours will&nbsp;not provide medical   advice.&nbsp;It is your responsibility to assess the risks and requirements   of each aspect of the Tour based on your own circumstances, limitations,   fitness level and medical requirements.</p>   <p>If during the trek you get sick of extreme altitude or any other   illness that not allows you to continuing with the journey, but you want   to visit Machu Picchu by train, we will work with you to coordinate   this trip.&nbsp;This will be a new trip and may involve additional costs.&nbsp;We   will use as much of the logistics purchased from the original route to   keep rates low.</p>   <p>If you experience problems while walking and cannot continue, a   porter will escort you to the nearest road and wait while a car comes to   pick you up and take you to the nearest health clinic.</p>   <h3>Group trips</h3>   <p>Group tours are made up of different types of people, with different   walking skills and ages.&nbsp;By accepting a group trip, you understand that   some people may be slower or faster than you.&nbsp;Everyone can make their   own pace for the walk, the guide will work through the group to spend   time with everyone.&nbsp;Groups can request some modifications to the tour   and&nbsp;the&nbsp;guide will work with everyone to make the best decision for the   group.</p>   <h3>Strikes</h3>   <p>Unfortunately, strikes are very common in Peru and can cause many   interruptions in our Tours.&nbsp;Roads are often blocked, trains stopped.&nbsp;We   will do everything possible to operate your Tour, even before the&nbsp;start   date.&nbsp;Some tours may&nbsp;be canceled under these circumstances.&nbsp;Our   Operations Department will coordinate with you in this situation.&nbsp;Your   safety is always our main concern and will determine how we decide.</p>   <h3>Lost Items</h3>   <p>You are responsible for your personal items throughout the Tour.&nbsp;Be   diligent about where&nbsp;you&nbsp;leave your stuff and remember&nbsp;to&nbsp;remove all   items from our vans,&nbsp;tents, restaurant, etc.&nbsp;Do not leave anything   involuntary while walking.&nbsp;Other hikers or teams can pick it up without   knowing to whom it belongs.</p>   <h3>Weather</h3>   <p>The climate in Cusco and Machu Picchu&nbsp;is unpredictable.&nbsp;In general,   the dry season in&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is from April to October, but this does not   prevent the rain from falling in June or the sun coming out in December,   just prepare for any weather condition.&nbsp;No matter which month you take   the hike or excursion, or which tour you are on, make sure you have   adequate clothing that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho and   waterproof gloves.</p>   <p>Also be prepared for&nbsp;four seasons in a day.&nbsp;Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a warm jacket.</p>   <h3>Altitude sickness</h3>   <p>As soon as the&nbsp;people reserve the trip to&nbsp;Peru, specifically   to&nbsp;Cusco, they begin to wonder about&nbsp;altitude sickness.&nbsp;High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.&nbsp;For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least&nbsp;amount of oxygen in the air.</p>   <p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p>   <p>for farther info about altitude sickness<a href=\"http://www.pptoursperu.com/altitud-sickness-in-cusco/\" target=\"_blank\"> CLIC HERE</a></p>   <h3>Travel insurance</h3>   <p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying&nbsp;travel   insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending   on your country of origin and at different prices&nbsp;according to your time   of stay, take some time to review them and hire the one that best suits   you.&nbsp;This is an excellent way to&nbsp;protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>', '', 'huchuy-qosqo-machu-picchu', 2, '', 0, 0, 59.00, 1, '2 days / 1 night', 3, 0, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"43656769\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=43656769\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 6, 4);
INSERT INTO `ProgramaPPT` (`Identificador`, `NombreIngles`, `MensajeIngles`, `MensajeSocialIngles`, `IntroduccionIngles`, `DescripcionIngles`, `IncluyeIngles`, `MasInformacionIngles`, `FAQIngles`, `Enlace`, `IdDestino`, `DestinosIngles`, `IdActividad`, `IdTipo`, `Precio`, `Duracion`, `DuracionIngles`, `Dificultad`, `EsPortada`, `OrdenPortada`, `CodigoWeTravel`, `CantidadImagenes`, `IdCategoria`) VALUES
(4, 'Sacred Valley Tour', 'Join this Sacred Valley tour, one of the most impressive and most popular tours in Cusco and all over Peru, On the Sacred Valley Tour you will discover beautiful nature, pictures of landscapes and great archeological sites from the time of the Incas.', 'By booking this tour your are planting 1 tree at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'Enjoy this wonderful Sacred Valley Tour where we will visit unique and wonderful places, get ready for this full day excursion to the magical valley of the Incas where you can take a selfie with a Lama', '<p>Enjoy this wonderful <strong>Sacred Valley</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Tour</strong> where we will visit unique and wonderful places, get ready for this full day excursion to&nbsp;the magical&nbsp;<strong>valley of the Incas</strong>&nbsp;where you can take a selfie with a Lama, enjoy the ruins of&nbsp;<strong>Pisac</strong>&nbsp;that are made in a Condor shape<strong>,</strong>&nbsp;the ruins of&nbsp;<strong>Ollantaytambo</strong>&nbsp;which is built in the shape of&nbsp;<strong>a Lama</strong>&nbsp;and the ruins of&nbsp;<strong>Chinchero</strong>&nbsp;with its colonial temple.</p> <p>Also, get ready to enjoy a delicious buffet lunch with organic Andean products in the heart of&nbsp;<strong>the Sacred Valley</strong>&nbsp;(Urubamba).</p>', '  <h3>What our sacred valley tour includes</h3>   <ul>     <li><strong>Professional</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Guide</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;We have the   best selection of guides, all graduates of the national university of   Cusco and grown up in this region with a deep love and passion for   teaching their culture.&nbsp;They are fun but professional and will make sure   you are safe and happy.</li>     <li><strong>Tourist transport.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We use clean and new vehicles   for all our services, with professional drivers that guarantee a safe   trip. Our drivers are constantly trained in prudent driving and customer   service.</li>     <li><strong>Pick up from the hotel.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Our service includes pick   up from your hotel to start the tour, pick up time will be confirmed   according to the location of your hotel, at the end of the tour we will   also leave you back at your hotel.&nbsp;(Our service does not include AIRBNB   house pickups because many of them do not have a clear name or address).</li>     <li><strong>Permanent Assistance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We want you doing all the   activities at our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so   you will always have an assigned personal assistant who will be in   constant communication with you and will be there at the beginning and   end of every tour.</li>   </ul>   <h3>what the sacred valley tour does not include</h3>   <ul>     <li><strong>Buffet lunch.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; After our tour in&nbsp;<strong>Pisac,</strong> the next stop will be in&nbsp;<strong>Urubamba,</strong> in this place we will have a delicious buffet lunch with organic Andean products.</li>     <li><strong>Entrance tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;Many of the&nbsp;<strong>archaeological sites of Cusco</strong>&nbsp;<strong>and Sacred Valley</strong>&nbsp;accept   the&nbsp;Tourist&nbsp;Ticket&nbsp;of Cusco (BTC)&nbsp;that you can acquire in the first   place of visit, we will help you in the purchase, just be sure to take   money in cash and in soles.</li>   </ul>   <h4><strong>Tickets you must buy.</strong></h4>   <table width=\"100%\" border=\"1px\">     <tbody>       <tr>         <td><strong>Tickets</strong></td>         <td><strong>Children&nbsp;up to 09 years and 11 months</strong></td>         <td><strong>Adults</strong></td>       </tr>       <tr>         <td>BTC For the&nbsp;ruins</td>         <td>They do not pay</td>         <td>70 soles&nbsp;valid&nbsp;for this tour.</td>       </tr>     </tbody>   </table>   <h4><strong>Buffet</strong>&nbsp;<strong>lunch places</strong>.</h4>   <table width=\"100%\" border=\"1px\">     <tbody>       <tr>         <td>Restaurant</td>         <td>Children&nbsp;up to 04 years</td>         <td>Adults</td>       </tr>       <tr>         <td><a href=\"https://www.tripadvisor.com.pe/Restaurant_Review-g294321-d3731368-Reviews-Inka_s_House_Valle-Urubamba_Sacred_Valley_Cusco_Region.html\">Incas&nbsp;House</a></td>         <td>They do not pay</td>         <td>$ 16 per person</td>       </tr>       <tr>         <td><a href=\"https://www.tripadvisor.com.pe/Restaurant_Review-g294314-d5113491-Reviews-El_Maizal_Restaurant_Buffet-Cusco_Cusco_Region.html\">Maizal</a></td>         <td>They do not pay</td>         <td>$ 15 per person</td>       </tr>       <tr>         <td><a href=\"https://www.tripadvisor.com.pe/Restaurant_Review-g294321-d3240333-Reviews-Tunupa_Valle_Sagrado-Urubamba_Sacred_Valley_Cusco_Region.html\">Tunupa</a></td>         <td>They do not pay</td>         <td>$ 19 per person</td>       </tr>       <tr>         <td><a href=\"https://www.munarestaurante.com/\">Mu&ntilde;a</a></td>         <td>They do not pay</td>         <td>$ 19 per person</td>       </tr>       <tr>         <td><a href=\"http://haciendapukapunku.com/\">Puka&nbsp;punku</a></td>         <td>They do not pay</td>         <td>$ 20 per person</td>       </tr>     </tbody>   </table>', '<h2>Useful information</h2> <h3>Altitude sickness</h3> <p>As soon as the&nbsp;people reserve the trip to&nbsp;Peru, specifically   to&nbsp;Cusco, they begin to wonder about&nbsp;altitude sickness.&nbsp;High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.&nbsp;For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least&nbsp;amount of oxygen in the air.</p> <p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p> <p>For farther info about altitude sickness, check out aour blog <a href=\"http://www.pptoursperu.com/altitud-sickness-in-cusco/\" target=\"_blank\">HERE</a></p> <h3>Weather</h3> <p>The weather in the Sacred Valley Tour. The dry season in&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is   from April through October, but this does not prevent the rain from   falling in June or the sun coming out in December, just be prepared&nbsp;for   any weather.&nbsp;No matter which month you take the hike&nbsp;or excursion, or   which tour you are on, make sure you have&nbsp;adequate&nbsp;clothing&nbsp;that   includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho and waterproof gloves.</p> <p>Also be prepared for&nbsp;four seasons in a day.&nbsp;Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a&nbsp;warm jacket.</p> <h3>Arriving to Cusco</h3> <p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU to choose according to your preference.&nbsp;Expect&nbsp;flight delays or   cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult   to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.&nbsp;Bus   tours&nbsp;are always available and although the journey may be long,   especially from&nbsp;Lima,&nbsp;Peru buses&nbsp;are well maintained and are   comfortable.&nbsp;This option is recommended if you come from a city closer   to&nbsp;Cusco like Puno or Arequipa.&nbsp;Buses from Lima will take around 20   hours to arrive to Cusco.</p> <h3>Exchange rate</h3> <p>If you come to visit&nbsp;Peru,&nbsp;try to exchange your local currency for   dollars. However, if you are coming directly to&nbsp;Cusco,&nbsp;there are many   money exchange houses at Sol. Avenue where you can buy the local   currency more safely.</p> <p>Check out our article about money exchage HERE</p> <h3>Travel insurance</h3> <p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying&nbsp;travel   insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending   on your country of origin and at different prices&nbsp;according to your time   of stay, take some time to review them and hire the one that best suits   you.&nbsp;This is an excellent way to&nbsp;protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p> <h3>Community</h3> <p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our   community.&nbsp;This is&nbsp;the&nbsp;main&nbsp;objective&nbsp;for our company.&nbsp;We are   working&nbsp;directly with the villages to help them meet the needs of their   families.&nbsp;We support the children of the villages by giving them&nbsp;school   supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and clothes.</p>', '', 'sacred-valley-tour', 0, 'Cusco & Machu Picchu', 0, 0, 99.00, 0, 'Full day', 1, 0, 1, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"78721574\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=78721574\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 6, 2),
(5, 'Salt Mines + Machu Picchu', 'Salt Mines + Machu Picchu; Full day\n\nThis tour requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend to do your reservation in advance, once you book, it will be confirmed as long as there is spaces available for selected date, please check Machu Picchu access availability.', 'By booking this tour you are planting 1 tree at high andean communities', 'This is a perfect combination for a day tour, we visit the Salt Mines of Maras in the morning,', '<p>This is a perfect combination for a day tour, we visit the&nbsp;Salt Mines of   Maras in the morning, with a short stop at a traditional chicheria in   the sacred valley where you will learn all about the process of making   the traditional Chicha de Jora.</p> <p>Doing the Machu Picchu tour in the   afternoon is the best option since it is not crowded like in the morning   and the weather is always better in the afternoon than in the morning,   you will have the world wonder almost empty during your tour.</p>', '  <h3>What our Day tour to Machu Picchu Includes</h3>   <ul>     <li><strong>Professional Guide</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;We have the best selection of   guides, all graduated from the national university of&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;and grown up   in this region with a deep love and passion for teaching their   culture.&nbsp;They are fun but professional and will make sure you are safe   and happy.</li>     <li><strong>Tourist transport.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We use clean and new vehicles   for all our services, with professional drivers that will guarantee you a   safe trip. Our drivers are constantly trained in prudent driving and   customer service.</li>     <li><strong>Pick up from the hotel</strong>.&nbsp;&ndash; Our service includes   picking up your&nbsp;hotel&nbsp;to start the tour, pick up time will be confirmed   according to the location of your hotel, at the end of the tour we will   also leave you back at your hotel.&nbsp;(Our&nbsp;service does not include pick up   of&nbsp;AIRBNB&nbsp;type houses&nbsp;because many do not have a clear name or   address), in that case we will coordinate a place and time to pick up.</li>     <li><strong>Meals.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; The lunch that we include is in one of the best restaurants in Machu Picchu Pueblo and it will be a well varied buffet lunch.</li>     <li><strong>Train Tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;The train ticket included is the   Inca Rail the Voyager service, however,&nbsp;but if you prefer you can make   an Up Grade to a 360 &deg; train that has windows on the roof to enjoy the   beautiful views on the road.&nbsp;This has an additional cost of $.&nbsp;$ 49 per   person and is subject to availability. The Up Grade can be done only for   one way (Ollantaytambo to Machu Picchu)</li>     <li><strong>Bus tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; It is 25 minutes from the Town to Machu Picchu and 25 minutes from Machu Picchu to the town.</li>     <li><strong>Entrance to Machu Picchu.</strong>&nbsp;We take care of providing   you with the entrance ticket to Machu Picchu and this will be giving to   you on the day of the tour, by your guide.</li>     <li><strong>Private transfer from Ollantaytambo</strong> to Cusco.&nbsp;&ndash;   Upon arrival at the Ollantaytambo train station our staff will be   waiting for you with a vehicle only for our group to transfer you to   your&nbsp;hotel in Cusco&nbsp;or Sacred Valley.</li>     <li>&nbsp;<strong>Permanent Assistance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We want all the activities   you do in our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so you   will always have an&nbsp;assigned&nbsp;personal assistant&nbsp;who will be in constant   communication with you.</li>   </ul>   <h3>What our day tour to machu picchu does not include</h3>   <ul>     <li><strong>Dinner.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Dinner at Machu Picchu Pueblo is not   included, after the tour ends, you will have about 30 minutes in the   town, if you want you can have an early dinner or if you wish you can do   it on your arrival in Cusco, although we will arrive in Cusco by   averaging the 22:30 pm.</li>     <li>&nbsp;<strong>Huayna Picchu</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;For the same itinerary of this   tour, it is not possible to include the climb to Huayna Picchu or Machu   Picchu Mountain, if you want to do any of these hikes, ask your travel   agent for a program that best suits to what you want.</li>     <li><strong>Tips</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;to be based entirely on your&nbsp;level   of&nbsp;satisfaction.&nbsp;Although it may not be usual for you, it has   considerable importance to the people who will assist you during your   trips.</li>   </ul>', '<h3>Altitude sickness</h3> <p>As soon as the&nbsp;people reserve the trip to&nbsp;Peru, specifically   to&nbsp;Cusco, they begin to wonder about&nbsp;altitude sickness.&nbsp;High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.&nbsp;For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least&nbsp;amount of oxygen in the air.</p> <p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p> <p>To read more about altitude sickness clic <a href=\"http://www.pptoursperu.com/en/altitud-sickness/\" target=\"_blank\">HERE</a></p> <h3>Weather</h3> <p>The weather in Cusco&nbsp;it&rsquo;s unpredictable.&nbsp;In general, the dry season   in&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is from April through October, but this does not prevent the   rain from falling in June or the sun coming out in December, just be   prepared&nbsp;for any weather.&nbsp;No matter which month you take the hike&nbsp;or   excursion, or which tour you are on, make sure you   have&nbsp;adequate&nbsp;clothing&nbsp;that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho   and waterproof gloves.</p> <p>Also be prepared&nbsp;for&nbsp;4 seasons in a day.&nbsp;Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a&nbsp;warm jacket.</p> <h3>Arriving to Cusco</h3> <p>The airport in Cusco&nbsp;is currently&nbsp;quite small and only for domestic   flights, so all international travelers by plane must disembark   in&nbsp;Lima&nbsp;and go through Customs.&nbsp;Even if your flight to&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is the same   day by the same airline, you must pick up your bags in Lima and then   register them again.</p> <p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU,   LC PERU&nbsp;to choose according to your preference.&nbsp;Expect&nbsp;flight delays or   cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult   to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.</p> <h3>Travel insurance</h3> <p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying&nbsp;travel   insurance. There are many insurance companies depending on your country   of origin and at different prices&nbsp;according to your time of stay, take   some time to review them and hire the one that best suits you.&nbsp;This is   an excellent way to&nbsp;protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>', '', 'salt-mines-machu-picchu', 0, 'Amazon & Jungle', 0, 0, 109.00, 0, 'Full day', 1, 0, 2, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"40569550\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=40569550\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 6, 2),
(6, 'Short Inca Trail to Machu Picchu With Hotel', 'This tour requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend to book it in advance, your reservation will be confirmed as long as there is spaces available for the date that you selected, please make sure to check the availability', 'By booking this tour your are planting 2 trees at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'A fantastic option for those who do not have much time to do the 4 or 5 days or who do not have the physical condition to support a multi-day trek through the mountains', '<p>The&nbsp;<strong>short 2-days</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Inca Trail&nbsp;</strong>is a   fantastic option for those who do not have much time to do the 4 or 5   days or who do not have the physical condition to support a multi-day   trek through the mountains.&nbsp;This option is also very good for families   with small children who wish to experience a walk along the Inca   Trail.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Along the route there are beautiful views of mountains and   valleys, Machu Picchu is entered by the same place as the walkers of 4   or 5 days but with the advantage of visiting Machu Picchu twice.</p>', '  <h3>What our Short Inca Trail Includes:</h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Professional Guide</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;We have the best selection of   guides, all graduated from the national university of&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;and grown up   in this region with a deep love and passion for teaching our   culture.&nbsp;They are fun but professional and will make sure you are safe   and happy.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tourist transport.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We use clean and new vehicles   for all our services, with professional drivers that will guarantee you a   safe trip. Our drivers are constantly trained in prudent driving and   customer service.&nbsp;The transport will be from Cusco to Soraypampa and   from Ollantaytambo to Cusco at the end of our trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Pick up from the hotel.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Our service includes pick   up from your&nbsp;hotel&nbsp;to start the tour, pick up time will be confirmed   according to the location of your hotel, at the end of the tour we will   also leave you back at your hotel.&nbsp;(Our service does not include pick up   from&nbsp;AIRBNB&nbsp;type houses&nbsp;because many do not have a clear name or   address), in that case we will coordinate a place and time to pick up.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Snacks</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; beside the breakfast, we will provide you   snacks every morning so that you can take you along the way. We will   also provide snack bags that are made of cloth, we are very careful with   the environment so we try not to take anything plastic to the route and   if we do, we bring it back.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Train Tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;The train ticket included is the   Inca Rail the Voyager service, however, on the way you can make an Up   Grade to a 360 &deg; train that has windows on the roof to enjoy the   beautiful views on the road.&nbsp;This has an additional cost of $.&nbsp;$&nbsp;75&nbsp;per   person&nbsp;up to Poroy&nbsp;and is subject to availability. Poroy station is 30   minutes out of Cusco, we will still include the transfer to your hotel.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Bus tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; It is 25 minutes from the Town to   Machu Picchu and 25 minutes from Machu Picchu to the town + one-way bus   ticket the day before.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Inca Trail Entrance Tickets</strong>: We will get the Inca   trail entrance tickets and provide you, this will be given to you in the   beginning of the hike, as well as we will get the entrance for our   crew.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Entrance to Machu Picchu.</strong>&nbsp;We take care of providing   you with the entrance ticket to Machu Picchu and this will be giving to   you on the day of the tour, by your guide.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Porters:</strong>&nbsp;We include a personal porter, who is   responsible for carrying your travel bag with your personal items.&nbsp;There   is no additional fee for this.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Hotel:</strong>&nbsp;this Inca trail option ends at Machu Picchu   Pueblo.&nbsp;The last night is spent in a hotel in the village, instead of   camping.&nbsp;This 3-star hotel is included in the cost of the trek and is   based on a shared room.&nbsp;If you want to improve your hotel or prefer a   single room, you will have an additional cost.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Camping equipment:</strong>&nbsp;In Peru Private Tours we have   the best equipment.&nbsp;We use a 4 people tent only between 2 people so you   will have more space to put your belongings inside your tent during the   night.&nbsp;You will have a large tent&nbsp;to enjoy your meals as well as chairs   and table.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Food:</strong>&nbsp;5 breakfasts (the last included in the hotel)   4 lunches and 4 dinners, all prepared by our professional walking   chef.&nbsp;Our professional chefs&nbsp;prepare delicious meals that many previous   hikers have commented on.&nbsp;We honor all dietary restrictions.&nbsp;Be sure to   remind your tour guide about any food restrictions at the beginning of   your walk (Breafing time).&nbsp;The food is typically served family   style.&nbsp;You will enjoy breakfast, lunch and dinner every day of the&nbsp;trek,   with a delicious happy hour every afternoon before dinner.&nbsp;You will   also be provided with a snack every morning, so that you can enjoy the   walk.&nbsp;Your last&nbsp;meal with your chef will be&nbsp;breakfast on day four&nbsp;since   lunch and dinner will be at a restaurant.&nbsp;Lunch on the last day&nbsp;(day   05)&nbsp;is not included.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Water:</strong>&nbsp;from your first lunch until your last   breakfast,&nbsp;PPT&nbsp;will provide you with all the necessary water.&nbsp;This water   will be boiled, filtered and then cooled, before distribution.&nbsp;You must   supply your own bottles of water or camelback.&nbsp;We recommend carrying   around 3L.&nbsp;We will fill our waters at every meal.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>First aid:</strong>&nbsp;each of our guides has received training   in first aid from a doctor.&nbsp;We hold mandatory training sessions every   February, to which all the guides must attend.&nbsp;Your tour guide will   always have a first aid kit for basic medical problems (traveler&rsquo;s   diarrhea, cuts, scratches, etc.) and oxygen tank.&nbsp;We will get you out of   the way as quickly and comfortably as possible if necessary, and we   will make sure you go directly to a clinic to receive treatment.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Extras:</strong>&nbsp;We believe that it is the attention to   small details that differentiates us from other travel companies.&nbsp;Each   hiker receives a backpack covers to protect your belongings during the   trek, a rain poncho. We will work hard to create your best vacations.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Private transfer from Ollantaytambo to Cusco.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;   Upon arrival at the Ollantaytambo train station our staff will be   waiting for you with a van only for our group to transfer you to   your&nbsp;hotel in Cusco or Sacred Valley.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Permanent Assistance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We want all the activities   you do in our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so you   will always have an&nbsp;assigned&nbsp;personal assistant&nbsp;who will be in constant   communication with you.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <h3>Not included</h3>\r\n  <p>All travelers need a sleeping bag on adventure routes, do not forget   to bring your own.&nbsp;The walking sticks and air mattresses are optional   and serve to provide greater comfort during the walk.&nbsp;If you do not want   to bring any camping gear you can always rent from our office.</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Walking sticks (pair)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $.&nbsp;USD 15 per person</strong></p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>headlamps:</strong> it&nbsp;is strongly recommended to bring a   head lamp for the evenings.&nbsp;There will be no lights on the camping sites   and it will be difficult to get to your dining tent or bathroom tent   without one.&nbsp;Hand lanterns are acceptable, if you do not have a head   lamp, but it makes some tasks difficult.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Huayna Picchu</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;<strong>Huayna Picchu</strong> is   the mountain that is seen behind Machu Picchu in the classic photos, to   go up this mountain you need to buy an additional entrance and it has a   cost of $.&nbsp;35 dollars per person, however,&nbsp;this entrance must be   requested at the time of your reservation and it will be confirmed   according to availability of spaces as they only allow 200 people.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Flights.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;Flying to Cusco can be   complicated.&nbsp;Delays occur frequently especially between October to March   and it is not uncommon for flights to be canceled.&nbsp;Make sure you arrive   in the city at least two days before the start date of your trek to   Machu Picchu.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;is the most reliable airline.&nbsp;Avianca and Peruvian   Airlines&nbsp;are also acceptable companies.&nbsp;You will not return from your   tour on the last day until around 8 pm So make sure your flight is not   the day of the Machu Picchu Tour, rather the next day.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Tips</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Tips are always appreciated and should be   based entirely on your level of satisfaction.&nbsp;Although it may not be   usual for you, it has considerable importance to the people who will   assist you during your trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Travel insurance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; To protect your travel   investment, we recommend the purchase&nbsp;a travel insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel   insurance before leaving home is highly recommended and very   easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending on your country of   origin and at different prices according to your time of stay, take some   time to review them and hire the one that best suits you.&nbsp;This is an   excellent way to protect yourself while visiting&nbsp;Peru.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n', '  <h3>Breafing (Previous Information)</h3>\n  <p>All information sessions are held in our office at 06:00 PM the night   before your trek.&nbsp;If you cannot assist to this talk please contact our   office staff to serve you better.</p>\n  <h3>Arrive in Cusco</h3>\n  <p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline   options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it   has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU,   LC PERU&nbsp;to choose according to your preference.&nbsp;Expect&nbsp;flight delays or   cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult   to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.&nbsp;Bus   tours&nbsp;are always available and although the journey may be long,   especially from&nbsp;Lima,&nbsp;Peru buses&nbsp;are well maintained and are   comfortable.&nbsp;This option is recommended if you come from a city closer   to&nbsp;Cusco like Puno or Arequipa.&nbsp;Buses from Lima will take around 20   hours to arrive to Cusco.</p>\n  <h3>Pick Up from The Hotels.</h3>\n  <p>We pick up all our clients from the hotel for all tours.&nbsp;While your   hotel is in the center of the city of Cusco, we will coordinate this   pick up&nbsp;with the&nbsp;guide at the information session.&nbsp;Pick-up&nbsp;times&nbsp;may   vary between 20 and 30&nbsp;minutes depending on traffic conditions and   hotel&nbsp;locations.</p>\n  <p>Cusco is an ancient city with cobblestone streets and very narrow   corridors.&nbsp;Very small hotels and Air BNBs are often located on streets   that cars cannot pass through.&nbsp;They are also usually located on the side   of the hill, with long and steep climbs to the property, difficult to   maneuver with luggage.&nbsp;We recommend that you do not&nbsp;stay in one of these   places and try to find places where there is easy access to carry your   bags.</p>\n  <h3>Leaving Machu Picchu requires a lot of logistics,&nbsp;but&nbsp;everything&nbsp;is&nbsp;included in your journey.</h3>\n  <p>From Machu Picchu&nbsp;Ruins&nbsp;to&nbsp;Machu Picchu Pueblo, you&nbsp;will take a   25-minute bus.&nbsp;The&nbsp;buses are in order of arrival and you can take any of   those in turn.</p>\n  <p>From Machu Picchu Pueblo,&nbsp;you will take a&nbsp;train&nbsp;to&nbsp;Ollantaytambo or   Poroy&nbsp;station.&nbsp;Your guide will give you your train tickets.&nbsp;Make sure   you get to the platform 30 minutes ahead of time.</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Ollantaytambo is 2 hours.</li>\n    <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Poroy is 3.5 hours.</li>\n  </ul>\n  <p>Once you arrive at the train station, look&nbsp;for our staff with a PPT sign.&nbsp;He&nbsp;will take you to the Plaza San Francisco, Cusco.</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>The trip on&nbsp;the van&nbsp;from Ollantaytambo to Plaza de San Francisco is 2 hours</li>\n    <li>Travel by&nbsp;van&nbsp;from Poroy to&nbsp;San Francisco Plaza is&nbsp;30 minutes</li>\n  </ul>\n  <p>Once you arrive at the Plaza San Francisco&nbsp;our staff will be waiting   for you to separate you and send in pre-paid taxis to your respective   hotels.</p>\n  <h3>Entrance fees to Machu Picchu</h3>\n  <p>Machu Picchu has now different schadules to visit: morning or   afternoon.&nbsp;Your ticket will be&nbsp;for a single&nbsp;entry,&nbsp;in the morning, once   your time is done, the&nbsp;guards will ask&nbsp;you&nbsp;to&nbsp;leave.</p>\n  <p><strong>NOTE:</strong>&nbsp;If you have tickets to&nbsp;climb to Huayna Picchu   or Machu Picchu Mountain, you will have additional time until 2:30   PM.&nbsp;And you can re-enter for a single time as long as it is within the   time of re-entry (05 hours from the first entry)</p>\n  <p>If you want&nbsp;to&nbsp;spend all day at Machu Picchu, we can add a ticket&nbsp;for   the&nbsp;afternoon&nbsp;group&nbsp;to your reservation for $ 50 per person.</p>\n  <h3>Huayna Picchu / Machu Picchu Mountain</h3>\n  <p>Machu Picchu is more beautiful when viewed from above, so it is very   popular to hike one of the mountains next to the ruins after your guided   tour.</p>\n  <p>Huayna Picchu is the most popular and must be booked in advance &hellip; it   sells very fast.&nbsp;This hike takes approximately&nbsp;50&nbsp;minutes to the top   and&nbsp;40&nbsp;minutes downhill to the bottom.&nbsp;There are 2 schedules or groups   to enter this mountain.&nbsp;The first group&nbsp;is 8-p am and&nbsp;the second&nbsp;is 10   am to 11 am.&nbsp;Again, this refers to when you can start your hike and   normally we reserve the second&nbsp;option&nbsp;so you can first enjoy your tour   with your guide&nbsp;in Machu Picchu.&nbsp;This walk will be&nbsp;done&nbsp;on your own, but   your guide will show you where to start.</p>\n  <p>The Machu Picchu mountain is a little longer and less popular.&nbsp;It   takes&nbsp;2&nbsp;hours to reach the top&nbsp;and 1.5&nbsp;hours to reach the bottom.&nbsp;There   are also 2 visiting hours: from 7-8 am and from 9 am to 10 am and we   usually buy&nbsp;for the second group.</p>\n  <h3>Health Concerns</h3>\n  <p>It is important that you be honest with your guide about any health   problems you may suffer.&nbsp;Although the guides are not medical   professionals, they are trained in first aid.&nbsp;We also work with a clinic   in Cusco that can help our team.</p>\n  <p>You are responsible for evaluating if a trek is suitable for you.&nbsp;You   should consult your doctor to confirm your physical condition to travel   and participate in any planned activity.&nbsp;You should seek advice from   your doctor about vaccinations and medical precautions.&nbsp;Peru Private   Tours will&nbsp;not provide medical advice.&nbsp;It is your responsibility to   assess the risks and requirements of each aspect of the Tour based on   your own circumstances, limitations, fitness level and medical   requirements.</p>\n  <p>If during the trek you get sick of extreme altitude or any other   illness that not allows you to continuing with the journey, but you want   to visit Machu Picchu by train, we will work with you to coordinate   this trip.&nbsp;This will be a new trip and may involve additional costs.&nbsp;We   will use as much of the logistics purchased from the original route to   keep rates low.</p>\n  <p>If you experience problems while walking and cannot continue, a   porter will escort you to the nearest road and wait while a car comes to   pick you up and take you to the nearest health clinic.</p>\n  <h3>Group trips</h3>\n  <p>Group tours are made up of different types of people, with different   walking skills and ages.&nbsp;By accepting a group trip, you understand that   some people may be slower or faster than you.&nbsp;Everyone can make their   own pace for the walk, the guide will work through the group to spend   time with everyone.&nbsp;Groups can request some modifications to the tour   and&nbsp;the&nbsp;guide will work with everyone to make the best decision for the   group.</p>\n  <h3>Strikes</h3>\n  <p>Unfortunately, strikes are very common in Peru and can cause many   interruptions in our Tours.&nbsp;Roads are often blocked, trains stopped.&nbsp;We   will do everything possible to operate your Tour, even before the&nbsp;start   date.&nbsp;Some tours may&nbsp;be canceled under these circumstances.&nbsp;Our   Operations Department will coordinate with you in this situation.&nbsp;Your   safety is always our main concern and will determine how we decide.</p>\n  <h3>Lost Items</h3>\n  <p>You are responsible for your personal items throughout the Tour.&nbsp;Be   diligent about where&nbsp;you&nbsp;leave your stuff and remember&nbsp;to&nbsp;remove all   items from our vans,&nbsp;tents, restaurant, etc.&nbsp;Do not leave anything   involuntary while walking.&nbsp;Other hikers or teams can pick it up without   knowing to whom it belongs.</p>\n  <h3>Weather</h3>\n  <p>The climate in Cusco and Machu Picchu&nbsp;is unpredictable.&nbsp;In general,   the dry season in&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is from April to October, but this does not   prevent the rain from falling in June or the sun coming out in December,   just prepare for any weather condition.&nbsp;No matter which month you take   the hike or excursion, or which tour you are on, make sure you have   adequate clothing that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho and   waterproof gloves.</p>\n  <p>Also be prepared for&nbsp;four seasons in a day.&nbsp;Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a warm jacket.</p>\n  <h3>Altitude sickness</h3>\n  <p>As soon as the&nbsp;people reserve the trip to&nbsp;Peru, specifically   to&nbsp;Cusco, they begin to wonder about&nbsp;altitude sickness.&nbsp;High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.&nbsp;For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least&nbsp;amount of oxygen in the air.</p>\n  <p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p>\n  <p>For farther information about altitude sickness read our article <a href=\"http://www.pptoursperu.com/altitud-sickness-in-cusco/\">HERE</a></p>\n  <h3>Travel Insurance</h3>\n  <p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying&nbsp;travel   insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending   on your country of origin and at different prices&nbsp;according to your time   of stay, take some time to review them and hire the one that best suits   you.&nbsp;This is an excellent way to&nbsp;protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>\n  <h3>Community</h3>\n  <p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our   community. This is&nbsp;the&nbsp;main&nbsp;objective&nbsp;for our company.&nbsp;We are   working&nbsp;directly with the villages to help them meet the needs of their   families.&nbsp;We support the children of the villages by giving them&nbsp;school   supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and clothes.</p>\n  <p>We buy all our food from farmers and local markets and serve the   freshest ingredients.&nbsp;We offer&nbsp;constant training&nbsp;for all our team:   guides, porters, chefs and drivers.&nbsp;We are a family born in the Andes   and we want to work with them and for them.&nbsp;That is why once&nbsp;a year we   bring our porters and their families to&nbsp;Machu&nbsp;Picchu.&nbsp;We want our team   to know the world wonder, since they work tirelessly at the doors of   this place without ever visiting it and&nbsp;showing them this place is our   greatest honor.</p>', '', 'short-inca-trail-hotel', 0, 'Machu Picchu, Aguas Calientes', 0, 0, 549.00, 0, '2 days / 1 night', 2, 1, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"26985351\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=26985351\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 7, 3);
INSERT INTO `ProgramaPPT` (`Identificador`, `NombreIngles`, `MensajeIngles`, `MensajeSocialIngles`, `IntroduccionIngles`, `DescripcionIngles`, `IncluyeIngles`, `MasInformacionIngles`, `FAQIngles`, `Enlace`, `IdDestino`, `DestinosIngles`, `IdActividad`, `IdTipo`, `Precio`, `Duracion`, `DuracionIngles`, `Dificultad`, `EsPortada`, `OrdenPortada`, `CodigoWeTravel`, `CantidadImagenes`, `IdCategoria`) VALUES
(7, 'Short Inca Trail to Machu Picchu with Camping', 'Short Inca Trail 2D/1N with Camping\r\n\r\nThis tour requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend bokking it in advance, once you make your reservation will be confirmed as long as there is availability of space for the date that you select, please make sure to check the availability of spaces for the Short Inca Trail To Machu Picchu', 'By booking this tour your are planting 2 trees at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'The Short Inca Trail To Machu Picchu is a fantastic option for those who do not have much time to do the 4 or 5 days or who do not have the physical condition to support a multi-day trek through the mountains', '<p>The <strong>Short</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Inca Trail To Machu Picchu&nbsp;</strong>is   a fantastic option for those who do not have much time to do the 4 or 5   days or who do not have the physical condition to support a multi-day   trek through the mountains.&nbsp;This option is also very good for families   with small children who wish to experience a walk along the Inca   Trail.</p>\r\n<p>Along the route there are beautiful views of mountains and   valleysand Machu Picchu is entered by the same place as the walkers of 4   or 5 days with the advantage of&nbsp;visiting Machu Picchu 2 times in   addition to experiencing an outdoor camp in the canyon of Machu Picchu.</p>', '  <h3><strong>What our Short Inca Trail To Machu Picchu Includes:</strong></h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Professional Guide</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;We have the best selection of   guides, all graduated from the national university of&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;and grown up   in this region with a deep love and passion for teaching our   culture.&nbsp;They are fun but professional and will make sure you are safe   and happy.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Tourist transport.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We use clean and new vehicles   for all our services, with professional drivers that will guarantee you   a safe trip. Our drivers are constantly trained in prudent driving and   customer service.&nbsp;The transport will be from Cusco to Soraypampa and   from Ollantaytambo to Cusco at the end of our trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Pick up from the hotel.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Our service includes pick   up from your&nbsp;hotel&nbsp;to start the tour, pick up time will be confirmed   according to the location of your hotel, at the end of the tour we will   also leave you back at your hotel.&nbsp;(Our service does not include pick up   from&nbsp;AIRBNB&nbsp;type houses&nbsp;because many do not have a clear name or   address), in that case we will coordinate a place and time to pick up.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Snacks</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; beside the breakfast, we will provide you   snacks every morning so that you can take you along the way. We will   also provide snack bags that are made of cloth, we are very careful with   the environment so we try not to take anything plastic to the route and   if we do, we bring it back.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Train Tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;The train ticket included is the   Inca Rail the Voyager service, however, on the way you can make an Up   Grade to a 360 &deg; train that has windows on the roof to enjoy the   beautiful views on the road.&nbsp;This has an additional cost of $.&nbsp;$&nbsp;75&nbsp;per   person&nbsp;up to Poroy&nbsp;and is subject to availability. Poroy station is 30   minutes out of Cusco, we will still include the transfer to your hotel.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Bus tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; It is 25 minutes from the Town to   Machu Picchu and 25 minutes from Machu Picchu to the town + one-way bus   ticket the day before.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>&nbsp;Short</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Inca Trail Entrance Tickets:</strong> We will get the Inca trail entrance tickets and provide you, this will   be given to you in the beginning of the hike, as well as we will get the   entrance for our crew.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Entrance to</strong> <strong>Machu</strong> <strong>Picchu.</strong>&nbsp;We   take care of providing you with the entrance ticket to Machu Picchu and   this will be giving to you on the day of the tour, by your guide.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Porters:</strong>&nbsp;We include a personal porter, who is   responsible for carrying your travel bag with your personal items.&nbsp;There   is no additional fee for this.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Camping equipment:</strong>&nbsp;In Peru Private Tours we have   the best equipment.&nbsp;We use a 4 people tent only between 2 people so you   will have more space to put your belongings inside your tent during the   night.&nbsp;You will have a large tent&nbsp;to enjoy your meals as well as chairs   and table.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Food:</strong> 2 breakfasts 2 lunches and 1 dinner, all   prepared by our professional walking chef.&nbsp;Our professional   chefs&nbsp;prepare delicious meals that many previous hikers have commented   on.&nbsp;We honor all dietary restrictions.&nbsp;Be sure to remind your tour guide   about any food restrictions at the beginning of your walk (Breafing   time).&nbsp;The food is typically served family style.&nbsp;You will enjoy   breakfast, lunch and dinner every day of the&nbsp;trek, with a delicious   happy hour every afternoon before dinner.&nbsp;You will also be provided with   a snack every morning, so that you can enjoy the walk.&nbsp;Your last&nbsp;meal   with your chef will be&nbsp;breakfast on day 2&nbsp;since lunch and dinner will be   at a restaurant.&nbsp;Lunch on the last day&nbsp;(day 05)&nbsp;is not included.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Water:</strong>&nbsp;from your first lunch until your last   breakfast,&nbsp;PPT&nbsp;will provide you with all the necessary water.&nbsp;This water   will be boiled, filtered and then cooled, before distribution.&nbsp;You must   supply your own bottles of water or camelback.&nbsp;We recommend carrying   around 3L.&nbsp;We will fill our waters at every meal.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>First aid:</strong>&nbsp;each of our guides has received training   in first aid from a doctor.&nbsp;We hold mandatory training sessions every   February, to which all the guides must attend.&nbsp;Your tour guide will   always have a first aid kit for basic medical problems (traveler&rsquo;s   diarrhea, cuts, scratches, etc.) and oxygen tank.&nbsp;We will get you out of   the way as quickly and comfortably as possible if necessary, and we   will make sure you go directly to a clinic to receive treatment.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Extras:</strong>&nbsp;We believe that it is the attention to   small details that differentiates us from other travel companies.&nbsp;Each   hiker receives a backpack covers to protect your belongings during the   trek, a rain poncho. We will work hard to create your best vacations.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Private transfer from Ollantaytambo to Cusco.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;   Upon arrival at the Ollantaytambo train station our staff will be   waiting for you with a van only for our group to transfer you to   your&nbsp;hotel in Cusco or Sacred Valley.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Permanent Assistance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We want all the activities   you do in our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so you   will always have an&nbsp;assigned&nbsp;personal assistant&nbsp;who will be in constant   communication with you.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <h3>Not included</h3>\r\n  <p><strong>All travelers need a sleeping bag on adventure routes, do not   forget to bring your own.&nbsp;The walking sticks and air mattresses are   optional and serve to provide greater comfort during the walk.&nbsp;If you do   not want to bring any camping gear you can always rent from our office.</strong></p>\r\n  <p>Walking sticks (pair): $.&nbsp;USD 10 per person</p>\r\n  <p>Sleeping Bag: $. USD 15 Per person</p>\r\n  <p>Air Matt: $. USD 10 Per person</p>\r\n  <h4><strong>Other things you must have with you:</strong></h4>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>headlamps:</strong> it&nbsp;is strongly recommended to bring a   head lamp for the evenings.&nbsp;There will be no lights on the camping sites   and it will be difficult to get to your dining tent or bathroom tent   without one.&nbsp;Hand lanterns are acceptable, if you do not have a head   lamp, but it makes some tasks difficult.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Huayna Picchu</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;<strong>Huayna Picchu</strong> is   the mountain that is seen behind Machu Picchu in the classic photos, to   go up this mountain you need to buy an additional entrance and it has a   cost of $.&nbsp;35 dollars per person, however,&nbsp;this entrance must be   requested at the time of your reservation and it will be confirmed   according to availability of spaces as they only allow 200 people.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Flights.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;Flying to Cusco can be   complicated.&nbsp;Delays occur frequently especially between October to March   and it is not uncommon for flights to be canceled.&nbsp;Make sure you arrive   in the city at least two days before the start date of your trek to   Machu Picchu.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;is the most reliable airline.&nbsp;Avianca and Peruvian   Airlines&nbsp;are also acceptable companies.&nbsp;You will not return from your   tour on the last day until around 8 pm So make sure your flight is not   the day of the Machu Picchu Tour, rather the next day.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tips</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Tips are always appreciated and should be   based entirely on your level of satisfaction.&nbsp;Although it may not be   usual for you, it has considerable importance to the people who will   assist you during your trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Travel insurance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; To protect your travel   investment, we recommend the purchase&nbsp;a travel insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel   insurance before leaving home is highly recommended and very   easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending on your country of   origin and at different prices according to your time of stay, take some   time to review them and hire the one that best suits you.&nbsp;This is an   excellent way to protect yourself while visiting&nbsp;Peru.</li>\r\n  </ul>', '  <h3>Breafing (Previous Information)</h3>\r\n  <p>All information sessions are held in our office at 06:00 PM the night   before your trek.&nbsp;If you cannot assist to this talk please contact our   office staff to serve you better.</p>\r\n  <h3>Arrive in Cusco</h3>\r\n  <p>The airport in Cusco&nbsp;is currently&nbsp;quite small and only for domestic   flights, so all international travelers by plane must disembark   in&nbsp;Lima&nbsp;and go through Customs.&nbsp;Even if your flight to&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is the same   day by the same airline, you must pick up your bags in Lima and then   register them again.</p>\r\n  <p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline   options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it   has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU,   LC PERU&nbsp;to choose according to your preference.&nbsp;Expect&nbsp;flight delays or   cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult   to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.&nbsp;Bus   tours&nbsp;are always available and although the journey may be long,   especially from&nbsp;Lima,&nbsp;Peru buses&nbsp;are well maintained and are   comfortable.&nbsp;This option is recommended if you come from a city closer   to&nbsp;Cusco like Puno or Arequipa.&nbsp;Buses from Lima will take around 20   hours to arrive to Cusco.</p>\r\n  <h3>Pick Up from The Hotels.</h3>\r\n  <p>We pick up all our clients from the hotel for all tours.&nbsp;While your   hotel is in the center of the city of Cusco, we will coordinate this   pick up&nbsp;with the&nbsp;guide at the information session.&nbsp;Pick-up&nbsp;times&nbsp;may   vary between 20 and 30&nbsp;minutes depending on traffic conditions and   hotel&nbsp;locations.</p>\r\n  <p>Cusco is an ancient city with cobblestone streets and very narrow   corridors.&nbsp;Very small hotels and Air BNBs are often located on streets   that cars cannot pass through.&nbsp;They are also usually located on the side   of the hill, with long and steep climbs to the property, difficult to   maneuver with luggage.&nbsp;We recommend that you do not&nbsp;stay in one of these   places and try to find places where there is easy access to carry your   bags.</p>\r\n  <h3>Leaving Machu <strong>Picchu</strong> requires a lot of logistics,&nbsp;but&nbsp;everything&nbsp;is&nbsp;included in your journey.</h3>\r\n  <p>From Machu Picchu&nbsp;Ruins&nbsp;to&nbsp;Machu Picchu Pueblo, you&nbsp;will take a   25-minute bus.&nbsp;The&nbsp;buses are in order of arrival and you can take any of   those in turn.</p>\r\n  <p>From Machu Picchu Pueblo,&nbsp;you will take a&nbsp;train&nbsp;to&nbsp;Ollantaytambo or   Poroy&nbsp;station.&nbsp;Your guide will give you your train tickets.&nbsp;Make sure   you get to the platform 30 minutes ahead of time.</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Ollantaytambo is 2 hours.</li>\r\n    <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Poroy is 3.5 hours.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>Once you arrive at the train station, look&nbsp;for our staff with a PPT sign.&nbsp;He&nbsp;will take you to the Plaza San Francisco, Cusco.</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>The trip on&nbsp;the van&nbsp;from Ollantaytambo to Plaza de San Francisco is 2 hours</li>\r\n    <li>Travel by&nbsp;van&nbsp;from Poroy to&nbsp;San Francisco Plaza is&nbsp;30 minutes</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>Once you arrive at the Plaza San Francisco&nbsp;our staff will be waiting   for you to separate you and send in pre-paid taxis to your respective   hotels.</p>\r\n  <h3>Entrance fees to Machu Picchu</h3>\r\n  <p>Machu Picchu now has two&nbsp;hours&nbsp;to visit: morning or afternoon.&nbsp;Your   ticket will be&nbsp;for a single&nbsp;entry,&nbsp;in the morning, once your time is   done, the&nbsp;guards will ask&nbsp;you&nbsp;to&nbsp;leave.</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Morning turn: 6AM &ndash; 12PM</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>Afternoon turn: 12PM &ndash; 5:30 PM</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>NOTE:</strong>&nbsp;If you have tickets to&nbsp;climb to Huayna Picchu   or Machu Picchu Mountain, you will have additional time until 2:30   PM.&nbsp;And you can re-enter for a single time as long as it is within the   time of re-entry (05 hours from the first entry)</p>\r\n  <p>If you want&nbsp;to&nbsp;spend all day at Machu Picchu, we can add a ticket&nbsp;for   the&nbsp;afternoon&nbsp;group&nbsp;to your reservation for $ 50 per person.</p>\r\n  <h3>Huayna Picchu / Machu Picchu Mountain</h3>\r\n  <p>Machu Picchu is more beautiful when viewed from above, so it is very   popular to hike one of the mountains next to the ruins after your guided   tour.</p>\r\n  <p>Huayna Picchu is the most popular and must be booked in advance &hellip; it   sells very fast.&nbsp;This hike takes approximately&nbsp;50&nbsp;minutes to the top   and&nbsp;40&nbsp;minutes downhill to the bottom.&nbsp;There are 2 schedules or groups   to enter this mountain.&nbsp;The first group&nbsp;is 8-p am and&nbsp;the second&nbsp;is 10   am to 11 am.&nbsp;Again, this refers to when you can start your hike and   normally we reserve the second&nbsp;option&nbsp;so you can first enjoy your tour   with your guide&nbsp;in Machu Picchu.&nbsp;This walk will be&nbsp;done&nbsp;on your own, but   your guide will show you where to start.</p>\r\n  <p>The Machu Picchu mountain is a little longer and less popular.&nbsp;It   takes&nbsp;2&nbsp;hours to reach the top&nbsp;and 1.5&nbsp;hours to reach the bottom.&nbsp;There   are also 2 visiting hours: from 7-8 am and from 9 am to 10 am and we   usually buy&nbsp;for the second group.</p>\r\n  <h3>Health Concerns</h3>\r\n  <p>It is important that you be honest with your guide about any health   problems you may suffer.&nbsp;Although the guides are not medical   professionals, they are trained in first aid.&nbsp;We also work with a clinic   in Cusco that can help our team.</p>\r\n  <p>You are responsible for evaluating if a trek is suitable for you.&nbsp;You   should consult your doctor to confirm your physical condition to travel   and participate in any planned activity.&nbsp;You should seek advice from   your doctor about vaccinations and medical precautions.&nbsp;Peru Private   Tours will&nbsp;not provide medical advice.&nbsp;It is your responsibility to   assess the risks and requirements of each aspect of the Tour based on   your own circumstances, limitations, fitness level and medical   requirements.</p>\r\n  <p>If during the trek you get sick of extreme altitude or any other   illness that not allows you to continuing with the journey, but you want   to visit Machu Picchu by train, we will work with you to coordinate   this trip.&nbsp;This will be a new trip and may involve additional costs.&nbsp;We   will use as much of the logistics purchased from the original route to   keep rates low.</p>\r\n  <p>If you experience problems while walking and cannot continue, a   porter will escort you to the nearest road and wait while a car comes to   pick you up and take you to the nearest health clinic.</p>\r\n  <h3>Group trips</h3>\r\n  <p>Group tours are made up of different types of people, with different   walking skills and ages.&nbsp;By accepting a group trip, you understand that   some people may be slower or faster than you.&nbsp;Everyone can make their   own pace for the walk, the guide will work through the group to spend   time with everyone.&nbsp;Groups can request some modifications to the tour   and&nbsp;the&nbsp;guide will work with everyone to make the best decision for the   group.</p>\r\n  <h3>Strikes</h3>\r\n  <p>Unfortunately, strikes are very common in Peru and can cause many   interruptions in our Tours.&nbsp;Roads are often blocked, trains stopped.&nbsp;We   will do everything possible to operate your Tour, even before the&nbsp;start   date.&nbsp;Some tours may&nbsp;be canceled under these circumstances.&nbsp;Our   Operations Department will coordinate with you in this situation.&nbsp;Your   safety is always our main concern and will determine how we decide.</p>\r\n  <h3>Lost Items</h3>\r\n  <p>You are responsible for your personal items throughout the Tour.&nbsp;Be   diligent about where&nbsp;you&nbsp;leave your stuff and remember&nbsp;to&nbsp;remove all   items from our vans,&nbsp;tents, restaurant, etc.&nbsp;Do not leave anything   involuntary while walking.&nbsp;Other hikers or teams can pick it up without   knowing to whom it belongs.</p>\r\n  <h3>Weather</h3>\r\n  <p>The climate in Cusco and Machu Picchu&nbsp;is unpredictable.&nbsp;In general,   the dry season in&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is from April to October, but this does not   prevent the rain from falling in June or the sun coming out in December,   just prepare for any weather condition.&nbsp;No matter which month you take   the hike or excursion, or which tour you are on, make sure you have   adequate clothing that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho and   waterproof gloves.</p>\r\n  <p>Also be prepared for&nbsp;four seasons in a day.&nbsp;Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a warm jacket.</p>\r\n  <h3>Altitude sickness</h3>\r\n  <p>As soon as the&nbsp;people reserve the trip to&nbsp;Peru, specifically   to&nbsp;Cusco, they begin to wonder about&nbsp;altitude sickness.&nbsp;High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.&nbsp;For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least&nbsp;amount of oxygen in the air.</p>\r\n  <p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p>\r\n  <p>Most of the time, these symptoms will be mild.&nbsp;We always recommend   easy activities and walk&nbsp;slowly, allowing your body to adapt.&nbsp;Drink   plenty of fluids such as water or coca tea.&nbsp;Coca tea&nbsp;has been used since   ancient times to help prevent&nbsp;altitude&nbsp;sickness.&nbsp;The leaves&nbsp;of the coca   plant&nbsp;contain alkaloids that help carry oxygen to the blood, helping   your body avoid the effects of altitude sickness.&nbsp;Avoid drinking a lot   of alcohol and coffee because it will make you urinate more often and   you will become dehydrated.&nbsp;Avoid smoking,&nbsp;Smoking makes it difficult   for your body to get oxygen.&nbsp;Avoid sleeping pills.&nbsp;They can cause   shallow breathing at night, which makes it difficult for your body to   absorb oxygen while you sleep.</p>\r\n  <p>Many people prefer to visit the doctor to give them a treatment with   pills even before traveling to avoid problems during their stay.&nbsp;Your   doctor&nbsp;may prescribe medications, such   as&nbsp;acetazolamide&nbsp;and&nbsp;dexamethasone, to&nbsp;help&nbsp;prevent altitude   sickness.&nbsp;Start the medicine two days before reaching a high   altitude.&nbsp;Continue taking it while you are at high altitude.</p>\r\n  <h3>Travel <strong>insurance</strong></h3>\r\n  <p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying&nbsp;travel   insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending   on your country of origin and at different prices&nbsp;according to your time   of stay, take some time to review them and hire the one that best suits   you.&nbsp;This is an excellent way to&nbsp;protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>\r\n  <h3><strong>Community</strong></h3>\r\n  <p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our   community. This is&nbsp;the&nbsp;main&nbsp;objective&nbsp;for our company.&nbsp;We are   working&nbsp;directly with the villages to help them meet the needs of their   families.&nbsp;We support the children of the villages by giving them&nbsp;school   supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and clothes.</p>\r\n  <p>We buy all our food from farmers and local markets and serve the   freshest ingredients.&nbsp;We offer&nbsp;constant training&nbsp;for all our team:   guides, porters, chefs and drivers.&nbsp;We are a family born in the Andes   and we want to work with them and for them.&nbsp;That is why once&nbsp;a year we   bring our porters and their families to&nbsp;Machu&nbsp;Picchu.&nbsp;We want our team   to know the world wonder, since they work tirelessly at the doors of   this place without ever visiting it and&nbsp;showing them this place is our   greatest honor.</p>', '', 'short-inca-trail', 0, '', 0, 0, 549.00, 0, '2 days / 1 night', 0, 0, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"53856403\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=53856403\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 7, 3),
(8, 'Machu Picchu Hike', 'This tour requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend to book it in advance, your reservation will be confirmed as long as there is spaces available for the date that you selected, please make sure to check the availability of spaces for the short inca trail 2 days 1 night', 'By booking this tour your are planting 4 trees at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'The Machu Picchu Hike or called Classic Inca Trail 04 days is one of the most popular trails in the world, starts at KM 82 of the Cusco railway to Machu Picchu Pueblo.', '<p>The <strong>Machu Picchu Hike</strong> or called&nbsp;<strong>Classic&nbsp;Inca Trail</strong>&nbsp;04 days is one of the most popular trails in the world, starts at KM 82 of the Cusco railway to <strong>Machu Picchu Pueblo</strong>,   the first 06 hours of walking is a very gradual ascent to the town of   Huayllabamba.&nbsp;From this point begins the ascent&nbsp;s&nbsp;and descent.</p>\r\n<p>It has   camps assigned by SERNAMP, the road ends in the Inti Punku or <strong>Sun Gate</strong> from where you have the first view of the sacred city of the Incas <strong>Machu Picchu</strong>.&nbsp;It   is ideal for adventurers who like outdoor camping, combining nature,   culture and history in a 45 km walk through mountains and valleys with   beautiful views.</p>', '  <h3>Included</h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Professional Guide</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;We have the best selection of   guides, all graduated from the national university of&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;and grown up   in this region with a deep love and passion for teaching our   culture.&nbsp;They are fun but professional and will make sure you are safe   and happy.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tourist transport.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We use clean and new vehicles   for all our services, with professional drivers that will guarantee you a   safe trip. Our drivers are constantly trained in prudent driving and   customer service.&nbsp;The transport will be from Cusco to Soraypampa and   from Ollantaytambo to Cusco at the end of our trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Pick</strong> up <strong>from the hotel.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Our   service includes pick up from your&nbsp;hotel&nbsp;to start the tour, pick up time   will be confirmed according to the location of your hotel, at the end   of the tour we will also leave you back at your hotel.&nbsp;(Our service does   not include pick up from&nbsp;AIRBNB&nbsp;type houses&nbsp;because many do not have a   clear name or address), in that case we will coordinate a place and time   to pick up.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Snacks</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; beside the breakfast, we will provide you   snacks every morning so that you can take you along the way. We will   also provide snack bags that are made of cloth, we are very careful with   the environment so we try not to take anything plastic to the route and   if we do, we bring it back.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Train Tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;The train ticket included is the   Inca Rail the Voyager service, however, on the way you can make an Up   Grade to a 360 &deg; train that has windows on the roof to enjoy the   beautiful views on the road.&nbsp;This has an additional cost of $.&nbsp;$&nbsp;65&nbsp;per   person&nbsp;up to Poroy&nbsp;and is subject to availability. Poroy station is 30   minutes out of Cusco, we will still include the transfer to your hotel.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Bus tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; It is 25 minutes from the Town to Machu Picchu and 25 minutes from Machu Picchu to the town.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Inca Trail Entrance Tickets:</strong> We will get the Inca   trail entrance tickets and provide you, this will be given to you in the   beginning of the hike, as well as we will get the entrance for our   crew.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Entrance to Machu Picchu.</strong>&nbsp;We take care of providing   you with the entrance ticket to Machu Picchu and this will be giving to   you on the day of the tour, by your guide.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Porters:</strong>&nbsp;We include a personal porter, who is   responsible for carrying your travel bag with your personal items.&nbsp;There   is no additional fee for this.&nbsp;The night before we will give you your   duffel bag so that it is filled with the things you will need for the   trek.&nbsp;You will not have access to your duffle bag until you arrive at   your campsite at first night.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Hotel:</strong>&nbsp;Alternative&nbsp;excursions end at Machu Picchu   Pueblo.&nbsp;The last night is spent in a hotel in the village, instead of   camping.&nbsp;This 3-star hotel is included in the cost of the trek and is   based on a shared room.&nbsp;If you want to improve your hotel or prefer a   single room, you will have an additional cost.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Camping equipment:</strong>&nbsp;In Peru Private Tours we have   the best equipment.&nbsp;We use a 4 people tent only between 2 people so you   will have more space to put your belongings inside your tent during the   night.&nbsp;You will have a large tent&nbsp;to enjoy your meals as well as chairs   and table.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Food:</strong>&nbsp;4 breakfasts (the last included in the hotel)   3 lunches and 3 dinners, all prepared by our professional walking   chef.&nbsp;Our professional chefs&nbsp;prepare delicious meals that many previous   hikers have commented on.&nbsp;We honor all dietary restrictions.&nbsp;Be sure to   remind your tour guide about any food restrictions at the beginning of   your walk (Breafing time).&nbsp;The food is typically served family   style.&nbsp;You will enjoy breakfast, lunch and dinner every day of the&nbsp;trek,   with a delicious happy hour every afternoon before dinner.&nbsp;You will   also be provided with a snack every morning, so that you can enjoy the   walk.&nbsp;Your last&nbsp;meal with your chef will be&nbsp;breakfast on day four&nbsp;since   lunch and dinner on day 4 it is not included.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Water:</strong>&nbsp;from your first lunch until your last   breakfast,&nbsp;PPT&nbsp;will provide you with all the necessary water.&nbsp;This water   will be boiled, filtered and then cooled, before distribution.&nbsp;You must   supply your own bottles of water or camelback.&nbsp;We recommend carrying   around 3L.&nbsp;We will fill our waters at every meal.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>First aid:</strong>&nbsp;each of our guides has received training   in first aid from a doctor.&nbsp;We hold mandatory training sessions every   February, to which all the guides must attend.&nbsp;Your tour guide will   always have a first aid kit for basic medical problems (traveler&rsquo;s   diarrhea, cuts, scratches, etc.) and oxygen tank.&nbsp;We will get you out of   the way as quickly and comfortably as possible if necessary, and we   will make sure you go directly to a clinic to receive treatment.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Extras:</strong>&nbsp;We believe that it is the attention to   small details that differentiates us from other travel companies.&nbsp;Each   hiker receives a small pillow for sleeping, a sponge mats to isolate   (Matra), a backpack covers to protect your belongings during the trek, a   rain poncho and a waterproof plastic bags to put your belongings before   placing them in the duffle bag. We will work hard to create your best   vacations.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Private</strong> <strong>transfer from Ollantaytambo to Cusco.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;   Upon arrival at the Ollantaytambo train station our staff will be   waiting for you with a van only for our group to transfer you to   your&nbsp;hotel in Cusco or Sacred Valley.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Permanent Assistance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We want all the activities   you do in our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so you   will always have an&nbsp;assigned&nbsp;personal assistant&nbsp;who will be in constant   communication with you.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <h3>Not included</h3>\r\n  <p>All travelers need a sleeping bag on adventure routes, do not forget   to bring your own.&nbsp;The walking sticks and air mattresses are optional   and serve to provide greater comfort during the walk.&nbsp;If you do not want   to bring any camping gear you can always rent from our office.</p>\r\n  <p>Sleeping bag: $.&nbsp;20 USD per person</p>\r\n  <p>Air Matras: $.&nbsp;20 USD per person</p>\r\n  <p>Walking sticks (pair): $.&nbsp;USD 15 per person</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>headlamps:</strong> it&nbsp;is strongly recommended to bring a   head lamp for the evenings.&nbsp;There will be no lights on the camping sites   and it will be difficult to get to your dining tent or bathroom tent   without one.&nbsp;Hand lanterns are acceptable, if you do not have a head   lamp, but it makes some tasks difficult.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Huayna</strong> Picchu&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;Huayna Picchu is the mountain that   is seen behind Machu Picchu in the classic photos, to go up this   mountain you need to buy an additional entrance and it has a cost of   $.&nbsp;35 dollars per person, however,&nbsp;this entrance must be requested at   the time of your reservation and it will be confirmed according to   availability of spaces as they only allow 200 people.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Flights.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;Flying to Cusco can be   complicated.&nbsp;Delays occur frequently especially between October to March   and it is not uncommon for flights to be canceled.&nbsp;Make sure you arrive   in the city at least two days before the start date of your trek to   Machu Picchu.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;is the most reliable airline.&nbsp;Avianca and Peruvian   Airlines&nbsp;are also acceptable companies.&nbsp;You will not return from your   tour on the last day until around 8 pm So make sure your flight is not   the day of the Machu Picchu Tour, rather the next day.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tips</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Tips are always appreciated and should be   based entirely on your level of satisfaction.&nbsp;Although it may not be   usual for you, it has considerable importance to the people who will   assist you during your trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Travel insurance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; To protect your travel   investment, we recommend the purchase&nbsp;a travel insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel   insurance before leaving home is highly recommended and very   easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending on your country of   origin and at different prices according to your time of stay, take some   time to review them and hire the one that best suits you.&nbsp;This is an   excellent way to protect yourself while visiting&nbsp;Peru.</li>\r\n  </ul>', '  <h3>Breafing (Previous Information)</h3>   <p>All information sessions are held in our office at 06:00 PM the night   before your trek.&nbsp;If you cannot assist to this talk please contact our   office staff to serve you better.</p>   <h3>Duffle Bags</h3>   <p>You will receive your duffle bag at the information session.&nbsp;These   bags are to put your belongings inside it, these will be carried by the   porters and will be returned to you each evening at the   campsite.&nbsp;However, beside from these bags, you should carry a small   backpack where you will carry everything you need during the trek.</p>   <p>Each duffle bag must have a maximum weight of 7kg.&nbsp;4kg will be for   your clothes and other personal items, the other 3kg will be for our   logistics, such as your sleeping bag and pad, if you have your own   sleeping bag and mat these must be included in the 7 kilos.</p>   <h3>Arrive in Cusco</h3>   <p>The airport in Cusco&nbsp;is currently&nbsp;quite small and only for domestic   flights, so all international travelers by plane must disembark   in&nbsp;Lima&nbsp;and go through Customs.&nbsp;Even if your flight to&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is the same   day by the same airline, you must pick up your bags in Lima and then   register them again.</p>   <p>The bst way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline   options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it   has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU,   LC PERU&nbsp;to choose according to your preference.&nbsp;Expect&nbsp;flight delays or   cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult   to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.&nbsp;Bus   tours&nbsp;are always available and although the journey may be long,   especially from&nbsp;Lima,&nbsp;Peru buses&nbsp;are well maintained and are   comfortable.&nbsp;This option is recommended if you come from a city closer   to&nbsp;Cusco like Puno or Arequipa.&nbsp;Buses from Lima will take around 20   hours to arrive to Cusco.</p>   <h3>Pick Up from The Hotels.</h3>   <p>We pick up all our clients from the hotel for all tours.&nbsp;While your   hotel is in the center of the city of Cusco, we will coordinate this   pick up&nbsp;with the&nbsp;guide at the information session.&nbsp;Pick-up&nbsp;times&nbsp;may   vary between 20 and 30&nbsp;minutes depending on traffic conditions and   hotel&nbsp;locations.</p>   <p>Cusco is an ancient city with cobblestone streets and very narrow   corridors.&nbsp;Very small hotels and Air BNBs are often located on streets   that cars cannot pass through.&nbsp;They are also usually located on the side   of the hill, with long and steep climbs to the property, difficult to   maneuver with luggage.&nbsp;We recommend that you do not&nbsp;stay in one of these   places and try to find places where there is easy access to carry your   bags.</p>   <h3>Leaving Machu Picchu requires a lot of logistics,&nbsp;but&nbsp;everything&nbsp;is&nbsp;included in your journey.</h3>   <p>From Machu Picchu&nbsp;Ruins&nbsp;to&nbsp;Machu Picchu Pueblo, you&nbsp;will take a   25-minute bus.&nbsp;The&nbsp;buses are in order of arrival and you can take any of   those in turn.</p>   <p>From Machu Picchu Pueblo,&nbsp;you will take a&nbsp;train&nbsp;to&nbsp;Ollantaytambo or   Poroy&nbsp;station.&nbsp;Your guide will give you your train tickets.&nbsp;Make sure   you get to the platform 30 minutes ahead of time.</p>   <ul>     <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Ollantaytambo is 2 hours.</li>     <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Poroy is 3.5 hours.</li>   </ul>   <p>Once you arrive at the train station, look&nbsp;for our staff with a PPT sign.&nbsp;He&nbsp;will take you to the Plaza San Francisco, Cusco.</p>   <ul>     <li>The trip on&nbsp;the van&nbsp;from Ollantaytambo to Plaza de San Francisco is 2 hours</li>     <li>Travel by&nbsp;van&nbsp;from Poroy to&nbsp;San Francisco Plaza is&nbsp;30 minutes</li>   </ul>   <p>Once you arrive at the Plaza San Francisco&nbsp;our staff will be waiting   for you to separate you and send in pre-paid taxis to your respective   hotels.</p>   <h3>Entrance fees to Machu Picchu</h3>   <p>Machu Picchu now has two&nbsp;hours&nbsp;to visit: morning or afternoon.&nbsp;Your   ticket will be&nbsp;for a single&nbsp;entry,&nbsp;in the morning, once your time is   done, the&nbsp;guards will ask&nbsp;you&nbsp;to&nbsp;leave.</p>   <p><strong>Morning turn: 6AM &ndash; 12PM</strong></p>   <p><strong>Afternoon turn: 12PM &ndash; 5:30 PM</strong></p>   <p><strong>NOTE:</strong>&nbsp;If you have tickets to&nbsp;climb to Huayna Picchu   or Machu Picchu Mountain, you will have additional time until 2:30   PM.&nbsp;And you can re-enter for a single time as long as it is within the   time of re-entry (05 hours from the first entry)</p>   <p>If you want&nbsp;to&nbsp;spend all day at Machu Picchu, we can add a ticket&nbsp;for   the&nbsp;afternoon&nbsp;group&nbsp;to your reservation for $ 50 per person.</p>   <h3>Huayna Picchu / Machu Picchu Mountain</h3>   <p>Machu Picchu is more beautiful when viewed from above, so it is very   popular to hike one of the mountains next to the ruins after your guided   tour.</p>   <p>Huayna Picchu is the most popular and must be booked in advance &hellip; it   sells very fast.&nbsp;This hike takes approximately&nbsp;50&nbsp;minutes to the top   and&nbsp;40&nbsp;minutes downhill to the bottom.&nbsp;There are 2 schedules or groups   to enter this mountain.&nbsp;The first group&nbsp;is 8-p am and&nbsp;the second&nbsp;is 10   am to 11 am.&nbsp;Again, this refers to when you can start your hike and   normally we reserve the second&nbsp;option&nbsp;so you can first enjoy your tour   with your guide&nbsp;in Machu Picchu.&nbsp;This walk will be&nbsp;done&nbsp;on your own, but   your guide will show you where to start.</p>   <p>The Machu Picchu mountain is a little longer and less popular.&nbsp;It   takes&nbsp;2&nbsp;hours to reach the top&nbsp;and 1.5&nbsp;hours to reach the bottom.&nbsp;There   are also 2 visiting hours: from 7-8 am and from 9 am to 10 am and we   usually buy&nbsp;for the second group.</p>   <h3>Health Concerns</h3>   <p>It is important that you be honest with your guide about any health   problems you may suffer.&nbsp;Although the guides are not medical   professionals, they are trained in first aid.&nbsp;We also work with a clinic   in Cusco that can help our team.</p>   <p>You are responsible for evaluating if a trek is suitable for you.&nbsp;You   should consult your doctor to confirm your physical condition to travel   and participate in any planned activity.&nbsp;You should seek advice from   your doctor about vaccinations and medical precautions.&nbsp;Peru Private   Tours will&nbsp;not provide medical advice.&nbsp;It is your responsibility to   assess the risks and requirements of each aspect of the Tour based on   your own circumstances, limitations, fitness level and medical   requirements.</p>   <p>If during the trek you get sick of extreme altitude or any other   illness that not allows you to continuing with the journey, but you want   to visit Machu Picchu by train, we will work with you to coordinate   this trip.&nbsp;This will be a new trip and may involve additional costs.&nbsp;We   will use as much of the logistics purchased from the original route to   keep rates low.</p>   <p>If you experience problems while walking and cannot continue, a   porter will escort you to the nearest road and wait while a car comes to   pick you up and take you to the nearest health clinic.</p>   <h3>Group trips</h3>   <p>Group tours are made up of different types of people, with different   walking skills and ages.&nbsp;By accepting a group trip, you understand that   some people may be slower or faster than you.&nbsp;Everyone can make their   own pace for the walk, the guide will work through the group to spend   time with everyone.&nbsp;Groups can request some modifications to the tour   and&nbsp;the&nbsp;guide will work with everyone to make the best decision for the   group.</p>   <h3>Strikes</h3>   <p>Unfortunately, strikes are very common in Peru and can cause many   interruptions in our Tours.&nbsp;Roads are often blocked, trains stopped.&nbsp;We   will do everything possible to operate your Tour, even before the&nbsp;start   date.&nbsp;Some tours may&nbsp;be canceled under these circumstances.&nbsp;Our   Operations Department will coordinate with you in this situation.&nbsp;Your   safety is always our main concern and will determine how we decide.</p>   <h3>Lost Items</h3>   <p>You are responsible for your personal items throughout the Tour.&nbsp;Be   diligent about where&nbsp;you&nbsp;leave your stuff and remember&nbsp;to&nbsp;remove all   items from our vans,&nbsp;tents, restaurant, etc.&nbsp;Do not leave anything   involuntary while walking.&nbsp;Other hikers or teams can pick it up without   knowing to whom it belongs.</p>   <h3>Weather</h3>   <p>The climate in Cusco and Machu Picchu&nbsp;is unpredictable.&nbsp;In general,   the dry season in&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is from April to October, but this does not   prevent the rain from falling in June or the sun coming out in December,   just prepare for any weather condition.&nbsp;No matter which month you take   the hike or excursion, or which tour you are on, make sure you have   adequate clothing that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho and   waterproof gloves.</p>   <p>Also be prepared for&nbsp;four seasons in a day.&nbsp;Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a warm jacket.</p>   <h3>Altitude sickness</h3>   <p>As soon as the&nbsp;people reserve the trip to&nbsp;Peru, specifically   to&nbsp;Cusco, they begin to wonder about&nbsp;altitude sickness.&nbsp;High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.&nbsp;For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least&nbsp;amount of oxygen in the air.</p>   <p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p>   <p>For farther information about altitude sicknes clic <a href=\"http://www.pptoursperu.com/altitude-sickness-in-cusco/\">HERE</a></p>   <h3>Travel insurance</h3>   <p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying&nbsp;travel   insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending   on your country of origin and at different prices&nbsp;according to your time   of stay, take some time to review them and hire the one that best suits   you.&nbsp;This is an excellent way to&nbsp;protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>   <h3>Community</h3>   <p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our   community. This is&nbsp;the&nbsp;main&nbsp;objective&nbsp;for our company.&nbsp;We are   working&nbsp;directly with the villages to help them meet the needs of their   families.&nbsp;We support the children of the villages by giving them&nbsp;school   supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and clothes.</p>   <p>We buy all our food from farmers and local markets and serve the   freshest ingredients.&nbsp;We offer&nbsp;constant training&nbsp;for all our team:   guides, porters, chefs and drivers.&nbsp;We are a family born in the Andes   and we want to work with them and for them.&nbsp;That is why once&nbsp;a year we   bring our porters and their families to&nbsp;Machu&nbsp;Picchu.&nbsp;We want our team   to know the world wonder, since they work tirelessly at the doors of   this place without ever visiting it and&nbsp;showing them this place is our   greatest honor.</p>', '', 'machu-picchu-hike', 0, '', 0, 0, 749.00, 0, '4 days / 3 nights', 0, 0, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"50344212\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=50344212\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 6, 3);
INSERT INTO `ProgramaPPT` (`Identificador`, `NombreIngles`, `MensajeIngles`, `MensajeSocialIngles`, `IntroduccionIngles`, `DescripcionIngles`, `IncluyeIngles`, `MasInformacionIngles`, `FAQIngles`, `Enlace`, `IdDestino`, `DestinosIngles`, `IdActividad`, `IdTipo`, `Precio`, `Duracion`, `DuracionIngles`, `Dificultad`, `EsPortada`, `OrdenPortada`, `CodigoWeTravel`, `CantidadImagenes`, `IdCategoria`) VALUES
(9, 'Natural Dyeing & Weaving Experience', 'This is one of our new kind of tours offered only by our company, we want to change the way how you know the local culture, that is why we have started PPT EXPERIENCES where you will fall more in deep to our culture.', 'By booking this tour, you are planting 1 tree at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'Live this unique experience of dyeing with plants and weaving in waist loom together with great master weavers of Peru recognized by UNESCO', '<p>Live this unique experience of dyeing with plants and weaving in waist   loom together with great master weavers of peru recognized by UNESCO, do   not be a typical visitor who observes the process of elaboration, we   want you to be involved, we want you dyeing your own wool, make your own   textile piece.</p> <p>A full day of adventures awaits you in the Sacred Valley   of the Incas.</p>', '  <h2>WHAT OUR TRADITIONAL TEXTILES WORKSHOP INCLUDES</h2>   <ul>     <li><strong>Pick up from the hotel and transfer to the workshop.</strong>&ndash; We pick up from all the hotels in Cusco and Sacred Valley in a private vehicle.</li>     <li><strong>Reception</strong>.- Upon your arrival at our workshop we will receive you with a warm welcome and reception ceremony.</li>     <li><strong>Materials for the development of the workshop.</strong></li>     <li><strong>Family Style Lunch.-</strong> We include a family lunch that we will share among all those present in the workshop, the food is homemade style.</li>     <li><strong>Personal Instructor.-</strong> You will be assigned a   personal artisan instructor who will teach you during the whole process   of the workshop. The artisans are masters with recognized national and   international trajectory.</li>     <li><strong>Local guide.-</strong> One of the members of the workshop   will provide you with all the theoretical information about the whole   process of the workshop, likewise this person will accompany you   throughout the day or duration of the workshop.</li>     <li><strong>Transfer of the workshop to your hotel.</strong>&ndash; At the end of the workshop we will transfer you back to your hotel in the Sacred Valley or Cusco.</li>     <li><strong>Souveniers</strong>.- At the end of the workshop you can take the loom where you learned as well as the wool that you dyed yourself with the plant.</li>   </ul>   <h3>WHAT OUR TRADITIONAL TEXTILES WORKSHOP DOES NOT INCLUDE</h3>   <ul>     <li><strong>Unspecified food.-</strong> Breakfast and dinner are not included in the workshop.</li>     <li><strong>Other expenses not specified.</strong> &ndash; Additional expenses that are not specified may have additional costs, as additional activities may have additional costs.</li>   </ul>', '', '', 'natural-dyeing', 0, 'Cusco', 0, 0, 149.00, 0, 'Full day', 1, 1, 6, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"73568763\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=73568763\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 8, 1),
(10, 'Alpaca Walking Tour & Natural Dye Experience', 'This experience goes beyond tourism; it actively involves local communities in the Sacred Valley. Your scenic hike supports the livelihoods of those who call this valley home. In the hands-on textile workshop, you connect with the rich cultural heritage of the area, as locals share traditional craftsmanship. The authentic Pachamanca lunch, enjoyed amidst the community, creates a symbiotic relationship, allowing travelers to intimately understand local life while supporting and appreciating cultural practices.', 'By Booking this Experience, you are planting trees in the high andean communities of Cusco', 'Unique Cultural Immersion: This tour offers a rare opportunity to immerse yourself in the enchanting culture of the Sacred Valley. A Memorable Full Day Adventure.', '<p>Unique Cultural Immersion: This tour offers a rare opportunity to   immerse yourself in the enchanting culture of the Sacred Valley.</p> <p>Scenic Hike through the Sacred Valley: The tour includes a 4-hour   hike through the breathtaking landscapes of the Sacred Valley. Enjoy   stunning views, explore the natural beauty of the region, and engage in   invigorating physical activity.</p> <p>Hands-On Textile Workshop: Participate in a private textile workshop   where you&rsquo;ll learn the art of natural dyeing. Collect leaves during the   hike, which you&rsquo;ll later use to dye alpaca wool and fabric. Authentic   Pachamanca Lunch: Indulge in a traditional Peruvian dish called   pachamanca, shared with locals.</p>', '<h3>What our Alpaca Walking Tour includes and what not</h3> <h2>INCLUDED</h2> <ul>   <li>Hotel pick-up and drop-off for your convenience</li>   <li>One alpaca per person, creating a special bond throughout the journey</li>   <li>Knowledgeable English-speaking guide to enhance your understanding of the region</li>   <li>Local alpaca owner to share insights into the alpaca&rsquo;s significance and care</li>   <li>Pachamanca lunch, a delicious traditional Peruvian dish shared with locals</li>   <li>All necessary materials and tools for the natural dye workshop</li>   <li>Water available on request to keep you refreshed throughout the day</li> </ul> <h2>Not included</h2> <ul>   <li><strong>Tips</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;The&nbsp;tips for your crew are voluntary and according to your satisfaction level.</li>   <li><strong>Breakfast or dinner,</strong> allowing you the flexibility to choose your meals</li> </ul>', '<h2><strong>What to bring the Alpaca Walking Tour</strong></h2> <p>Please take note of these recommendations to do the Rainbow Mountain Tour.</p> <ul>   <li><strong>PASSPORT OR IDENTITY DOCUMENT</strong>&nbsp;(VERY IMPORTANT)</li>   <li><strong>Hat or cap for the sun:</strong> Very important for the walk, radiation is stronger in the Sacred Valley</li>   <li><strong>Sunglasses:</strong>&nbsp;Highly recommended.</li>   <li><strong>Sunscreen:</strong>&nbsp;The radiation in the mountains is stronger, use&nbsp;sunscreen every day.</li>   <li><strong>Waterproof jacket or windbreaker</strong>&nbsp;(if it is light much better)</li>   <li><strong>Bottle of water or CAMELBAK.</strong>&nbsp; double the regular dose of water you drink normally.</li>   <li><strong>Shoe with</strong> a <strong>good grip:</strong>&nbsp;If you have trekking shoe is much better</li>   <li><strong>Personal medication pills:</strong> Do not forget to take your personal medication, most importantly the ones you take daily.</li>   <li><strong>Others you consider necessary.</strong> However, remember that this is an ADVENTURE walk!</li>   <li><strong>Above all, a lot of desire to have fun, enjoy nature and learn about&nbsp;the local culture</strong>.</li> </ul> <h3>Altitude sickness</h3> <p>As soon as the people reserve the trip to Peru, specifically to   Cusco, they begin to wonder about altitude sickness. High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.</p> <p>In our rainbow mountain tour in the afternoon we will always have   oxygen tank and first aid kit, our guides all well trained to assist you   in case you have any altitude sympthom.</p> <p>For farther information about altitude sickness please read our article <a href=\"http://www.pptoursperu.com/en/altitud-sickness/\">HERE.</a></p> <h3>Weather</h3> <p>The weather in the Sacred Valley is unpredictable. Dry season in   Cusco is from April through October, but this does not prevent the rain   from falling in June or the sun coming out in December, just be prepared   for any weather.</p> <p>Make sure you have adequate clothing that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho and waterproof gloves.</p> <h3>Arriving to Cusco</h3> <p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline options.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.latam.com/en_us/\">LATAM</a> tends to be the most expensive, but it has more flight options.</p> <p>Expect&nbsp;flight delays or cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of   Cusco, tends to be difficult to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can   paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.</p> <h3>Travel insurance</h3> <p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying travel   insurance. Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.</p> <p>There are many insurance companies depending on your country of   origin and at different prices according to your time of stay, take some   time to review them and hire the one that best suits you. However, this   is an excellent way to protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p> <h3>Community</h3> <p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our community.&nbsp;This   is&nbsp;the&nbsp;main&nbsp;objective&nbsp;for our company.&nbsp;We are working&nbsp;directly with the   villages to help them meet the needs of their families.&nbsp;We support the   children of the villages by giving them&nbsp;school supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and   clothes.</p> <p>PPT offers constant training for all our team. We are a family born   in the Andes and we want to work with them and for them. In adition, we   plant a tree for every booking we receive from our customers, so thank   you for suppurting this wonderful project.</p>', '', 'alpaca-walking-tour', 0, 'Cusco, Sacred Valley', 0, 0, 139.00, 1, 'Full day', 1, 1, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"69644450\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=69644450\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 8, 1),
(11, 'Plant-Based Dyeing Workshop', 'This is a tour that requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend making the reservation in advance, once you make your reservation will be confirmed as long as there is availability of space for the date that you select, please make sure to check the availability of spaces for Inca trail 4 days.', 'By reserving this experience, you\'re contributing to the planting of 2 trees within a local indigenous community in Cusco.', 'Immerse yourself in the captivating world of Andean textile artistry with our Traditional Andean Textile Crafting workshop. Delve into the time-honored techniques of plant-based dyeing and backstrap loom weaving under the guidance of expert artisans.', '<p>Immerse yourself in the captivating world of Andean textile artistry   with our Traditional Andean Textile Crafting workshop. Delve into the   time-honored techniques of plant-based dyeing and backstrap loom weaving   under the guidance of expert artisans. Gain insights into the rich   history of Andean textiles and their cultural significance.</p> <p>Indulge in a   family-style lunch and embrace the community spirit. Depart with   cherished memories, a handcrafted keepsake, and a UNESCO-recognized   certificate, having journeyed through the heart of Peru&rsquo;s vibrant textile heritage.</p>', '   <h2><strong>Our Plant-Based Dyeing Workshop includes: </strong></h2>   <ul>     <li>Hotel Pickup and Transfer to Workshop: We provide private vehicle pickup from all hotels in Cusco and the Sacred Valley.</li>     <li>Workshop Reception: Upon your workshop arrival, a warm welcome and reception ceremony await you.</li>     <li>Materials for Workshop: All necessary tools and materials for the workshop will be provided to you.</li>     <li>Personal Instructor: An assigned artisan instructor will guide you   throughout the workshop. Our artisans are recognized for their expertise   nationally and internationally.</li>     <li>Local Guide: A workshop member will offer theoretical insights into the workshop process, accompanying you throughout the day.</li>     <li>Return Transfer: After the workshop, we will transport you back to your hotel in the Sacred Valley or Cusco.</li>     <li>Souvenir Keepsake: At the end of the workshop, take home the plant-dyed wool you&rsquo;ve crafted.</li>   </ul>   <h3><strong>Our Plant-Based Dyeing Workshop does not include: </strong></h3>   <ul>     <li>Unspecified Meals: Breakfast, Lunch and dinner are not included in the workshop since this is a half day experience.</li>     <li>Other Unspecified Expenses: Additional costs that are not specified   may arise, and additional activities may incur additional charges.</li>   </ul>', '<h3><strong>Altitude Sickness</strong></h3> <p>As soon as individuals plan their trip to Peru, specifically Cusco,   concerns about altitude sickness arise. The air at high altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level, compelling your body to work   harder to procure the oxygen it needs. Over several days at high   altitude, your body adjusts to the reduced oxygen levels in the air.</p>   <p>Initial <a href=\"https://www.pptoursperu.com/altitud-sickness-in-cusco/\">symptoms of altitude sickness</a> may include a headache, fatigue, followed by loss of appetite, nausea   or vomiting, dizziness, difficulty sleeping, and labored breathing   during exercise. Should any of these symptoms worsen, please contact our   office, and we will assist you in seeking medical attention.</p>   <h3><strong>Community Engagement</strong></h3>   <p>At Peru Private Tours (PPT), we take immense pride in our community initiatives. This is the   core objective of our company. We work directly with villages to help   meet the needs of their families. We support village children by   providing them with school supplies, books, and clothing.</p>   <p>We regularly organize clean-up activities along the paths we traverse, ensuring we leave attractions better than we found them.</p>', '', 'plant-based-dyeing-workshop', 0, '', 0, 0, 69.00, 0, 'Half day', 0, 0, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"68384525\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=68384525\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 4, 1),
(12, 'Salkantay Trek', 'This is a tour that requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend making the reservation in advance, once you make your reservation will be confirmed as long as there is availability of space for the date that you select, please make sure to check the availability of spaces for Inca trail 4 days.', 'By booking this tour your are planting 1 tree at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'Salkantay has become one of the most important hiking routes to Machu Picchu after the Inca Trail, which makes it so interesting to this route is the combination of all kinds of attractions', '<p><strong>Salkantay&nbsp;</strong>has become one of the most important hiking   routes to Machu Picchu after the Inca Trail, which makes it so   interesting to this route is the combination of all kinds of   attractions: Natural, cultural, local history and adventure, combined   all in a single program.</p>\r\n<p>Also the change of scenery is impressive   because you can descend in a single day from cold mountains near the   snowy to fertile valleys where you can appreciate coffee, bananas and   all kinds of tropical fruits. in addition to our itinerary you will have   the opportunity to enjoy adventure activities such   as&nbsp;Zipline&nbsp;or&nbsp;river&nbsp;rafting.</p>', '  <h3>Included</h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Professional Guide</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;We have the best selection of   guides, all graduated from the national university of&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;and grown up   in this region with a deep love and passion for teaching our   culture.&nbsp;They are fun but professional and will make sure you are safe   and happy.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tourist transport.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We use clean and new vehicles   for all our services, with professional drivers that will guarantee you a   safe trip. Our drivers are constantly trained in prudent driving and   customer service.&nbsp;The transport will be from Cusco to Soraypampa and   from Ollantaytambo to Cusco at the end of our trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Pick up from the hotel.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Our service includes pick   up from your&nbsp;hotel&nbsp;to start the tour, pick up time will be confirmed   according to the location of your hotel, at the end of the tour we will   also leave you back at your hotel.&nbsp;(Our service does not include pick up   from&nbsp;AIRBNB&nbsp;type houses&nbsp;because many do not have a clear name or   address), in that case we will coordinate a place and time to pick up.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Snacks</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; beside the breakfast, we will provide you   snacks every morning so that you can take you along the way. We will   also provide snack bags that are made of cloth, we are very careful with   the environment so we try not to take anything plastic to the route and   if we do, we bring it back.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Train Tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;The train ticket included is the   Inca Rail the Voyager service, however, on the way you can make an Up   Grade to a 360 &deg; train that has windows on the roof to enjoy the   beautiful views on the road.&nbsp;This has an additional cost of $.&nbsp;$&nbsp;65&nbsp;per   person&nbsp;up to Poroy&nbsp;and is subject to availability. Poroy station is 30   minutes out of Cusco, we will still include the transfer to your hotel.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Bus tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; It is 25 minutes from the Town to Machu Picchu and 25 minutes from Machu Picchu to the town.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Entrance</strong> to Machu Picchu.&nbsp;We take care of providing   you with the entrance ticket to Machu Picchu and this will be giving to   you on the day of the tour, by your guide.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Porters:</strong>&nbsp;We include a personal porter, who is   responsible for carrying your travel bag with your personal items.&nbsp;There   is no additional fee for this.&nbsp;The night before we will give you your   duffel bag so that it is filled with the things you will need for the   trek.&nbsp;You will not have access to your duffle bag until you arrive at   your campsite at first night.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Hotel:</strong>&nbsp;Alternative&nbsp;excursions end at Machu Picchu   Pueblo.&nbsp;The last night is spent in a hotel in the village, instead of   camping.&nbsp;This 3-star hotel is included in the cost of the trek and is   based on a shared room.&nbsp;If you want to improve your hotel or prefer a   single room, you will have an additional cost.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Camping equipment:</strong>&nbsp;In Peru Private Tours we have   the best equipment.&nbsp;We use a 4 people tent only between 2 people so you   will have more space to put your belongings inside your tent during the   night.&nbsp;You will have a large tent&nbsp;to enjoy your meals as well as chairs   and table.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Food:</strong>&nbsp;4 breakfasts (the last included in the   hotel) 3 lunches and 3 dinners, all prepared by our professional walking   chef.&nbsp;Our professional chefs&nbsp;prepare delicious meals that many previous   hikers have commented on.&nbsp;We honor all dietary restrictions.&nbsp;Be sure to   remind your tour guide about any food restrictions at the beginning of   your walk (Breafing time).&nbsp;The food is typically served family   style.&nbsp;You will enjoy breakfast, lunch and dinner every day of the&nbsp;trek,   with a delicious happy hour every afternoon before dinner.&nbsp;You will   also be provided with a snack every morning, so that you can enjoy the   walk.&nbsp;Your last&nbsp;meal with your chef will be&nbsp;breakfast on day four&nbsp;since   lunch and dinner will be at a restaurant.&nbsp;Lunch on the last day&nbsp;(day   04)&nbsp;is not included.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Water:</strong>&nbsp;from your first lunch until your last   breakfast,&nbsp;PPT&nbsp;will provide you with all the necessary water.&nbsp;This water   will be boiled, filtered and then cooled, before distribution.&nbsp;You must   supply your own bottles of water or camelback.&nbsp;We recommend carrying   around 3L.&nbsp;We will fill our waters at every meal.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>First aid:</strong>&nbsp;each of our guides has received training   in first aid from a doctor.&nbsp;We hold mandatory training sessions every   February, to which all the guides must attend.&nbsp;Your tour guide will   always have a first aid kit for basic medical problems (traveler&rsquo;s   diarrhea, cuts, scratches, etc.) and oxygen tank.&nbsp;We will get you out of   the way as quickly and comfortably as possible if necessary, and we   will make sure you go directly to a clinic to receive treatment.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Extras:</strong>&nbsp;We believe that it is the attention to   small details that differentiates us from other travel companies.&nbsp;Each   hiker receives a small pillow for sleeping, a sponge mats to isolate   (Matra), a backpack covers to protect your belongings during the trek, a   rain poncho and a waterproof plastic bags to put your belongings before   placing them in the duffle bag. We will work hard to create your best   vacations.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Private transfer from Ollantaytambo to Cusco.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;   Upon arrival at the Ollantaytambo train station our staff will be   waiting for you with a van only for our group to transfer you to   your&nbsp;hotel in Cusco or Sacred Valley.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Permanent Assistance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We want all the activities   you do in our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so you   will always have an&nbsp;assigned&nbsp;personal assistant&nbsp;who will be in constant   communication with you.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <h3>Not included</h3>\r\n  <p>All travelers need a sleeping bag, do not forget to bring your   own.&nbsp;The walking sticks and air mattresses or matras are optional and   provides greater comfort during the walk.&nbsp;If you do not want to bring   any camping gear you can always rent from our office.</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Sleeping bag: $.&nbsp;20 USD per person</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>Air&nbsp;Mattress: $.&nbsp;20 USD per person</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>Walking sticks (01 pair): $.&nbsp;USD 15 per person</strong></p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Headlamps:</strong> it&nbsp;is strongly recommended to bring a   head lamp for the evenings.&nbsp;There will be no lights on the camping sites   and it will be difficult to get to your dining tent or bathroom tent   without one.&nbsp;Hand lanterns are acceptable, if you do not have a head   lamp, but it makes some tasks difficult.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Huayna Picchu</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;Huayna Picchu is the mountain that   is seen behind Machu Picchu in the classic photos, to go up this   mountain you need to buy an additional entrance and it has a cost of   $.&nbsp;35 dollars per person, however,&nbsp;this entrance must be requested at   the time of your reservation and it will be confirmed according to   availability of spaces as they only allow 200 people.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Flights.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;Flying to Cusco can be   complicated.&nbsp;Delays occur frequently especially between October to March   and it is not uncommon for flights to be canceled.&nbsp;Make sure you arrive   in the city at least two days before the start date of your trek to   Machu Picchu.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;is the most reliable airline.&nbsp;Avianca and Peruvian   Airlines&nbsp;are also acceptable companies.&nbsp;You will not return from your   tour on the last day until around 8 pm So make sure your flight is not   the day of the Machu Picchu Tour, rather the next day.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tips</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Tips are always appreciated and should be   based entirely on your level of satisfaction.&nbsp;Although it may not be   usual for you, it has considerable importance to the people who will   assist you during your trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Travel insurance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; To protect your travel   investment, we recommend the purchase&nbsp;a travel insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel   insurance before leaving home is highly recommended and very   easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending on your country of   origin and at different prices according to your time of stay, take some   time to review them and hire the one that best suits you.&nbsp;This is an   excellent way to protect yourself while visiting&nbsp;Peru.</li>\r\n  </ul>', '  <h3>Breafing (Previous Information)</h3>\r\n  <p>All information sessions are held in our office at 06:00 PM the night   before your trek.&nbsp;If you cannot assist to this talk please contact our   office staff to serve you better.</p>\r\n  <h3>Duffle Bags</h3>\r\n  <p>You will receive your duffle bag at the information session.&nbsp;These   bags are to put your belongings inside it, these will be carried by the   porters and will be returned to you each evening at the   campsite.&nbsp;However, beside from these bags, you should carry a small   backpack where you will carry everything you need during the trek.</p>\r\n  <p>Each duffle bag must have a maximum weight of 7kg.&nbsp;4kg will be for   your clothes and other personal items, the other 3kg will be for our   logistics, such as your sleeping bag and pad, if you have your own   sleeping bag and mat these must be included in the 7 kilos.</p>\r\n  <h3>Arrive in Cusco</h3>\r\n  <p>The airport in Cusco&nbsp;is currently&nbsp;quite small and only for domestic   flights, so all international travelers by plane must disembark   in&nbsp;Lima&nbsp;and go through Customs.&nbsp;Even if your flight to&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is the same   day by the same airline, you must pick up your bags in Lima and then   register them again.</p>\r\n  <p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline   options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it   has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU,   LC PERU&nbsp;to choose according to your preference.&nbsp;Expect&nbsp;flight delays or   cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult   to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.&nbsp;Bus   tours&nbsp;are always available and although the journey may be long,   especially from&nbsp;Lima,&nbsp;Peru buses&nbsp;are well maintained and are   comfortable.&nbsp;This option is recommended if you come from a city closer   to&nbsp;Cusco like Puno or Arequipa.&nbsp;Buses from Lima will take around 20   hours to arrive to Cusco.</p>\r\n  <h3>Pick Up from The Hotels.</h3>\r\n  <p>We pick up all our clients from the hotel for all tours.&nbsp;While your   hotel is in the center of the city of Cusco, we will coordinate this   pick up&nbsp;with the&nbsp;guide at the information session.&nbsp;Pick-up&nbsp;times&nbsp;may   vary between 20 and 30&nbsp;minutes depending on traffic conditions and   hotel&nbsp;locations.</p>\r\n  <p>Cusco is an ancient city with cobblestone streets and very narrow   corridors.&nbsp;Very small hotels and Air BNBs are often located on streets   that cars cannot pass through.&nbsp;They are also usually located on the side   of the hill, with long and steep climbs to the property, difficult to   maneuver with luggage.&nbsp;We recommend that you do not&nbsp;stay in one of these   places and try to find places where there is easy access to carry your   bags.</p>\r\n  <h3>Leaving Machu Picchu requires a lot of logistics,&nbsp;but&nbsp;everything&nbsp;is&nbsp;included in your journey.</h3>\r\n  <p>From Machu Picchu&nbsp;Ruins&nbsp;to&nbsp;Machu Picchu Pueblo, you&nbsp;will take a   25-minute bus.&nbsp;The&nbsp;buses are in order of arrival and you can take any of   those in turn.</p>\r\n  <p>From Machu Picchu Pueblo,&nbsp;you will take a&nbsp;train&nbsp;to&nbsp;Ollantaytambo or   Poroy&nbsp;station.&nbsp;Your guide will give you your train tickets.&nbsp;Make sure   you get to the platform 30 minutes ahead of time.</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Ollantaytambo is 2 hours.</li>\r\n    <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Poroy is 3.5 hours.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>Once you arrive at the train station, look&nbsp;for our staff with a PPT sign.&nbsp;He&nbsp;will take you to the Plaza San Francisco, Cusco.</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>The trip on&nbsp;the van&nbsp;from Ollantaytambo to Plaza de San Francisco is 2 hours</li>\r\n    <li>Travel by&nbsp;van&nbsp;from Poroy to&nbsp;San Francisco Plaza is&nbsp;30 minutes</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>Once you arrive at the Plaza San Francisco&nbsp;our staff will be waiting   for you to separate you and send in pre-paid taxis to your respective   hotels.</p>\r\n  <h3>Entrance fees to Machu Picchu</h3>\r\n  <p>Machu Picchu now has two&nbsp;hours&nbsp;to visit: morning or afternoon.&nbsp;Your   ticket will be&nbsp;for a single&nbsp;entry,&nbsp;in the morning, once your time is   done, the&nbsp;guards will ask&nbsp;you&nbsp;to&nbsp;leave.</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Morning turn: 6AM &ndash; 12PM</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>Afternoon turn: 12PM &ndash; 5:30 PM</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>NOTE:</strong>&nbsp;If you have tickets to&nbsp;climb to Huayna Picchu   or Machu Picchu Mountain, you will have additional time until 2:30   PM.&nbsp;And you can re-enter for a single time as long as it is within the   time of re-entry (05 hours from the first entry)</p>\r\n  <p>If you want&nbsp;to&nbsp;spend all day at Machu Picchu, we can add a ticket&nbsp;for   the&nbsp;afternoon&nbsp;group&nbsp;to your reservation for $ 50 per person.</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Huayna Picchu / Machu Picchu Mountain</strong></p>\r\n  <p>Machu Picchu is more beautiful when viewed from above, so it is very   popular to hike one of the mountains next to the ruins after your guided   tour.</p>\r\n  <p>Huayna Picchu is the most popular and must be booked in advance &hellip; it   sells very fast.&nbsp;This hike takes approximately&nbsp;50&nbsp;minutes to the top   and&nbsp;40&nbsp;minutes downhill to the bottom.&nbsp;There are 2 schedules or groups   to enter this mountain.&nbsp;The first group&nbsp;is 8-p am and&nbsp;the second&nbsp;is 10   am to 11 am.&nbsp;Again, this refers to when you can start your hike and   normally we reserve the second&nbsp;option&nbsp;so you can first enjoy your tour   with your guide&nbsp;in Machu Picchu.&nbsp;This walk will be&nbsp;done&nbsp;on your own, but   your guide will show you where to start.</p>\r\n  <p>The Machu Picchu mountain is a little longer and less popular.&nbsp;It   takes&nbsp;2&nbsp;hours to reach the top&nbsp;and 1.5&nbsp;hours to reach the bottom.&nbsp;There   are also 2 visiting hours: from 7-8 am and from 9 am to 10 am and we   usually buy&nbsp;for the second group.</p>\r\n  <h3>Health Concerns</h3>\r\n  <p>It is important that you be honest with your guide about any health   problems you may suffer.&nbsp;Although the guides are not medical   professionals, they are trained in first aid.&nbsp;We also work with a clinic   in Cusco that can help our team.</p>\r\n  <p>You are responsible for evaluating if a trek is suitable for you.&nbsp;You   should consult your doctor to confirm your physical condition to travel   and participate in any planned activity.&nbsp;You should seek advice from   your doctor about vaccinations and medical precautions.&nbsp;Peru Private   Tours will&nbsp;not provide medical advice.&nbsp;It is your responsibility to   assess the risks and requirements of each aspect of the Tour based on   your own circumstances, limitations, fitness level and medical   requirements.</p>\r\n  <p>If during the trek you get sick of extreme altitude or any other   illness that not allows you to continuing with the journey, but you want   to visit Machu Picchu by train, we will work with you to coordinate   this trip.&nbsp;This will be a new trip and may involve additional costs.&nbsp;We   will use as much of the logistics purchased from the original route to   keep rates low.</p>\r\n  <p>If you experience problems while walking and cannot continue, a   porter will escort you to the nearest road and wait while a car comes to   pick you up and take you to the nearest health clinic.</p>\r\n  <h3>Group trips</h3>\r\n  <p>Group tours are made up of different types of people, with different   walking skills and ages.&nbsp;By accepting a group trip, you understand that   some people may be slower or faster than you.&nbsp;Everyone can make their   own pace for the walk, the guide will work through the group to spend   time with everyone.&nbsp;Groups can request some modifications to the tour   and&nbsp;the&nbsp;guide will work with everyone to make the best decision for the   group.</p>\r\n  <h3>Strikes</h3>\r\n  <p>Unfortunately, strikes are very common in Peru and can cause many   interruptions in our Tours.&nbsp;Roads are often blocked, trains stopped.&nbsp;We   will do everything possible to operate your Tour, even before the&nbsp;start   date.&nbsp;Some tours may&nbsp;be canceled under these circumstances.&nbsp;Our   Operations Department will coordinate with you in this situation.&nbsp;Your   safety is always our main concern and will determine how we decide.</p>\r\n  <h3>Lost Items</h3>\r\n  <p>You are responsible for your personal items throughout the Tour.&nbsp;Be   diligent about where&nbsp;you&nbsp;leave your stuff and remember&nbsp;to&nbsp;remove all   items from our vans,&nbsp;tents, restaurant, etc.&nbsp;Do not leave anything   involuntary while walking.&nbsp;Other hikers or teams can pick it up without   knowing to whom it belongs.</p>\r\n  <h3>Weather</h3>\r\n  <p>The climate in Cusco and Machu Picchu&nbsp;is unpredictable.&nbsp;In general,   the dry season in&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is from April to October, but this does not   prevent the rain from falling in June or the sun coming out in December,   just prepare for any weather condition.&nbsp;No matter which month you take   the hike or excursion, or which tour you are on, make sure you have   adequate clothing that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho and   waterproof gloves.</p>\r\n  <p>Also be prepared for&nbsp;four seasons in a day.&nbsp;Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a warm jacket.</p>\r\n  <h3>Altitude sickness</h3>\r\n  <p>As soon as the&nbsp;people reserve the trip to&nbsp;Peru, specifically   to&nbsp;Cusco, they begin to wonder about&nbsp;altitude sickness.&nbsp;High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.&nbsp;For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least&nbsp;amount of oxygen in the air.</p>\r\n  <p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p>\r\n  <p>Most of the time, these symptoms will be mild.&nbsp;We always recommend   easy activities and walk&nbsp;slowly, allowing your body to adapt.&nbsp;Drink   plenty of fluids such as water or coca tea.&nbsp;Coca tea&nbsp;has been used since   ancient times to help prevent&nbsp;altitude&nbsp;sickness.&nbsp;The leaves&nbsp;of the coca   plant&nbsp;contain alkaloids that help carry oxygen to the blood, helping   your body avoid the effects of altitude sickness.&nbsp;Avoid drinking a lot   of alcohol and coffee because it will make you urinate more often and   you will become dehydrated.&nbsp;Avoid smoking,&nbsp;Smoking makes it difficult   for your body to get oxygen.&nbsp;Avoid sleeping pills.&nbsp;They can cause   shallow breathing at night, which makes it difficult for your body to   absorb oxygen while you sleep.</p>\r\n  <p>Many people prefer to visit the doctor to give them a treatment with   pills even before traveling to avoid problems during their stay.&nbsp;Your   doctor&nbsp;may prescribe medications, such   as&nbsp;acetazolamide&nbsp;and&nbsp;dexamethasone, to&nbsp;help&nbsp;prevent altitude   sickness.&nbsp;Start the medicine two days before reaching a high   altitude.&nbsp;Continue taking it while you are at high altitude.</p>\r\n  <h3>Travel insurance</h3>\r\n  <p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying&nbsp;travel   insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending   on your country of origin and at different prices&nbsp;according to your time   of stay, take some time to review them and hire the one that best suits   you.&nbsp;This is an excellent way to&nbsp;protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>\r\n  <h3>Community</h3>\r\n  <p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our   community. This is&nbsp;the&nbsp;main&nbsp;objective&nbsp;for our company.&nbsp;We are   working&nbsp;directly with the villages to help them meet the needs of their   families.&nbsp;We support the children of the villages by giving them&nbsp;school   supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and clothes.</p>\r\n  <p>We buy all our food from farmers and local markets and serve the   freshest ingredients.&nbsp;We offer&nbsp;constant training&nbsp;for all our team:   guides, porters, chefs and drivers.&nbsp;We are a family born in the Andes   and we want to work with them and for them.&nbsp;That is why once&nbsp;a year we   bring our porters and their families to&nbsp;Machu&nbsp;Picchu.&nbsp;We want our team   to know the world wonder, since they work tirelessly at the doors of   this place without ever visiting it and&nbsp;showing them this place is our   greatest honor.</p>', '', 'salkantay-trek', 0, '', 0, 0, 499.00, 0, '4 days / 3 nights', 0, 0, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"94789504\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=94789504\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 7, 4),
(13, 'Palcoyo Mountain Tour', 'We do the Palcoyo mountain tour in a completely different way than any other company, allowing you to enjoy this spectacular attraction with no one else at the top, it will be an experience that you will never ever forget.', 'Did you know? By booking this tour you are planting 1 tree in an indigenous community of Cusco', '90% of the people that do the Palcoyo Mountain tour daily, go in the morning. At the moment, Peru Private Tours is Cusco’s only travel agency that provides afternoon tours to the mountain.', '<p>90% of the people that do the <strong>Palcoyo Mountain tour</strong> daily, go in the morning. </p>\r\n<p>At the moment, <strong>Peru Private Tours</strong> is <strong>Cusco&rsquo;s</strong> only travel agency that provides <strong>afternoon tours to the mountain</strong>. </p>\r\n<p>Unlike other times of the day, once we get to the top we will be able to enjoy the splendor of <strong>Palcoyo Mountain</strong> almost entirely in private. See the gallery of beautiful images we captured of this <strong>experience.</strong></p>', '  <h3>What our Palcoyo Mountain Tour includes and what not.</h3>\r\n  <h3>INCLUDED</h3>\r\n  <h3><strong>Professional Guide</strong></h3>\r\n  <p>We have the best selection of guides, all graduated in the national   university of Cusco and grown up in this region with a deep love and   passion for teaching their culture. They are fun but professional and   will make sure you are safe and happy. In addition, they are well   trained in first aid and carry an oxygen tank if necessary because of   the high altitude in the Palcoyo Mountain Tour.</p>\r\n  <h3><strong>Tourist transportation</strong></h3>\r\n  <p>We use clean and new vehicles for all our services, with professional drivers that guarantees you a safe trip.</p>\r\n  <h3><strong>Buffet Lunch.</strong></h3>\r\n  <p>We will have a buffet lunch after our journey to Palcoyo Mountain Tour.</p>\r\n  <h3><strong>&nbsp;Pick up from the hotel</strong></h3>\r\n  <p>Our service includes picking up from your hotel to start the tour,   pick up time will be confirmed according to the location of your hotel,   at the end of the tour we will also leave you back at your hotel.</p>\r\n  <h3><strong>Permanent Assistance</strong></h3>\r\n  <p>We want all the activities you do in our destination to be unique,   unforgettable and safe, so you will always have an&nbsp;assigned&nbsp;personal   assistant&nbsp;who will be in constant communication with you in case you   need something.</p>\r\n  <h3>NOT INCLUDED</h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Tips</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;The&nbsp;tips for your crew are voluntary and according to your satisfaction level.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Horses. &ndash;&nbsp;</strong>In this hike, there is no horses for rent.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Entrance tickets.- </strong>The cost its S/. 20.00 soles per person</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Walking sticks. &ndash;&nbsp;</strong>If you want to rent a pair of walking sticks there is an extra $. 5 usd cost, please let us now at your booking time</li>\r\n  </ul>', '<h3>What to bring for the Palcoyo mountain tour</h3>\r\n<p>Please take note of these recommendations to do the Rainbow Mountain Tour.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li><strong>PASSPORT OR IDENTITY DOCUMENT</strong>&nbsp;(VERY IMPORTANT)</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Hat or cap for the sun:</strong>&nbsp;Very important for the walk, radiation is stronger on the rainbow mountain.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Sunglasses:</strong>&nbsp;Highly recommended.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Sunscreen:</strong>&nbsp;The radiation in the mountains is stronger, use&nbsp;sunscreen every day.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Waterproof jacket or windbreaker</strong>&nbsp;(if it is light much better)</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Gloves:</strong> Especially for when you are on the the Rainbow Mountain Viewpoint, because there it is very windy and cold.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Shoe with</strong> a <strong>good grip:</strong>&nbsp;If you have trekking shoe is much better</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Personal medication pills:</strong>&nbsp;Do not forget to take your personal medication that is very important.</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Others that you consider necessary.</strong>&nbsp;But remember that this&nbsp;is an ADVENTURE walk!</li>\r\n  <li><strong>Above all, a lot of desire to have fun, enjoy nature and learn about&nbsp;the local culture</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Altitude sickness in Palcoyo Mountain Tour</h3>\r\n<p>Consider that the highest elevation you will get in the Palcoyo   Mountain Tour its 4,900 meters above sea level, but as soon as you walk   10 minutes you will already be able to see the amazing views and   colorful mountains around you, however, consider the recommendations for   the tour.</p>\r\n<p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.   Our team is well trained on first aid assistance and specially on   altitude problems, if you feel any of the altitude symptoms mentioned   during your hike, please let your guide know so he or she will help you   as soon as possible.</p>\r\n<p>For further information about altitude sickness please read our article <a href=\"http://www.pptoursperu.com/altitud-sickness/\" target=\"_blank\">HERE.</a></p>\r\n<h3>Weather</h3>\r\n<p>The weather in the Palcoyo Mountain is unpredictable. Dry season in   Cusco is from April through October, but this does not prevent the rain   from falling in June or the sun coming out in December, just be prepared   for any weather.</p>\r\n<p>Many of the excursions through the Andes involve many microclimates   and you will have to be prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always   key because they are easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the   nights will always be cold, so get ready with a&nbsp;warm jacket.</p>\r\n<h3>Arriving to Cusco</h3>\r\n<p>The airport in Cusco&nbsp;is currently&nbsp;quite small and only for domestic   flights, so all international travelers by plane must disembark   in&nbsp;Lima&nbsp;and go through Customs.</p>\r\n<p>Even if your flight to&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is the same day by the same airline, you   must pick up your bags in Lima and then register them again.</p>\r\n<p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline options.&nbsp;LATAM tends to be the most expensive, but it has more flight options. But you   also have PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU to choose according to your   preference. Expect flight delays or cancellations, due to the high   altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult to land so that on rainy days   it can paralyze air traffic.</p>\r\n<p>Please consider at least 2 days of acclimatization before going to   the palcoyo mountain tour, this is especially high and doesn&rsquo;t matter   how fit you are, the altitude will affect you.Community</p>\r\n<p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our   community.&nbsp;This is&nbsp;the&nbsp;main&nbsp;objective&nbsp;for our company.&nbsp;We are   working&nbsp;directly with the villages to help them meet the needs of their   families.&nbsp;We support the children of the villages by giving them&nbsp;school   supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and clothes.</p>\r\n<p>PPT offers constant training for all our team. We are a family born   in the Andes and we want to work with them and for them. That is why   once a year we bring our porters and their families to Machu Picchu.</p>', '', 'palcoyo-mountain-tour', 0, 'Palcoyo, Cusipata', 0, 0, 119.00, 0, 'Full day', 2, 1, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"15499296\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=15499296\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 7, 2);
INSERT INTO `ProgramaPPT` (`Identificador`, `NombreIngles`, `MensajeIngles`, `MensajeSocialIngles`, `IntroduccionIngles`, `DescripcionIngles`, `IncluyeIngles`, `MasInformacionIngles`, `FAQIngles`, `Enlace`, `IdDestino`, `DestinosIngles`, `IdActividad`, `IdTipo`, `Precio`, `Duracion`, `DuracionIngles`, `Dificultad`, `EsPortada`, `OrdenPortada`, `CodigoWeTravel`, `CantidadImagenes`, `IdCategoria`) VALUES
(14, 'Humantay Lagoon Tour', 'This is a tour that requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend making the reservation in advance, once you make your reservation will be confirmed as long as there is availability of space for the date that you select, please make sure to check the availability of spaces for Inca trail 4 days', 'By booking this tour, you contribute to our reforestation efforts, supporting the planting of endemic trees', 'Nestled beneath Andean peaks, the Humantay Lagoon is an emerald gem reflecting the sky.', '<p>Nestled beneath Andean peaks, the Humantay Lagoon is an emerald gem   reflecting the sky.</p>\r\n<p>Surrounded by snow-capped mountains, this serene   lagoon whispers tales of ancient spirits and untouched beauty, offering a   tranquil sanctuary for those seeking nature&rsquo;s poetic splendor.</p>', '<h2><strong>Humantay Lagoon Tour: What&rsquo;s Included</strong></h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Hotel Pick-Up &amp; Drop-Off:</strong> Convenient transportation from and to your accommodation.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>All-Inclusive Transportation:</strong> Comfortable travel throughout the entire tour.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Professional Tour Guide:</strong> Expert guidance to enrich your experience.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Included Lunch:</strong> Enjoy a delicious meal after the hike.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Snack Pack:</strong> Refresh with a bottle of water, chocolate, Andean cereal, local fruit, and candies.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>First Aid Kit &amp; Oxygen:</strong> Available upon request to ensure your safety and comfort.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n  <h3><strong>Not included: Additional Costs:</strong></h3>\r\n              <ul>\r\n                <li><strong>Entrance Fee:</strong> A fee of 20 soles per person is required and must be paid directly at the entrance.</li>\r\n                <li><strong>Horse Riding:</strong> For those wishing to conserve energy   and enjoy a leisurely ride, horseback riding is available for 80 soles   per person for the uphill journey.</li>\r\n                <li><strong>Tips</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;The&nbsp;tips for your crew are voluntary and according to your satisfaction level.</li>\r\n              </ul>', '  <h3>What to Bring for the Humantay Lagoon Tour:</h3>\r\n  <p><strong>Please ensure you have the following items with you on the day of your tour:</strong></p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Sunscreen</strong>: To protect your skin from the high-altitude sun.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Sunhat</strong>: To shield your face from the sun.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Sunglasses</strong>: For eye protection.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Comfortable Hiking Shoes</strong>: Essential for the trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Warm Jacket:</strong> For the cooler afternoon temperatures.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Passports</strong>: Optional, but you can get a unique stamp as a keepsake.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Shoes with</strong> <strong>a</strong> <strong>good grip:</strong> If you have trekking shoes is much bette</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Personal medication pills:</strong> Do not forget to take your personal medication, most importantly the ones you take daily.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Others you consider necessary.</strong> However, remember that this is an ADVENTURE walk</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Above all, a lot of desire to have fun, enjoy nature and learn about&nbsp;the local culture</strong>.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <h3>Altitude sickness</h3>\r\n  <p>As soon as people reserve their trip to Peru, specifically to Cusco,   they often start to worry about altitude sickness. Higher altitudes have   less oxygen than at sea level, making your body work harder to get the   oxygen it needs.</p>\r\n  <p>During our<strong> Humantay Lake Tour</strong>, we always carry an   oxygen tank and a first aid kit. Our guides are well-trained to assist   you in case you experience any symptoms of altitude sickness. Rest   assured, your safety and well-being are our top priorities.</p>\r\n  <p>For farther information about altitude sickness please read our article <a href=\"http://www.pptoursperu.com/altitude-sickness/\" target=\"_blank\">HERE.</a></p>\r\n  <h3>Weather</h3>\r\n  <p>The weather at Humantay Lake is notoriously unpredictable. While   Cusco&rsquo;s dry season typically spans from April through October, rain can   still surprise you in June, and sunshine may brighten December. It&rsquo;s   best to be prepared for any weather.</p>\r\n  <p>Ensure you pack appropriate clothing, including a waterproof jacket, pants, and rain poncho.</p>\r\n  <p>Additionally, brace yourself for a potentially chilly day during the   Humantay lake Tour. At the summit, it can be both cold and windy, so   dress warmly to enjoy the breathtaking views comfortably.</p>\r\n  <h3>Arriving to Cusco</h3>\r\n  <p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU, LC PERU&nbsp;to choose according to your preference.</p>\r\n  <p>Expect&nbsp;flight delays or cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of   Cusco, tends to be difficult to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can   paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.</p>\r\n  <h3>Travel Insurance</h3>\r\n  <p>To safeguard your travel investment, we highly recommend purchasing   travel insurance. Obtaining coverage before your trip is straightforward   and essential. Various insurance providers offer plans tailored to your   country of origin and duration of stay. Take the time to review options   and choose the one that best fits your needs. This precaution ensures   peace of mind while visiting Peru.</p>\r\n  <h3>Community Commitment</h3>\r\n  <p>At Peru Private Tours (PPT), we take immense pride in our community   work, which is the cornerstone of our mission. We collaborate directly   with local villages to address their families&rsquo; needs, providing school   supplies, books, and clothing to children. Our team receives ongoing   training, reinforcing our commitment to the Andean community.   Additionally, for every booking, we plant a tree, contributing to   environmental sustainability. Thank you for supporting this meaningful   project.</p>', '', 'humantay-lagoon-tour', 0, 'Ausangate, Humantay', 0, 0, 89.00, 0, 'Full day', 3, 1, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"18022772\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=18022772\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 5, 2),
(15, 'Maras Moray Tour', 'This is a tour that requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend making the reservation in advance, once you make your reservation will be confirmed as long as there is availability of space for the date that you select, please make sure to check the availability of spaces for Inca trail 4 days.', 'By booking this tour your are planting 1 tree at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'Enjoy a guided tour of Maras, Moray, and the Salt Mines with a team of experts knowledgeable in the area’s history, geography, and cultural traditions.', '<p>Enjoy a guided tour of Maras, Moray, and the Salt Mines with a team of   experts knowledgeable in the area&rsquo;s history, geography, and cultural   traditions. This tour is ideal for those with an evening flight from   Cusco, starting at 6:00 PM, and offers a fantastic half-day option to   explore part of the Sacred Valley.</p>\r\n<p>You&rsquo;ll experience breathtaking views   of the Urubamba snow-capped peaks, Mount Veronica, and the lush green   valleys of the surrounding farms. During this half-day journey, you&rsquo;ll   gain insights into Incan agriculture, textiles, and history.</p>', '<h3>What Our Maras Moray Tour Includes</h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Professional</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Guide</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;We have the   best selection of guides, all graduates of the national university of   Cusco and grown up in this region with a deep love and passion for   teaching their culture.&nbsp;They are fun but professional and will make sure   you are safe and happy on your <strong>maras moray tour</strong>.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tourist transport.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We use clean and new vehicles   for all our services, with professional drivers that guarantee a safe   trip. Our drivers are constantly trained in prudent driving and customer   service.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Pick up from the hotel.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Our Maras Moray Tour   service includes pick up from your hotel to start the tour, pick up time   will be confirmed according to the location of your hotel, at the end   of the tour we will also leave you back at your hotel.&nbsp;(Our service does   not include AIRBNB house pickups because many of them do not have a   clear name or address).</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Permanent Assistance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We want you doing all the   activities at our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so   you will always have an assigned personal assistant who will be in   constant communication with you and will be there at the beginning and   end of every tour.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <h3>Not included</h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Entrance tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;Many of the&nbsp;archaeological   sites of Cusco&nbsp;and Sacred Valley&nbsp;accept the&nbsp;Tourist&nbsp;Ticket&nbsp;of Cusco   (BTC)&nbsp;that you can acquire in the first place of visit, we will help you   in the purchase, just be sure to take money in cash and in soles.&nbsp;There   are 2 types of tickets: The partial BTC that gives access only to the   places visited on this tour and has a cost of S /.&nbsp;70 soles per person   and it lasts for 2 days.&nbsp;The general BTC that gives access to   16&nbsp;attractions of Cusco&nbsp;including those visited in this tour, has a cost   of S /.&nbsp;130 soles per person and it lasts 10 days, if you also have a   tour to&nbsp;the Sacred Valley&nbsp;or Trips in Cusco,&nbsp;the second option is   better.&nbsp;However, the ticket to the&nbsp;Salt Mines&nbsp;has an additional cost of S   /.&nbsp;10 Soles per person that must be paid directly to tle locals.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <h3><strong>Tickets you must buy.</strong></h3>\r\n  <table width=\"100%\" border=\"1px\">\r\n    <tbody>\r\n      <tr>\r\n        <td>Tickets</td>\r\n        <td>Children&nbsp;up to 09 years and 11 months</td>\r\n        <td>Adults</td>\r\n      </tr>\r\n      <tr>\r\n        <td>Salt mines</td>\r\n        <td>They do not pay</td>\r\n        <td>15 soles</td>\r\n      </tr>\r\n      <tr>\r\n        <td>BTC For the&nbsp;ruins</td>\r\n        <td>They do not pay</td>\r\n        <td>70 soles&nbsp;valid&nbsp;for this tour.</td>\r\n      </tr>\r\n    </tbody>\r\n  </table>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Meals.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>&ndash;</strong>&nbsp;Our   Maras Moray Tour does not have food included so you must eat before   starting the tour or at the end depending your tour start time.</li>\r\n  </ul>', '  <h2>Useful information</h2>\r\n  <h3>Altitude sickness</h3>\r\n  <p>As soon as the&nbsp;people reserve the trip to&nbsp;Peru, specifically   to&nbsp;Cusco, they begin to wonder about&nbsp;altitude sickness.&nbsp;High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.&nbsp;For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least&nbsp;amount of oxygen in the air.</p>\r\n  <p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p>\r\n  <p>for farther information about altitude sickness check out our blog <a href=\"http://www.pptoursperu.com/altitude-sickness\" target=\"_blank\">HERE</a></p>\r\n  <h3>Weather</h3>\r\n  <p>The weather in Cusco&nbsp;it&rsquo;s unpredictable.&nbsp;In general, the dry season   in&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is from April through October, but this does not prevent the   rain from falling in June or the sun coming out in December, just be   prepared&nbsp;for any weather.&nbsp;No matter which month you take the hike&nbsp;or   excursion, or which tour you are on, make sure you   have&nbsp;adequate&nbsp;clothing&nbsp;that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho   and waterproof gloves.</p>\r\n  <p>Also prepare&nbsp;for&nbsp;four seasons in a day.&nbsp;Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a&nbsp;warm jacket.</p>\r\n  <h3>Arrive in Cusco</h3>\r\n  <p>The airport in Cusco&nbsp;is currently&nbsp;quite small and only for domestic   flights, so all international travelers by plane must disembark   in&nbsp;Lima&nbsp;and go through Customs.&nbsp;Even if your flight to&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is the same   day by the same airline, you must pick up your bags in Lima and then   register them again.</p>\r\n  <p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU,&nbsp;   to choose according to your preference.&nbsp;Expect&nbsp;flight delays or   cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult   to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.&nbsp;Bus   tours&nbsp;are always available and although the journey may be long,   especially from&nbsp;Lima,&nbsp;Peru buses&nbsp;are well maintained and are   comfortable.&nbsp;This option is recommended if you come from a city closer   to&nbsp;Cusco like Puno or Arequipa.&nbsp;Buses from Lima will take around 20   hours to arrive to Cusco.</p>\r\n  <h3>Exchange rate</h3>\r\n  <p>If you come to visit&nbsp;Peru,&nbsp;try to exchange your local currency for   dollars.&nbsp;If you arrive at the&nbsp;Jorge Ch&aacute;vez airport in Lima&nbsp;without   dollars, there is a foreign currency exchange office inside the   Lima&nbsp;Airport&nbsp;Partners, there you can&nbsp;change: (US dollars, CAD dollars,   euros, yen, pounds sterling, pesos from almost all countries in&nbsp;Latin   America), change the necessary amount of dollars that allows you to have   enough soles to settle, then try to change more dollars per soles in   physical exchange houses that are safer and offer you a better exchange   rate.&nbsp;However, if you are coming directly to&nbsp;Cusco,&nbsp;there are many money   exchange houses at Sol. Avenue where you can buy the local currency   more safely.</p>\r\n  <p>For farther info about money exchange check out our blog HERE</p>\r\n  <h3>Travel insurance</h3>\r\n  <p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying&nbsp;travel   insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending   on your country of origin and at different prices&nbsp;according to your time   of stay, take some time to review them and hire the one that best suits   you.&nbsp;This is an excellent way to&nbsp;protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>\r\n  <h3>Community</h3>\r\n  <p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our   community.&nbsp;This is&nbsp;the&nbsp;main&nbsp;objective&nbsp;for our company.&nbsp;We are   working&nbsp;directly with the villages to help them meet the needs of their   families.&nbsp;We support the children of the villages by giving them&nbsp;school   supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and clothes.</p>\r\n  <p>We buy all our food from farmers and local markets and serve the   freshest ingredients.&nbsp;We offer&nbsp;constant training&nbsp;for all our team:   guides, porters, chefs and drivers.&nbsp;We are a family born in the Andes   and we want to work with them and for them.&nbsp;That is why once&nbsp;a year we   bring our porters and their families to&nbsp;Machu&nbsp;Picchu.&nbsp;We want our team   to know the world wonder, since they work tirelessly at the doors of   this place without ever visiting it and&nbsp;showing them this place is our   greatest honor.</p>', '', 'maras-moray-tour', 0, '', 0, 0, 59.00, 0, 'Half day', 0, 0, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"82464172\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=82464172\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 7, 2),
(16, 'City Tour Cusco + 4 Nearby Inca Ruins', 'We recive bookings for this tour until 2 hours before the start time of the tour whenever it is a group tour, for a private tour you must do your booking at least 4 hours in advance, before paying the tour please make sure to contact our office staff.', 'By booking this tour your are planting 1 tree at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'Cusco is the center of the Inca history and the oldest inhabited city in South America, South America’s archeological capital   and the most cosmopolitan city in Peru.', '<p><strong>Cusco</strong>&nbsp;is the center of the&nbsp;<strong>Inca</strong>&nbsp;history&nbsp;and&nbsp;the oldest inhabited&nbsp;city&nbsp;in&nbsp;South America,&nbsp;South <strong>America&rsquo;s archeological capital</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;and the most cosmopolitan city in&nbsp;Peru. Exploring it with a member of the&nbsp;<strong>Peru Private Tours (PPT)</strong> team will help bring this period of history to life. </p>\r\n<p>Visit the beautiful&nbsp;<strong>Cathedral in the Main Square,</strong> the&nbsp;<strong>Temple of the Sun</strong>&nbsp;and then drive to the city limits to visit the 4 main Inca ruins, including&nbsp;<strong>Sacsayhuaman.</strong>&nbsp;A <strong>City Tour in Cusco,</strong> it is perfect start to your visit to&nbsp;<strong>Machu Picchu</strong>&nbsp;and your experience with the&nbsp;<strong>Andean culture.</strong></p>', '<h3>What our Cusco tour Includes</h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Professional</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Guide</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;We have the   best selection of guides, all graduated from the national university of   Cusco and grown up in this region with a deep love and passion for   teaching their culture.&nbsp;They are fun but professional and will make sure   you are safe and happy on our cusco tour.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Tourist transport.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We use clean and new vehicles   for all our services and our cusco excursion is not the exception, with   professional drivers that guarantee you a safe trip. Our drivers are   constantly trained in prudent driving and customer service.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Pick up from the hotel.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Our cusco jount service   includes pick up from your hotel to start the tour, pick up time will be   confirmed according to the location of your hotel, at the end of the   tour we will also leave you back at your hotel.&nbsp;(Our service does not   include AIRBNB house pickups because many of them do not have a clear   name or address, we will coordinate pick up plce and time).</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Permanent Assistance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We want you doing all the   activities at our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so   you will always have an assigned personal assistant who will be in   constant communication with you and will be there at the beginning and   end of every tour.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <h3>Not included</h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Entrance tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;Many of the&nbsp;archaeological   sites of Cusco&nbsp;and Sacred Valley&nbsp;accept the&nbsp;Tourist&nbsp;Ticket&nbsp;of Cusco   (BTC)&nbsp;that can be acquired in the first place of visit and we will help   you in the purchase, just be sure to take money in cash and in soles.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>There are 2 types of tickets: The partial BTC that gives access only   to the places visited on this tour and has a cost of S /. 70 soles per   person and it lasts for only 1 day. The general BTC that gives access to   16 attractions in Cusco including those we visit in this tour, has a   cost of S /. 130 soles per person and it lasts 10 days, if you also have   a tour to the Sacred Valley the second option is better. However, the   entrances to the Cathedral of Cusco and Coricancha (the temple of the   sun) have a separate cost of 25 and 15 soles respectively.</p>\r\n  <h3><strong>Tickets you must buy.</strong></h3>\r\n  <table width=\"100%\" border=\"1px\">\r\n    <tbody>\r\n      <tr>\r\n        <td>Tickets</td>\r\n        <td>Chibldren&nbsp;up to<strong> 09</strong> years and 11 months</td>\r\n        <td>Adults</td>\r\n      </tr>\r\n      <tr>\r\n        <td>Cathedral</td>\r\n        <td>12.50 soles</td>\r\n        <td>40 soles</td>\r\n      </tr>\r\n      <tr>\r\n        <td>Qoricancha</td>\r\n        <td>10 soles</td>\r\n        <td>25 soles</td>\r\n      </tr>\r\n      <tr>\r\n        <td>BTC For 4 ruins</td>\r\n        <td>They do not pay</td>\r\n        <td><strong>70</strong> soles&nbsp;valid&nbsp;for this tour.</td>\r\n      </tr>\r\n    </tbody>\r\n  </table>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Meals.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>&ndash;</strong>&nbsp;Our cusco tour does not   have food included so you must eat before starting the tour or at the   end of it, depending on the start time of the tour.</li>\r\n  </ul>', '<h2>Useful information</h2>\r\n<h3>Altitude sickness</h3>\r\n<p>As soon as the&nbsp;people reserve the trip to&nbsp;Peru, specifically   to&nbsp;Cusco, they begin to wonder about&nbsp;altitude sickness.&nbsp;High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.&nbsp;For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least&nbsp;amount of oxygen in the air.</p>\r\n<p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p>\r\n<p>for farther information about altitude sickness real our blog <a href=\"http://www.pptoursperu.com/altitude-sickness\" target=\"_blank\">HERE</a></p>\r\n<h3>Weather</h3>\r\n<p>The weather in Cusco&nbsp;it&rsquo;s unpredictable.&nbsp;In general, the dry season   in&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is from April through October, but this does not prevent the   rain from falling in June or the sun coming out in December, just be   prepared&nbsp;for any weather.&nbsp;No matter which month you take the hike&nbsp;or   excursion, or which tour you are on, make sure you   have&nbsp;adequate&nbsp;clothing&nbsp;that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho   and waterproof gloves.</p>\r\n<p>Also prepare&nbsp;for&nbsp;four seasons in a day.&nbsp;Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a&nbsp;warm jacket.</p>\r\n<h3>Arrive in Cusco</h3>\r\n<p>The airport in Cusco&nbsp;is currently&nbsp;quite small and only for domestic   flights, so all international travelers by plane must disembark   in&nbsp;Lima&nbsp;and go through Customs.&nbsp;Even if your flight to&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is the same   day by the same airline, you must pick up your bags in Lima and then   register them again.</p>\r\n<p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU,to   choose according to your preference.&nbsp;Expect&nbsp;flight delays or   cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult   to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days they can paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.&nbsp;Bus   tours&nbsp;are always available and although the journey may be long,   especially from&nbsp;Lima,&nbsp;Peru buses&nbsp;are well maintained and are   comfortable.&nbsp;This option is recommended if you come from a city closer   to&nbsp;Cusco like Puno or Arequipa.&nbsp;Buses from Lima will take around 20   hours to arrive to Cusco.</p>\r\n<h3>Exchange rate</h3>\r\n<p>If you come to visit&nbsp;Peru,&nbsp;try to exchange your local currency to   dollars.&nbsp;If you arrive at the&nbsp;Jorge Ch&aacute;vez airport in Lima&nbsp;without   dollars, there is a foreign currency exchange office inside the   Lima&nbsp;Airport&nbsp;Partners, there you can&nbsp;change: (US dollars, CAD dollars,   euros, yen, pounds sterling, pesos from almost all countries in&nbsp;Latin   America), change the necessary amount of dollars that allows you to have   enough soles to settle, then try to change more dollars per soles in   physical exchange houses that are safer and offer you a better exchange   rate.&nbsp;However, if you are coming directly to&nbsp;Cusco,&nbsp;there are many money   exchange houses at Sol. Avenue where you can buy the local currency   more safely.</p>\r\n<h3>Travel insurance</h3>\r\n<p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying&nbsp;travel   insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending   on your country of origin and at different prices&nbsp;according to your time   of stay, take some time to review them and hire the one that best suits   you.&nbsp;This is an excellent way to&nbsp;protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>\r\n<h3>Community</h3>\r\n<p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our   community.&nbsp;This is&nbsp;the&nbsp;main&nbsp;objective&nbsp;for our company.&nbsp;We are   working&nbsp;directly with the villages to help them meet the needs of their   families.&nbsp;We support the children of the villages by giving them&nbsp;school   supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and clothes.</p>', '', 'city-tour-cusco', 0, '', 0, 0, 35.00, 0, 'Half day', 0, 0, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"86781829\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=86781829\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 7, 2);
INSERT INTO `ProgramaPPT` (`Identificador`, `NombreIngles`, `MensajeIngles`, `MensajeSocialIngles`, `IntroduccionIngles`, `DescripcionIngles`, `IncluyeIngles`, `MasInformacionIngles`, `FAQIngles`, `Enlace`, `IdDestino`, `DestinosIngles`, `IdActividad`, `IdTipo`, `Precio`, `Duracion`, `DuracionIngles`, `Dificultad`, `EsPortada`, `OrdenPortada`, `CodigoWeTravel`, `CantidadImagenes`, `IdCategoria`) VALUES
(17, 'Inca Jungle Adventure', 'This is a tour that requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend making the reservation in advance, once you make your reservation will be confirmed as long as there is availability of space for the date that you select, please make sure to check the availability of spaces for Inca trail 4 days.', 'By booking this tour your are planting 1 tree at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'Inca Jungle Adventure is an excellent alternative to all adventure hikes, recommended for young people with a strong desire to live a unique adventure in life.', '<p><strong>Inca Jungle Adventure&nbsp;</strong>is an excellent alternative to   all adventure hikes, recommended for young people with a strong desire   to live a unique adventure in life.</p>\r\n<p>It is the only one that combines   hiking, biking, rafting and Zipline.&nbsp;With our expert team specialized in   this type of activities you will live a fantastic and safe adventure experience.</p>', '  <h3>Included</h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Professional Guide</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;We have the best selection of   guides, all graduated from the national university of&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;and grown up   in this region with a deep love and passion for teaching our   culture.&nbsp;They are fun but professional and will make sure you are safe   and happy.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tourist transport.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We use clean and new vehicles   for all our services, with professional drivers that will guarantee you a   safe trip. Our drivers are constantly trained in prudent driving and   customer service.&nbsp;The transport will be from Cusco to Soraypampa and   from Ollantaytambo to Cusco at the end of our trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Pick</strong> up <strong>from the hotel.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Our   service includes pick up from your&nbsp;hotel&nbsp;to start the tour, pick up time   will be confirmed according to the location of your hotel, at the end   of the tour we will also leave you back at your hotel.&nbsp;(Our service does   not include pick up from&nbsp;AIRBNB&nbsp;type houses&nbsp;because many do not have a   clear name or address), in that case we will coordinate a place and time   to pick up.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Snacks</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; beside the breakfast, we will provide you   snacks every morning so that you can take you along the way. We will   also provide snack bags that are made of cloth, we are very careful with   the environment so we try not to take anything plastic to the route and   if we do, we bring it back.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Train Tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;The train ticket included is the   Inca Rail the Voyager service, however, on the way you can make an Up   Grade to a 360 &deg; train that has windows on the roof to enjoy the   beautiful views on the road.&nbsp;This has an additional cost of $.&nbsp;$&nbsp;65&nbsp;per   person&nbsp;up to Poroy&nbsp;and is subject to availability. Poroy station is 30   minutes out of Cusco, we will still include the transfer to your hotel.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Bus tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; It is 25 minutes from the Town to Machu Picchu and 25 minutes from Machu Picchu to the town.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Entrance</strong> to <strong>Machu Picchu.</strong>&nbsp;We take   care of providing you with the entrance ticket to Machu Picchu and this   will be giving to you on the day of the tour, by your guide.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Horses:</strong>&nbsp;We include horses and horseman who is   responsible for carrying your travel bag with your personal items.&nbsp;There   is no additional fee for this.&nbsp;The night before we will give you your   duffel bag so that it is filled with the things you will need for the   trek.&nbsp;You will not have access to your duffle bag until you arrive at   your campsite at first night.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Hotel:</strong>&nbsp;Alternative&nbsp;excursions end at Machu Picchu   Pueblo.&nbsp;The last night is spent in a hotel in the village, instead of   camping.&nbsp;This 3-star hotel is included in the cost of the trek and is   based on a shared room.&nbsp;If you want to improve your hotel or prefer a   single room, you will have an additional cost.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Camping equipment:</strong>&nbsp;In Peru Private Tours we have   the best equipment.&nbsp;We use a 4 people tent only between 2 people so you   will have more space to put your belongings inside your tent during the   night.&nbsp;You will have a large tent&nbsp;to enjoy your meals as well as chairs   and table.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Food:</strong>&nbsp;4 breakfasts (the last included in the hotel)   3 lunches and 3 dinners, all prepared by our professional walking   chef.&nbsp;Our professional chefs&nbsp;prepare delicious meals that many previous   hikers have commented on.&nbsp;We honor all dietary restrictions.&nbsp;Be sure to   remind your tour guide about any food restrictions at the beginning of   your walk (Breafing time).&nbsp;The food is typically served family   style.&nbsp;You will enjoy breakfast, lunch and dinner every day of the&nbsp;trek,   with a delicious happy hour every afternoon before dinner.&nbsp;You will   also be provided with a snack every morning, so that you can enjoy the   walk.&nbsp;Your last&nbsp;meal with your chef will be&nbsp;breakfast on day four&nbsp;since   lunch and dinner will be at a restaurant.&nbsp;Lunch on the last day&nbsp;(day   04)&nbsp;is not included.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Water:</strong>&nbsp;from your first lunch until your last   breakfast,&nbsp;PPT&nbsp;will provide you with all the necessary water.&nbsp;This water   will be boiled, filtered and then cooled, before distribution.&nbsp;You must   supply your own bottles of water or camelback.&nbsp;We recommend carrying   around 3L.&nbsp;We will fill our waters at every meal.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>First aid:</strong>&nbsp;each of our guides has received   training in first aid from a doctor.&nbsp;We hold mandatory training sessions   every February, to which all the guides must attend.&nbsp;Your tour guide   will always have a first aid kit for basic medical problems (traveler&rsquo;s   diarrhea, cuts, scratches, etc.) and oxygen tank.&nbsp;We will get you out of   the way as quickly and comfortably as possible if necessary, and we   will make sure you go directly to a clinic to receive treatment.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Extras:</strong>&nbsp;We believe that it is the attention to   small details that differentiates us from other travel companies.&nbsp;Each   hiker receives a small pillow for sleeping, a sponge mats to isolate   (Matra), a backpack covers to protect your belongings during the trek, a   rain poncho and a waterproof plastic bags to put your belongings before   placing them in the duffle bag. We will work hard to create your best   vacations.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Private transfer from Ollantaytambo</strong> to <strong>Cusco.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;   Upon arrival at the Ollantaytambo train station our staff will be   waiting for you with a van only for our group to transfer you to   your&nbsp;hotel in Cusco or Sacred Valley.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Permanent</strong> Assistance.&nbsp;&ndash; We want all the activities   you do in our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so you   will always have an&nbsp;assigned&nbsp;personal assistant&nbsp;who will be in constant   communication with you.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <h3>Not included</h3>\r\n  <p>All travelers need a sleeping bag, do not forget to bring your   own.&nbsp;The walking sticks and air mattresses or matras are optional and   provides greater comfort during the walk.&nbsp;If you do not want to bring   any camping gear you can always rent from our office.</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Sleeping bag: $.&nbsp;20 USD per person</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>Air&nbsp;Mattress: $.&nbsp;20 USD per person</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>Walking sticks (01 pair): $. 15 USD per person</strong></p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>headlamps:</strong> it&nbsp;is strongly recommended to bring a   head lamp for the evenings.&nbsp;There will be no lights on the camping sites   and it will be difficult to get to your dining tent or bathroom tent   without one.&nbsp;Hand lanterns are acceptable, if you do not have a head   lamp, but it makes some tasks difficult.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Huayna Picchu</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;<strong>Huayna Picchu</strong> is   the mountain that is seen behind Machu Picchu in the classic photos, to   go up this mountain you need to buy an additional entrance and it has a   cost of $.&nbsp;35 dollars per person, however,&nbsp;this entrance must be   requested at the time of your reservation and it will be confirmed   according to availability of spaces as they only allow 200 people.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Flights.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;Flying to Cusco can be   complicated.&nbsp;Delays occur frequently especially between October to March   and it is not uncommon for flights to be canceled.&nbsp;Make sure you arrive   in the city at least two days before the start date of your trek to   Machu Picchu.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;is the most reliable airline.&nbsp;Avianca and Peruvian   Airlines&nbsp;are also acceptable companies.&nbsp;You will not return from your   tour on the last day until around 8 pm So make sure your flight is not   the day of the Machu Picchu Tour, rather the next day.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tips</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Tips are always appreciated and should be   based entirely on your level of satisfaction.&nbsp;Although it may not be   usual for you, it has considerable importance to the people who will   assist you during your trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Travel insurance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; To protect your travel   investment, we recommend the purchase&nbsp;a travel insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel   insurance before leaving home is highly recommended and very   easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending on your country of   origin and at different prices according to your time of stay, take some   time to review them and hire the one that best suits you.&nbsp;This is an   excellent way to protect yourself while visiting&nbsp;Peru.</li>\r\n  </ul>', '  <h3>Breafing (Previous Information)</h3>\r\n  <p>All information sessions are held in our office at 06:00 PM the night   before your trek.&nbsp;If you cannot assist to this talk please contact our   office staff to serve you better.</p>\r\n  <h3>Duffle Bags</h3>\r\n  <p>You will receive your duffle bag at the information session.&nbsp;These   bags are to put your belongings inside it, these will be carried by the   porters and will be returned to you each evening at the   campsite.&nbsp;However, beside from these bags, you should carry a small   backpack where you will carry everything you need during the trek.</p>\r\n  <p>Each duffle bag must have a maximum weight of 7kg.&nbsp;4kg will be for   your clothes and other personal items, the other 3kg will be for our   logistics, such as your sleeping bag and pad, if you have your own   sleeping bag and mat these must be included in the 7 kilos.</p>\r\n  <h3>Arrive in Cusco</h3>\r\n  <p>The airport in Cusco&nbsp;is currently&nbsp;quite small and only for domestic   flights, so all international travelers by plane must disembark   in&nbsp;Lima&nbsp;and go through Customs.&nbsp;Even if your flight to&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is the same   day by the same airline, you must pick up your bags in Lima and then   register them again.</p>\r\n  <p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline   options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it   has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU,   LC PERU&nbsp;to choose according to your preference.&nbsp;Expect&nbsp;flight delays or   cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult   to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.&nbsp;Bus   tours&nbsp;are always available and although the journey may be long,   especially from&nbsp;Lima,&nbsp;Peru buses&nbsp;are well maintained and are   comfortable.&nbsp;This option is recommended if you come from a city closer   to&nbsp;Cusco like Puno or Arequipa.&nbsp;Buses from Lima will take around 20   hours to arrive to Cusco.</p>\r\n  <h3>Pick Up from The Hotels.</h3>\r\n  <p>We pick up all our clients from the hotel for all tours.&nbsp;While your   hotel is in the center of the city of Cusco, we will coordinate this   pick up&nbsp;with the&nbsp;guide at the information session.&nbsp;Pick-up&nbsp;times&nbsp;may   vary between 20 and 30&nbsp;minutes depending on traffic conditions and   hotel&nbsp;locations.</p>\r\n  <p>Cusco is an ancient city with cobblestone streets and very narrow   corridors.&nbsp;Very small hotels and Air BNBs are often located on streets   that cars cannot pass through.&nbsp;They are also usually located on the side   of the hill, with long and steep climbs to the property, difficult to   maneuver with luggage.&nbsp;We recommend that you do not&nbsp;stay in one of these   places and try to find places where there is easy access to carry your   bags.</p>\r\n  <h3>Leaving Machu Picchu requires a lot of logistics,&nbsp;but&nbsp;everything&nbsp;is&nbsp;included in your journey.</h3>\r\n  <p>From Machu Picchu&nbsp;Ruins&nbsp;to&nbsp;Machu Picchu Pueblo, you&nbsp;will take a   25-minute bus.&nbsp;The&nbsp;buses are in order of arrival and you can take any of   those in turn.</p>\r\n  <p>From Machu Picchu Pueblo,&nbsp;you will take a&nbsp;train&nbsp;to&nbsp;Ollantaytambo or   Poroy&nbsp;station.&nbsp;Your guide will give you your train tickets.&nbsp;Make sure   you get to the platform 30 minutes ahead of time.</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Ollantaytambo is 2 hours.</li>\r\n    <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Poroy is 3.5 hours.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>Once you arrive at the train station, look&nbsp;for our staff with a PPT sign.&nbsp;He&nbsp;will take you to the Plaza San Francisco, Cusco.</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>The trip on&nbsp;the van&nbsp;from Ollantaytambo to Plaza de San Francisco is 2 hours</li>\r\n    <li>Travel by&nbsp;van&nbsp;from Poroy to&nbsp;San Francisco Plaza is&nbsp;30 minutes</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>Once you arrive at the Plaza San Francisco&nbsp;our staff will be waiting   for you to separate you and send in pre-paid taxis to your respective   hotels.</p>\r\n  <h3>Entrance fees to Machu Picchu</h3>\r\n  <p>Machu Picchu now has two&nbsp;hours&nbsp;to visit: morning or afternoon.&nbsp;Your   ticket will be&nbsp;for a single&nbsp;entry,&nbsp;in the morning, once your time is   done, the&nbsp;guards will ask&nbsp;you&nbsp;to&nbsp;leave.</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Morning turn: 6AM &ndash; 12PM</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>Afternoon turn: 12PM &ndash; 5:30 PM</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>NOTE:</strong>&nbsp;If you have tickets to&nbsp;climb to Huayna Picchu   or Machu Picchu Mountain, you will have additional time until 2:30   PM.&nbsp;And you can re-enter for a single time as long as it is within the   time of re-entry (05 hours from the first entry)</p>\r\n  <p>If you want&nbsp;to&nbsp;spend all day at Machu Picchu, we can add a ticket&nbsp;for   the&nbsp;afternoon&nbsp;group&nbsp;to your reservation for $ 50 per person.</p>\r\n  <h3>Huayna Picchu / Machu Picchu Mountain</h3>\r\n  <p>Machu Picchu is more beautiful when viewed from above, so it is very   popular to hike one of the mountains next to the ruins after your guided   tour.</p>\r\n  <p>Huayna Picchu is the most popular and must be booked in advance &hellip; it   sells very fast.&nbsp;This hike takes approximately&nbsp;50&nbsp;minutes to the top   and&nbsp;40&nbsp;minutes downhill to the bottom.&nbsp;There are 2 schedules or groups   to enter this mountain.&nbsp;The first group&nbsp;is 8-p am and&nbsp;the second&nbsp;is 10   am to 11 am.&nbsp;Again, this refers to when you can start your hike and   normally we reserve the second&nbsp;option&nbsp;so you can first enjoy your tour   with your guide&nbsp;in Machu Picchu.&nbsp;This walk will be&nbsp;done&nbsp;on your own, but   your guide will show you where to start.</p>\r\n  <p>The Machu Picchu mountain is a little longer and less popular.&nbsp;It   takes&nbsp;2&nbsp;hours to reach the top&nbsp;and 1.5&nbsp;hours to reach the bottom.&nbsp;There   are also 2 visiting hours: from 7-8 am and from 9 am to 10 am and we   usually buy&nbsp;for the second group.</p>\r\n  <h3>Health Concerns</h3>\r\n  <p>It is important that you be honest with your guide about any health   problems you may suffer.&nbsp;Although the guides are not medical   professionals, they are trained in first aid.&nbsp;We also work with a clinic   in Cusco that can help our team.</p>\r\n  <p>You are responsible for evaluating if a trek is suitable for you.&nbsp;You   should consult your doctor to confirm your physical condition to travel   and participate in any planned activity.&nbsp;You should seek advice from   your doctor about vaccinations and medical precautions.&nbsp;Peru Private   Tours will&nbsp;not provide medical advice.&nbsp;It is your responsibility to   assess the risks and requirements of each aspect of the Tour based on   your own circumstances, limitations, fitness level and medical   requirements.</p>\r\n  <p>If during the trek you get sick of extreme altitude or any other   illness that not allows you to continuing with the journey, but you want   to visit Machu Picchu by train, we will work with you to coordinate   this trip.&nbsp;This will be a new trip and may involve additional costs.&nbsp;We   will use as much of the logistics purchased from the original route to   keep rates low.</p>\r\n  <p>If you experience problems while walking and cannot continue, a   porter will escort you to the nearest road and wait while a car comes to   pick you up and take you to the nearest health clinic.</p>\r\n  <h3>Group trips</h3>\r\n  <p>Group tours are made up of different types of people, with different   walking skills and ages.&nbsp;By accepting a group trip, you understand that   some people may be slower or faster than you.&nbsp;Everyone can make their   own pace for the walk, the guide will work through the group to spend   time with everyone.&nbsp;Groups can request some modifications to the tour   and&nbsp;the&nbsp;guide will work with everyone to make the best decision for the   group.</p>\r\n  <h3>Strikes</h3>\r\n  <p>Unfortunately, strikes are very common in Peru and can cause many   interruptions in our Tours.&nbsp;Roads are often blocked, trains stopped.&nbsp;We   will do everything possible to operate your Tour, even before the&nbsp;start   date.&nbsp;Some tours may&nbsp;be canceled under these circumstances.&nbsp;Our   Operations Department will coordinate with you in this situation.&nbsp;Your   safety is always our main concern and will determine how we decide.</p>\r\n  <h3>Lost Items</h3>\r\n  <p>You are responsible for your personal items throughout the Tour.&nbsp;Be   diligent about where&nbsp;you&nbsp;leave your stuff and remember&nbsp;to&nbsp;remove all   items from our vans,&nbsp;tents, restaurant, etc.&nbsp;Do not leave anything   involuntary while walking.&nbsp;Other hikers or teams can pick it up without   knowing to whom it belongs.</p>\r\n  <h3>Weather</h3>\r\n  <p>The climate in Cusco and Machu Picchu&nbsp;is unpredictable.&nbsp;In general,   the dry season in&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is from April to October, but this does not   prevent the rain from falling in June or the sun coming out in December,   just prepare for any weather condition.&nbsp;No matter which month you take   the hike or excursion, or which tour you are on, make sure you have   adequate clothing that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho and   waterproof gloves.</p>\r\n  <p>Also be prepared for&nbsp;four seasons in a day.&nbsp;Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a warm jacket.</p>\r\n  <h3>Altitude sickness</h3>\r\n  <p>As soon as the&nbsp;people reserve the trip to&nbsp;Peru, specifically   to&nbsp;Cusco, they begin to wonder about&nbsp;altitude sickness.&nbsp;High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.&nbsp;For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least&nbsp;amount of oxygen in the air.</p>\r\n  <p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p>\r\n  <p>Most of the time, these symptoms will be mild.&nbsp;We always recommend   easy activities and walk&nbsp;slowly, allowing your body to adapt.&nbsp;Drink   plenty of fluids such as water or coca tea.&nbsp;Coca tea&nbsp;has been used since   ancient times to help prevent&nbsp;altitude&nbsp;sickness.&nbsp;The leaves&nbsp;of the coca   plant&nbsp;contain alkaloids that help carry oxygen to the blood, helping   your body avoid the effects of altitude sickness.&nbsp;Avoid drinking a lot   of alcohol and coffee because it will make you urinate more often and   you will become dehydrated.&nbsp;Avoid smoking,&nbsp;Smoking makes it difficult   for your body to get oxygen.&nbsp;Avoid sleeping pills.&nbsp;They can cause   shallow breathing at night, which makes it difficult for your body to   absorb oxygen while you sleep.</p>\r\n  <p>Many people prefer to visit the doctor to give them a treatment with   pills even before traveling to avoid problems during their stay.&nbsp;Your   doctor&nbsp;may prescribe medications, such   as&nbsp;acetazolamide&nbsp;and&nbsp;dexamethasone, to&nbsp;help&nbsp;prevent altitude   sickness.&nbsp;Start the medicine two days before reaching a high   altitude.&nbsp;Continue taking it while you are at high altitude.</p>\r\n  <h3>Travel insurance</h3>\r\n  <p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying&nbsp;travel   insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending   on your country of origin and at different prices&nbsp;according to your time   of stay, take some time to review them and hire the one that best suits   you.&nbsp;This is an excellent way to&nbsp;protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>\r\n  <h3>Community</h3>\r\n  <p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our   community. This is&nbsp;the&nbsp;main&nbsp;objective&nbsp;for our company.&nbsp;We are   working&nbsp;directly with the villages to help them meet the needs of their   families.&nbsp;We support the children of the villages by giving them&nbsp;school   supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and clothes.</p>\r\n  <p>We buy all our food from farmers and local markets and serve the   freshest ingredients.&nbsp;We offer&nbsp;constant training&nbsp;for all our team:   guides, porters, chefs and drivers.&nbsp;We are a family born in the Andes   and we want to work with them and for them.&nbsp;That is why once&nbsp;a year we   bring our porters and their families to&nbsp;Machu&nbsp;Picchu.&nbsp;We want our team   to know the world wonder, since they work tirelessly at the doors of   this place without ever visiting it and&nbsp;showing them this place is our   greatest honor.</p>', '', 'inca-jungle-adventure', 0, '', 0, 0, 499.00, 0, '4 days / 3 nights', 0, 0, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"20887310\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=20887310\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 6, 4),
(18, 'Lares Trek', 'This is a tour that requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend making the reservation in advance, once you make your reservation will be confirmed as long as there is availability of space for the date that you select.', 'By booking this tour your are planting 1 tree at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'Lares Trek has become one of the most important hiking routes to Machu Picchu after the Inca Trail and Salkantay.', '<p><strong>Lares Trek&nbsp;</strong>has become one of the most important hiking   routes to Machu Picchu after the Inca Trail&nbsp;and Salkantay.</p>\r\n<p>It combines   the beauty of the mountains with a cultural visit to 2 indigenous   communities along the trail.&nbsp;You will learn about their culture,   traditions and customs as well as enjoy a football game with the   children&rsquo;s at 4000 meters above sea level.</p>', '  <h3>Included</h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Professional Guide</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;We have the best selection of   guides, all graduated from the national university of&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;and grown up   in this region with a deep love and passion for teaching our   culture.&nbsp;They are fun but professional and will make sure you are safe   and happy.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tourist transport.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; We use clean and new vehicles   for all our services, with professional drivers that will guarantee you a   safe trip. Our drivers are constantly trained in prudent driving and   customer service.&nbsp;The transport will be from Cusco to Soraypampa and   from Ollantaytambo to Cusco at the end of our trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Pick up from the hotel.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Our service includes pick   up from your&nbsp;hotel&nbsp;to start the tour, pick up time will be confirmed   according to the location of your hotel, at the end of the tour we will   also leave you back at your hotel.&nbsp;(Our service does not include pick up   from&nbsp;AIRBNB&nbsp;type houses&nbsp;because many do not have a clear name or   address), in that case we will coordinate a place and time to pick up.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Snacks</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; beside the breakfast, we will provide you   snacks every morning so that you can take you along the way. We will   also provide snack bags that are made of cloth, we are very careful with   the environment so we try not to take anything plastic to the route and   if we do, we bring it back.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Train Tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;The train ticket included is the   Inca Rail the Voyager service, however, on the way you can make an Up   Grade to a 360 &deg; train that has windows on the roof to enjoy the   beautiful views on the road.&nbsp;This has an additional cost of $.&nbsp;$&nbsp;65&nbsp;per   person&nbsp;up to Poroy&nbsp;and is subject to availability. Poroy station is 30   minutes out of Cusco, we will still include the transfer to your hotel.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Bus tickets.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; It is 25 minutes from the Town to Machu Picchu and 25 minutes from Machu Picchu to the town.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Entrance</strong> to <strong>Machu Picchu.</strong>&nbsp;We take   care of providing you with the entrance ticket to Machu Picchu and this   will be giving to you on the day of the tour, by your guide.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Horses:</strong>&nbsp;We include horses and horseman who is   responsible for carrying your travel bag with your personal items.&nbsp;There   is no additional fee for this.&nbsp;The night before we will give you your   duffel bag so that it is filled with the things you will need for the   trek.&nbsp;You will not have access to your duffle bag until you arrive at   your campsite at first night.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Hotel:</strong>&nbsp;Alternative&nbsp;excursions end at Machu Picchu   Pueblo.&nbsp;The last night is spent in a hotel in the village, instead of   camping.&nbsp;This 3-star hotel is included in the cost of the trek and is   based on a shared room.&nbsp;If you want to improve your hotel or prefer a   single room, you will have an additional cost.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Camping equipment:</strong>&nbsp;In Peru Private Tours we have   the best equipment.&nbsp;We use a 4 people tent only between 2 people so you   will have more space to put your belongings inside your tent during the   night.&nbsp;You will have a large tent&nbsp;to enjoy your meals as well as chairs   and table.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Food:</strong>&nbsp;4 breakfasts (the last included in the hotel)   3 lunches and 3 dinners, all prepared by our professional walking   chef.&nbsp;Our professional chefs&nbsp;prepare delicious meals that many previous   hikers have commented on.&nbsp;We honor all dietary restrictions.&nbsp;Be sure to   remind your tour guide about any food restrictions at the beginning of   your walk (Breafing time).&nbsp;The food is typically served family   style.&nbsp;You will enjoy breakfast, lunch and dinner every day of the&nbsp;trek,   with a delicious happy hour every afternoon before dinner.&nbsp;You will   also be provided with a snack every morning, so that you can enjoy the   walk.&nbsp;Your last&nbsp;meal with your chef will be&nbsp;breakfast on day four&nbsp;since   lunch and dinner will be at a restaurant.&nbsp;Lunch on the last day&nbsp;(day   04)&nbsp;is not included.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Water:</strong>&nbsp;from your first lunch until your last   breakfast,&nbsp;PPT&nbsp;will provide you with all the necessary water.&nbsp;This water   will be boiled, filtered and then cooled, before distribution.&nbsp;You must   supply your own bottles of water or camelback.&nbsp;We recommend carrying   around 3L.&nbsp;We will fill our waters at every meal.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>First aid:</strong>&nbsp;each of our guides has received   training in first aid from a doctor.&nbsp;We hold mandatory training sessions   every February, to which all the guides must attend.&nbsp;Your tour guide   will always have a first aid kit for basic medical problems (traveler&rsquo;s   diarrhea, cuts, scratches, etc.) and oxygen tank.&nbsp;We will get you out of   the way as quickly and comfortably as possible if necessary, and we   will make sure you go directly to a clinic to receive treatment.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Extras:</strong>&nbsp;We believe that it is the attention to   small details that differentiates us from other travel companies.&nbsp;Each   hiker receives a small pillow for sleeping, a sponge mats to isolate   (Matra), a backpack covers to protect your belongings during the trek, a   rain poncho and a waterproof plastic bags to put your belongings before   placing them in the duffle bag. We will work hard to create your best   vacations.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Private transfer from Ollantaytambo</strong> to <strong>Cusco.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;   Upon arrival at the Ollantaytambo train station our staff will be   waiting for you with a van only for our group to transfer you to   your&nbsp;hotel in Cusco or Sacred Valley.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Permanent</strong> Assistance.&nbsp;&ndash; We want all the activities   you do in our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so you   will always have an&nbsp;assigned&nbsp;personal assistant&nbsp;who will be in constant   communication with you.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <h3>Not included</h3>\r\n  <p>All travelers need a sleeping bag, do not forget to bring your   own.&nbsp;The walking sticks and air mattresses or matras are optional and   provides greater comfort during the walk.&nbsp;If you do not want to bring   any camping gear you can always rent from our office.</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Sleeping bag: $.&nbsp;20 USD per person</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>Air&nbsp;Mattress: $.&nbsp;20 USD per person</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>Walking sticks (01 pair): $. 15 USD per person</strong></p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>headlamps:</strong> it&nbsp;is strongly recommended to bring a   head lamp for the evenings.&nbsp;There will be no lights on the camping sites   and it will be difficult to get to your dining tent or bathroom tent   without one.&nbsp;Hand lanterns are acceptable, if you do not have a head   lamp, but it makes some tasks difficult.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Huayna Picchu</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;<strong>Huayna Picchu</strong> is   the mountain that is seen behind Machu Picchu in the classic photos, to   go up this mountain you need to buy an additional entrance and it has a   cost of $.&nbsp;35 dollars per person, however,&nbsp;this entrance must be   requested at the time of your reservation and it will be confirmed   according to availability of spaces as they only allow 200 people.</li>\r\n    <li>&nbsp;<strong>Flights.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash;&nbsp;Flying to Cusco can be   complicated.&nbsp;Delays occur frequently especially between October to March   and it is not uncommon for flights to be canceled.&nbsp;Make sure you arrive   in the city at least two days before the start date of your trek to   Machu Picchu.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;is the most reliable airline.&nbsp;Avianca and Peruvian   Airlines&nbsp;are also acceptable companies.&nbsp;You will not return from your   tour on the last day until around 8 pm So make sure your flight is not   the day of the Machu Picchu Tour, rather the next day.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tips</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Tips are always appreciated and should be   based entirely on your level of satisfaction.&nbsp;Although it may not be   usual for you, it has considerable importance to the people who will   assist you during your trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Travel insurance.</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; To protect your travel   investment, we recommend the purchase&nbsp;a travel insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel   insurance before leaving home is highly recommended and very   easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending on your country of   origin and at different prices according to your time of stay, take some   time to review them and hire the one that best suits you.&nbsp;This is an   excellent way to protect yourself while visiting&nbsp;Peru.</li>\r\n  </ul>', '  <h3>Breafing (Previous Information)</h3>\r\n  <p>All information sessions are held in our office at 06:00 PM the night   before your trek.&nbsp;If you cannot assist to this talk please contact our   office staff to serve you better.</p>\r\n  <h3>Duffle Bags</h3>\r\n  <p>You will receive your duffle bag at the information session.&nbsp;These   bags are to put your belongings inside it, these will be carried by the   porters and will be returned to you each evening at the   campsite.&nbsp;However, beside from these bags, you should carry a small   backpack where you will carry everything you need during the trek.</p>\r\n  <p>Each duffle bag must have a maximum weight of 7kg.&nbsp;4kg will be for   your clothes and other personal items, the other 3kg will be for our   logistics, such as your sleeping bag and pad, if you have your own   sleeping bag and mat these must be included in the 7 kilos.</p>\r\n  <h3>Arrive in Cusco</h3>\r\n  <p>The airport in Cusco&nbsp;is currently&nbsp;quite small and only for domestic   flights, so all international travelers by plane must disembark   in&nbsp;Lima&nbsp;and go through Customs.&nbsp;Even if your flight to&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is the same   day by the same airline, you must pick up your bags in Lima and then   register them again.</p>\r\n  <p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline   options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it   has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU,   LC PERU&nbsp;to choose according to your preference.&nbsp;Expect&nbsp;flight delays or   cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult   to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.&nbsp;Bus   tours&nbsp;are always available and although the journey may be long,   especially from&nbsp;Lima,&nbsp;Peru buses&nbsp;are well maintained and are   comfortable.&nbsp;This option is recommended if you come from a city closer   to&nbsp;Cusco like Puno or Arequipa.&nbsp;Buses from Lima will take around 20   hours to arrive to Cusco.</p>\r\n  <h3>Pick Up from The Hotels.</h3>\r\n  <p>We pick up all our clients from the hotel for all tours.&nbsp;While your   hotel is in the center of the city of Cusco, we will coordinate this   pick up&nbsp;with the&nbsp;guide at the information session.&nbsp;Pick-up&nbsp;times&nbsp;may   vary between 20 and 30&nbsp;minutes depending on traffic conditions and   hotel&nbsp;locations.</p>\r\n  <p>Cusco is an ancient city with cobblestone streets and very narrow   corridors.&nbsp;Very small hotels and Air BNBs are often located on streets   that cars cannot pass through.&nbsp;They are also usually located on the side   of the hill, with long and steep climbs to the property, difficult to   maneuver with luggage.&nbsp;We recommend that you do not&nbsp;stay in one of these   places and try to find places where there is easy access to carry your   bags.</p>\r\n  <h3>Leaving Machu Picchu requires a lot of logistics,&nbsp;but&nbsp;everything&nbsp;is&nbsp;included in your journey.</h3>\r\n  <p>From Machu Picchu&nbsp;Ruins&nbsp;to&nbsp;Machu Picchu Pueblo, you&nbsp;will take a   25-minute bus.&nbsp;The&nbsp;buses are in order of arrival and you can take any of   those in turn.</p>\r\n  <p>From Machu Picchu Pueblo,&nbsp;you will take a&nbsp;train&nbsp;to&nbsp;Ollantaytambo or   Poroy&nbsp;station.&nbsp;Your guide will give you your train tickets.&nbsp;Make sure   you get to the platform 30 minutes ahead of time.</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Ollantaytambo is 2 hours.</li>\r\n    <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Poroy is 3.5 hours.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>Once you arrive at the train station, look&nbsp;for our staff with a PPT sign.&nbsp;He&nbsp;will take you to the Plaza San Francisco, Cusco.</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li>The trip on&nbsp;the van&nbsp;from Ollantaytambo to Plaza de San Francisco is 2 hours</li>\r\n    <li>Travel by&nbsp;van&nbsp;from Poroy to&nbsp;San Francisco Plaza is&nbsp;30 minutes</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <p>Once you arrive at the Plaza San Francisco&nbsp;our staff will be waiting   for you to separate you and send in pre-paid taxis to your respective   hotels.</p>\r\n  <h3>Entrance fees to Machu Picchu</h3>\r\n  <p>Machu Picchu now has two&nbsp;hours&nbsp;to visit: morning or afternoon.&nbsp;Your   ticket will be&nbsp;for a single&nbsp;entry,&nbsp;in the morning, once your time is   done, the&nbsp;guards will ask&nbsp;you&nbsp;to&nbsp;leave.</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Morning turn: 6AM &ndash; 12PM</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>Afternoon turn: 12PM &ndash; 5:30 PM</strong></p>\r\n  <p><strong>NOTE:</strong>&nbsp;If you have tickets to&nbsp;climb to Huayna Picchu   or Machu Picchu Mountain, you will have additional time until 2:30   PM.&nbsp;And you can re-enter for a single time as long as it is within the   time of re-entry (05 hours from the first entry)</p>\r\n  <p>If you want&nbsp;to&nbsp;spend all day at Machu Picchu, we can add a ticket&nbsp;for   the&nbsp;afternoon&nbsp;group&nbsp;to your reservation for $ 50 per person.</p>\r\n  <h3>Huayna Picchu / Machu Picchu Mountain</h3>\r\n  <p>Machu Picchu is more beautiful when viewed from above, so it is very   popular to hike one of the mountains next to the ruins after your guided   tour.</p>\r\n  <p>Huayna Picchu is the most popular and must be booked in advance &hellip; it   sells very fast.&nbsp;This hike takes approximately&nbsp;50&nbsp;minutes to the top   and&nbsp;40&nbsp;minutes downhill to the bottom.&nbsp;There are 2 schedules or groups   to enter this mountain.&nbsp;The first group&nbsp;is 8-p am and&nbsp;the second&nbsp;is 10   am to 11 am.&nbsp;Again, this refers to when you can start your hike and   normally we reserve the second&nbsp;option&nbsp;so you can first enjoy your tour   with your guide&nbsp;in Machu Picchu.&nbsp;This walk will be&nbsp;done&nbsp;on your own, but   your guide will show you where to start.</p>\r\n  <p>The Machu Picchu mountain is a little longer and less popular.&nbsp;It   takes&nbsp;2&nbsp;hours to reach the top&nbsp;and 1.5&nbsp;hours to reach the bottom.&nbsp;There   are also 2 visiting hours: from 7-8 am and from 9 am to 10 am and we   usually buy&nbsp;for the second group.</p>\r\n  <h3>Health Concerns</h3>\r\n  <p>It is important that you be honest with your guide about any health   problems you may suffer.&nbsp;Although the guides are not medical   professionals, they are trained in first aid.&nbsp;We also work with a clinic   in Cusco that can help our team.</p>\r\n  <p>You are responsible for evaluating if a trek is suitable for you.&nbsp;You   should consult your doctor to confirm your physical condition to travel   and participate in any planned activity.&nbsp;You should seek advice from   your doctor about vaccinations and medical precautions.&nbsp;Peru Private   Tours will&nbsp;not provide medical advice.&nbsp;It is your responsibility to   assess the risks and requirements of each aspect of the Tour based on   your own circumstances, limitations, fitness level and medical   requirements.</p>\r\n  <p>If during the trek you get sick of extreme altitude or any other   illness that not allows you to continuing with the journey, but you want   to visit Machu Picchu by train, we will work with you to coordinate   this trip.&nbsp;This will be a new trip and may involve additional costs.&nbsp;We   will use as much of the logistics purchased from the original route to   keep rates low.</p>\r\n  <p>If you experience problems while walking and cannot continue, a   porter will escort you to the nearest road and wait while a car comes to   pick you up and take you to the nearest health clinic.</p>\r\n  <h3>Group trips</h3>\r\n  <p>Group tours are made up of different types of people, with different   walking skills and ages.&nbsp;By accepting a group trip, you understand that   some people may be slower or faster than you.&nbsp;Everyone can make their   own pace for the walk, the guide will work through the group to spend   time with everyone.&nbsp;Groups can request some modifications to the tour   and&nbsp;the&nbsp;guide will work with everyone to make the best decision for the   group.</p>\r\n  <h3>Strikes</h3>\r\n  <p>Unfortunately, strikes are very common in Peru and can cause many   interruptions in our Tours.&nbsp;Roads are often blocked, trains stopped.&nbsp;We   will do everything possible to operate your Tour, even before the&nbsp;start   date.&nbsp;Some tours may&nbsp;be canceled under these circumstances.&nbsp;Our   Operations Department will coordinate with you in this situation.&nbsp;Your   safety is always our main concern and will determine how we decide.</p>\r\n  <h3>Lost Items</h3>\r\n  <p>You are responsible for your personal items throughout the Tour.&nbsp;Be   diligent about where&nbsp;you&nbsp;leave your stuff and remember&nbsp;to&nbsp;remove all   items from our vans,&nbsp;tents, restaurant, etc.&nbsp;Do not leave anything   involuntary while walking.&nbsp;Other hikers or teams can pick it up without   knowing to whom it belongs.</p>\r\n  <h3>Weather</h3>\r\n  <p>The climate in Cusco and Machu Picchu&nbsp;is unpredictable.&nbsp;In general,   the dry season in&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is from April to October, but this does not   prevent the rain from falling in June or the sun coming out in December,   just prepare for any weather condition.&nbsp;No matter which month you take   the hike or excursion, or which tour you are on, make sure you have   adequate clothing that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho and   waterproof gloves.</p>\r\n  <p>Also be prepared for&nbsp;four seasons in a day.&nbsp;Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a warm jacket.</p>\r\n  <h3>Altitude sickness</h3>\r\n  <p>As soon as the&nbsp;people reserve the trip to&nbsp;Peru, specifically   to&nbsp;Cusco, they begin to wonder about&nbsp;altitude sickness.&nbsp;High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.&nbsp;For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least&nbsp;amount of oxygen in the air.</p>\r\n  <p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p>\r\n  <p>Most of the time, these symptoms will be mild.&nbsp;We always recommend   easy activities and walk&nbsp;slowly, allowing your body to adapt.&nbsp;Drink   plenty of fluids such as water or coca tea.&nbsp;Coca tea&nbsp;has been used since   ancient times to help prevent&nbsp;altitude&nbsp;sickness.&nbsp;The leaves&nbsp;of the coca   plant&nbsp;contain alkaloids that help carry oxygen to the blood, helping   your body avoid the effects of altitude sickness.&nbsp;Avoid drinking a lot   of alcohol and coffee because it will make you urinate more often and   you will become dehydrated.&nbsp;Avoid smoking,&nbsp;Smoking makes it difficult   for your body to get oxygen.&nbsp;Avoid sleeping pills.&nbsp;They can cause   shallow breathing at night, which makes it difficult for your body to   absorb oxygen while you sleep.</p>\r\n  <p>Many people prefer to visit the doctor to give them a treatment with   pills even before traveling to avoid problems during their stay.&nbsp;Your   doctor&nbsp;may prescribe medications, such   as&nbsp;acetazolamide&nbsp;and&nbsp;dexamethasone, to&nbsp;help&nbsp;prevent altitude   sickness.&nbsp;Start the medicine two days before reaching a high   altitude.&nbsp;Continue taking it while you are at high altitude.</p>\r\n  <h3>Travel insurance</h3>\r\n  <p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying&nbsp;travel   insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending   on your country of origin and at different prices&nbsp;according to your time   of stay, take some time to review them and hire the one that best suits   you.&nbsp;This is an excellent way to&nbsp;protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>\r\n  <h3>Community</h3>\r\n  <p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our   community. This is&nbsp;the&nbsp;main&nbsp;objective&nbsp;for our company.&nbsp;We are   working&nbsp;directly with the villages to help them meet the needs of their   families.&nbsp;We support the children of the villages by giving them&nbsp;school   supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and clothes.</p>\r\n  <p>We buy all our food from farmers and local markets and serve the   freshest ingredients.&nbsp;We offer&nbsp;constant training&nbsp;for all our team:   guides, porters, chefs and drivers.&nbsp;We are a family born in the Andes   and we want to work with them and for them.&nbsp;That is why once&nbsp;a year we   bring our porters and their families to&nbsp;Machu&nbsp;Picchu.&nbsp;We want our team   to know the world wonder, since they work tirelessly at the doors of   this place without ever visiting it and&nbsp;showing them this place is our   greatest honor.</p>', '', 'lares-trek', 0, '', 0, 0, 549.00, 0, '4 days / 3 nights', 0, 0, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"88085464\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=88085464\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 6, 4);
INSERT INTO `ProgramaPPT` (`Identificador`, `NombreIngles`, `MensajeIngles`, `MensajeSocialIngles`, `IntroduccionIngles`, `DescripcionIngles`, `IncluyeIngles`, `MasInformacionIngles`, `FAQIngles`, `Enlace`, `IdDestino`, `DestinosIngles`, `IdActividad`, `IdTipo`, `Precio`, `Duracion`, `DuracionIngles`, `Dificultad`, `EsPortada`, `OrdenPortada`, `CodigoWeTravel`, `CantidadImagenes`, `IdCategoria`) VALUES
(19, 'Huchuy Qosqo', 'This is a tour that requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend making the reservation in advance, once you make your reservation will be confirmed as long as there is availability of space for the date that you select.', 'By booking this tour your are planting 1 tree at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'Huchuy Qosqo Trek It is an excellent option of trekking for those who want outdoor activities but do not have much time.', '<p><strong>Huchuy Qosqo Trek </strong>It is an excellent option of trekking   for those who want outdoor activities but do not have much time, this   fantastic option of a single day is something unique and wonderful, in   the tour we will enjoy beautiful views of hills, valleys, lagoons, flora   and fauna, canyons and the archaeological center of <strong>Huchuy Qosqo.</strong></p>\r\n<p>In   addition, it is not a. overcrowded trail so you can enjoy your walk   being the only one in the mountains, our itinerary will help you enjoy   unique views on the route.</p>', '<h3>What Our Cusco Day Hike Includeds</h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Professional Guide</strong> – We have the best selection of   guides, all graduated from the national university of Cusco and grown up   in this region with a deep love and passion for teaching their   culture. They are fun but professional and will make sure you are safe   and happy.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tourist transportation.</strong> – We use clean and new   vehicles for all our services, with professional drivers that will   guarantee you a safe trip. Our drivers are constantly trained in prudent   driving and customer service. The car transfer will be from Cusco to   the trail head, then from sacred valley to Cusco.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Pick up from the hotel.</strong> – Our service includes   picking up your hotel to start the tour, pick up time will be confirmed   according to the location of your hotel, at the end of the tour we will   also leave you back at your hotel. (Our service does not include pick up   from AIRBNB type houses because many do not have a clear name or   address), in that case we will coordinate a place and time to pick up.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Meals.</strong> – 01 box lunch that will be taken by a support staff.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>First aid:</strong> each of our guides has received training   in first aid from a doctor. We hold mandatory training sessions every   February, to which all the guides must attend. Your tour guide will   always have a first aid kit for basic medical problems (traveler&rsquo;s   diarrhea, cuts, scratches, etc.) and oxygen. We will get you out of the   way as quickly and comfortably as possible, if necessary, and we will   make sure you go directly to a clinic to receive treatment..</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Permanent Assistance.</strong> – We want all the activities   you do in our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so you   will always have an assigned personal assistant who will be in constant   communication with you.</li>\r\n  </ul>\r\n  <h3>What Our Cusco Day Hike Doesn`t Include</h3>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Flights.</strong> – Flying to Cusco can be complicated.   Delays occur frequently especially between October to March and it is   not uncommon for flights to be canceled. Make sure you arrive in the   city at least two days before the start date of your hike. <a href=\"https://www.latam.com/en_us/\">LATAM</a> is   the most reliable airline. Avianca and Peruvian Airlines are also   acceptable companies. You will not return from your tour until around 8   pm So make sure your flight is not the trekking day, rather the next   day.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tips</strong> – Tips are always appreciated and should be   based entirely on your level of satisfaction. Although it may not be   usual for you, it has considerable importance for the people who will   assist you during your trek.</li>\r\n    <li> <strong>Travel insurance.</strong> – To protect your travel   investment, we recommend the purchase of travel insurance. Getting   travel insurance before leaving home is highly recommended and very   easy. There are many insurance companies depending on your country of   origin and at different prices according to your time of stay, take some   time to review them and hire the one that best suits you. This is an   excellent way to protect yourself while visiting <strong>Peru.</strong></li>\r\n  </ul>', '<h3>Breafing (Previous Information)</h3>\r\n  <p>All information sessions are held in our office at 06:00 PM the night   before your trek. If you cannot assist to this talk please contact our   office staff to serve you better.</p>\r\n  <h3>Arriving to Cusco</h3>\r\n  <p>The airport in Cusco is currently quite small and only for domestic   flights, so all international travelers by plane must disembark   in Lima and go through Customs. Even if your flight to Cusco is the same   day by the same airline, you must pick up your bags in Lima and then   register them again.</p>\r\n  <p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several airline options. <a href=\"https://www.latam.com/en_us/\">LATAM</a> tends   to be the most expensive, but it has more flight options. But you also   have PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU, LC PERU to choose according to your   preference. Also Expect flight delays or cancellations, due to the   high altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult to land so that on rainy   days you can paralyze air traffic. Bus tours are always available and   although the journey may be long, especially from Lima, Peru buses are   well maintained and are comfortable. This option is recommended if you   come from a city closer to Cusco like Puno or Arequipa. Buses from Lima   will take around 20 hours to arrive to Cusco.</p>\r\n  <h3>Pick Up from The Hotels.</h3>\r\n  <p>We pick up all our clients from the hotel for all tours. While your   hotel is in the center of the city of Cusco, we will coordinate this   pick up with the guide at the information session. Pick-up times may   vary between 20 and 30 minutes depending on traffic conditions and   hotel locations.</p>\r\n  <p>Cusco is an ancient city with cobblestone streets and very narrow   corridors. Very small hotels and Air BNBs are often located on streets   that cars cannot pass through. They are also usually located on the side   of the hill, with long and steep climbs to the property, difficult to   maneuver with luggage. We recommend that you do not stay in one of these   places and try to find places where there is easy access to carry your   bags.</p>\r\n  <h3>Health Concerns</h3>\r\n  <p>It is important that you be honest with your guide about any health   problems you may suffer. Although the guides are not medical   professionals, they are trained in first aid. We also work with a clinic   in Cusco that can help our team.</p>\r\n  <p>You are responsible for evaluating if a trek is suitable for you.   Consult your doctor to confirm your physical condition to travel and   participate in any planned activity. You should seek advice from your   doctor about vaccinations and medical precautions. Peru Private Tours   will not provide medical advice. It is your responsibility to assess the   risks and requirements of each aspect of the Tour based on your own   circumstances, limitations, fitness level and medical requirements.</p>\r\n  <p>If during the trek you get sick of extreme altitude or any other   illness that not allows you to continuing with the journey, but you want   to visit Machu Picchu by train, we will work with you to coordinate   this trip. This will be a new trip and may involve additional costs. We   will use as much of the logistics purchased from the original route to   keep rates low.</p>\r\n  <p>If you experience problems while walking and cannot continue, a   porter will escort you to the nearest road and wait while a car comes to   pick you up and take you to the nearest health clinic.</p>\r\n  <h3>Group trips</h3>\r\n  <p>Group tours are made up of different types of people, with different   walking skills and ages. By accepting a group trip, you understand that   some people may be slower or faster than you. Everyone can make their   own pace for the walk, the guide will work through the group to spend   time with everyone. Groups can request some modifications to the tour   and the guide will work with everyone to make the best decision for the   group.</p>\r\n  <h3>Strikes</h3>\r\n  <p>Unfortunately, strikes are very common in Peru and can cause many   interruptions in our Tours. Roads are often blocked, trains stopped. We   will do everything possible to operate your Tour, even before the start   date. Some tours may be canceled under these circumstances. Our   Operations Department will coordinate with you in this situation. Your   safety is always our main concern and will determine how we decide.</p>\r\n  <h3>Lost Items</h3>\r\n  <p>You are responsible for your personal items throughout the Tour. Be   diligent about where you leave your stuff and remember to remove all   items from our vans, tents, restaurant, etc. Do not leave anything   involuntary while walking. Other hikers or teams can pick it up without   knowing to whom it belongs.</p>\r\n  <h3>Weather</h3>\r\n  <p>The climate in Cusco and Machu Picchu is unpredictable. In general,   the dry season in Cusco is from April to October, but this does not   prevent the rain from falling in June or the sun coming out in December,   just prepare for any weather condition. No matter which month you take   the hike or excursion, or which tour you are on, make sure you have   adequate clothing that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho and   waterproof gloves.</p>\r\n  <p>Also be prepared for four seasons in a day. Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons. The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures. And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a warm jacket.</p>\r\n  <h3>Altitude sickness</h3>\r\n  <p>As soon as the people reserve the trip to Peru, specifically   to Cusco, they begin to wonder about altitude sickness. High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs. For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least amount of oxygen in the air.</p>\r\n  <p>The first symptoms of altitude sickness may be; headache,   fatigue, followed by loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise. If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p>\r\n  <p>for farther info about altitude sickness <a href=\"http://www.pptoursperu.com/altitud-sickness-in-cusco/\">CLIC HERE</a></p>\r\n  <h3>Travel insurance</h3>\r\n  <p>To protect your travel investment, we also recommend buying travel   insurance. Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy. There are many insurance companies depending   on your country of origin and at different prices according to your time   of stay, take some time to review them and hire the one that best suits   you. This is an excellent way to protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>', '', 'huchuy-qosqo', 0, '', 0, 0, 89.00, 0, 'Full day', 0, 0, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"41595923\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=41595923\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 7, 2),
(20, 'Salkantay Trek 5D/4N', 'This is a tour that requires a special permit issued by the Peruvian government through the Ministry of Culture, so we recommend making the reservation in advance, once you make your reservation will be confirmed as long as there is availability of space for the date that you select, please make sure to check the availability.', 'by booking this tour your are planting 1 tree at an indiginous community of Cusco', 'Salkantay has become one of the most important hiking routes to Machu Picchu after the Inca Trail, which makes it so interesting to this route is the combination of all kinds of attractions...', '<p><strong>Salkantay</strong>&nbsp;has become one of the most important hiking   routes to Machu Picchu after the Inca Trail, which makes it so   interesting to this route is the combination of all kinds of   attractions: Natural, cultural, local history and adventure, combined   all in a single program, also the&nbsp;change of scenery is impressive   because you can descend in a single day from cold mountains near the   snowy to fertile valleys where you can appreciate coffee, bananas and   all kinds of tropical fruits.</p>\r\n<p>In addition, we are one of the very few   agencies that camp in front of Machu Picchu with a unique and privileged   view of the hydroelectric valley.&nbsp;See Machu Picchu from the comfort of   your tent is something you cannot have even on the Inca Trail.</p>', '  <h2>Included</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Professional</strong> Guide.&ndash;We have the best selection of   guides, all graduated from the national university ofCuscoand grown up   in this region with a deep love and passion for teaching our   culture.They are fun but professional and will make sure you are safe   and happy.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tourist transport.</strong>&ndash; We use clean and new vehicles   for all our services, with professional drivers that will guarantee you a   safe trip. Our drivers are constantly trained in prudent <strong>driving</strong> and customer service.The transport will be from Cusco to Soraypampa and from Ollantaytambo to Cusco at the end of our trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Pick up from the hotel.</strong>&ndash; Our service includes pick   up from yourhotelto start the tour, pick up time will be confirmed   according to the location of your hotel, at the end of the tour we will   also leave you back at your hotel.(Our service does not include pick up   fromAIRBNBtype housesbecause many do not have a clear name or   address), in that case we will coordinate a place and time to pick up.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Snacks</strong>&ndash; beside the breakfast, we will provide you   snacks every morning so that you can take you along the way. We will   also provide snack bags that are made of cloth, we are very careful with   the environment so we try not to take anything plastic to the route and   if we do, we bring it back.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Train Tickets.</strong>&ndash;The train ticket included is the   Inca Rail the Voyager service, however, on the way you can make an Up   Grade to a 360 &deg; train that has windows on the roof to enjoy the   beautiful views on the road.This has an additional cost of $.$65per   personup to Poroyand is subject to availability. Poroy station is 30   minutes out of Cusco, we will still include the transfer to your hotel.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Bus tickets.</strong>&ndash; It is 25 minutes from the Town to Machu Picchu and 25 minutes from Machu Picchu to the town.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Entrance to Machu Picchu.</strong>We take care of providing   you with the entrance ticket to Machu Picchu and this will be giving to   you on the day of the tour, by your guide.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Porters:</strong>We include a personal porter, who is   responsible for carrying your travel bag with your personal items.There   is no additional fee for this.The night before we will give you your   duffel bag so that it is filled with the things you will need for the   trek.You will not have access to your duffle bag until you arrive at   your campsite at first night.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Hotel:</strong>Alternativeexcursions end at Machu Picchu   Pueblo.The last night is spent in a hotel in the village, instead of   camping.This 3-star hotel is included in the cost of the trek and is   based on a shared room.If you want to improve your hotel or prefer a   single room, you will have an additional cost.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Camping equipment:</strong>In Peru Private Tours we have   the best equipment.We use a 4 people tent only between 2 people so you   will have more space to put your belongings inside your tent during the   night.You will have a large tentto enjoy your meals as well as chairs   and table.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Food:</strong>5 breakfasts (the last included in the hotel)   4 lunches and 4 dinners, all prepared by our professional walking   chef.Our professional chefsprepare delicious meals that many previous   hikers have commented on.We honor all dietary restrictions.Be sure to   remind your tour guide about any food restrictions at the beginning of   your walk (Breafing time).The food is typically served family   style.You will enjoy breakfast, lunch and dinner every day of thetrek,   with a delicious happy hour every afternoon before dinner.You will   also be provided with a snack every morning, so that you can enjoy the   walk.Your lastmeal with your chef will bebreakfast on day foursince   lunch and dinner will be at a restaurant.Lunch on the last day(day   05)is not included.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Water:</strong>from your first lunch until your last   breakfast,PPTwill provide you with all the necessary water.This water   will be boiled, filtered and then cooled, before distribution.You must   supply your own bottles of water or camelback.We recommend carrying   around 3L.We will fill our waters at every meal.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>First aid:</strong>each of our guides has received training   in first aid from a doctor.We hold mandatory training sessions every   February, to which all the guides must attend.Your tour guide will   always have a first aid kit for basic medical problems (traveler&rsquo;s   diarrhea, cuts, scratches, etc.) and oxygen tank.We will get you out of   the way as quickly and comfortably as possible if necessary, and we   will make sure you go directly to a clinic to receive treatment.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Extras:</strong>We believe that it is the attention to   small details that differentiates us from other travel companies.Each   hiker receives a small pillow for sleeping, a sponge mats to isolate   (Matra), a backpack covers to protect your belongings during the trek, a   rain poncho and a waterproof plastic bags to put your belongings before   placing them in the duffle bag. We will work hard to create your best   vacations.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Private transfer from Ollantaytambo</strong> to Cusco.&ndash;   Upon arrival at the Ollantaytambo train station our staff will be   waiting for you with a van only for our group to transfer you to   yourhotel in Cusco or Sacred Valley.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Permanent Assistance.</strong>&ndash; We want all the activities   you do in our destination to be unique, unforgettable and safe, so you   will always have anassignedpersonal assistantwho will be in constant   communication with you.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n  <h3>Not included</h3>\r\n  <p>All travelers need a sleeping bag, do not forget to bring your   own.The walking sticks and air mattresses or matras are optional and   provides greater comfort during the walk.If you do not want to bring   any camping gear you can always rent from our office.</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Sleeping bag</strong> $.20 USD per person</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Air</strong><strong> Matress </strong>$.20 USD per person</p>\r\n  <p><strong>Walking sticks</strong> (01 pair)  $.USD 15 per person</p>\r\n  <ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Headlamps:</strong> itis strongly recommended to bring a   head lamp for the evenings.There will be no lights on the camping sites   and it will be difficult to get to your dining tent or bathroom tent   without one.Hand lanterns are acceptable, if you do not have a head   lamp, but it makes some tasks difficult.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Huayna Picchu</strong> &ndash; Huayna Picchu is the mountain   that is seen behind Machu Picchu in the classic photos, to go up this   mountain you need to buy an additional entrance and it has a cost of   $.35 dollars per person, however,this entrance must be requested at   the time of your reservation and it will be confirmed according to   availability of spaces as they only allow 200 people.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Flights.</strong>&ndash;Flying to Cusco can be   complicated.Delays occur frequently especially between October to March   and it is not uncommon for flights to be canceled.Make sure you arrive   in the city at least two days before the start date of your trek to   Machu Picchu.LATAMis the most reliable airline.Avianca and Peruvian   Airlinesare also acceptable companies.You will not return from your   tour on the last day until around 8 pm So make sure your flight is not   the day of the Machu Picchu Tour, rather the next day.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Tips</strong>&ndash; Tips are always appreciated and should be   based entirely on your level of satisfaction.Although it may not be   usual for you, it has considerable importance to the people who will   assist you during your trek.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Travel insurance.</strong>&ndash; To protect your travel   investment, we recommend the purchasea travel insurance.Getting travel   insurance before leaving home is highly recommended and very   easy.There are many insurance companies depending on your country of   origin and at different prices according to your time of stay, take some   time to review them and hire the one that best suits you.This is an   excellent way to protect yourself while visiting <strong>Peru.</strong></li>\r\n  </ul>', '<h3>Breafing (Previous Information)</h3>\r\n<p>All information sessions are held in our office at 06:00 PM the night   before your trek.&nbsp;If you cannot assist to this talk please contact our   office staff to serve you better.</p>\r\n<h3>Duffle Bags</h3>\r\n<p>You will receive your duffle bag at the information session.&nbsp;These   bags are to put your belongings inside it, these will be carried by the   porters and will be returned to you each evening at the   campsite.&nbsp;However, beside from these bags, you should carry a small   backpack where you will carry everything you need during the trek.</p>\r\n<p>Each duffle bag must have a maximum weight of 7kg.&nbsp;4kg will be for   your clothes and other personal items, the other 3kg will be for our   logistics, such as your sleeping bag and pad, if you have your own   sleeping bag and mat these must be included in the 7 kilos.</p>\r\n<h3>Arrive in Cusco</h3>\r\n<p>The airport in Cusco&nbsp;is currently&nbsp;quite small and only for domestic   flights, so all international travelers by plane must disembark   in&nbsp;Lima&nbsp;and go through Customs.&nbsp;Even if your flight to&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is the same   day by the same airline, you must pick up your bags in Lima and then   register them again.</p>\r\n<p>The best way to get to Cusco is by air and there are several&nbsp;airline   options.&nbsp;LATAM&nbsp;tends to be the most expensive, but it   has&nbsp;more&nbsp;flight&nbsp;options.&nbsp;But you also have&nbsp;PERUVIAN, AVIANCA, STAR PERU,   LC PERU&nbsp;to choose according to your preference.&nbsp;Expect&nbsp;flight delays or   cancellations,&nbsp;due to the high&nbsp;altitude of Cusco, tends to be difficult   to land&nbsp;so that on rainy days you can paralyze&nbsp;air traffic.&nbsp;Bus   tours&nbsp;are always available and although the journey may be long,   especially from&nbsp;Lima,&nbsp;Peru buses&nbsp;are well maintained and are   comfortable.&nbsp;This option is recommended if you come from a city closer   to&nbsp;Cusco like Puno or Arequipa.&nbsp;Buses from Lima will take around 20   hours to arrive to Cusco.</p>\r\n<h3>Pick Up from The Hotels.</h3>\r\n<p>We pick up all our clients from the hotel for all tours.&nbsp;While your   hotel is in the center of the city of Cusco, we will coordinate this   pick up&nbsp;with the&nbsp;guide at the information session.&nbsp;Pick-up&nbsp;times&nbsp;may   vary between 20 and 30&nbsp;minutes depending on traffic conditions and   hotel&nbsp;locations.</p>\r\n<p>Cusco is an ancient city with cobblestone streets and very narrow   corridors.&nbsp;Very small hotels and Air BNBs are often located on streets   that cars cannot pass through.&nbsp;They are also usually located on the side   of the hill, with long and steep climbs to the property, difficult to   maneuver with luggage.&nbsp;We recommend that you do not&nbsp;stay in one of these   places and try to find places where there is easy access to carry your   bags.</p>\r\n<h3>Leaving Machu Picchu requires a lot of logistics,&nbsp;but&nbsp;everything&nbsp;is&nbsp;included in your journey.</h3>\r\n<p>From Machu Picchu&nbsp;Ruins&nbsp;to&nbsp;Machu Picchu Pueblo, you&nbsp;will take a   25-minute bus.&nbsp;The&nbsp;buses are in order of arrival and you can take any of   those in turn.</p>\r\n<p>From Machu Picchu Pueblo,&nbsp;you will take a&nbsp;train&nbsp;to&nbsp;Ollantaytambo or   Poroy&nbsp;station.&nbsp;Your guide will give you your train tickets.&nbsp;Make sure   you get to the platform 30 minutes ahead of time.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Ollantaytambo is 2 hours.</li>\r\n  <li>The train from Aguas Calientes to Poroy is 3.5 hours.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Once you arrive at the train station, look&nbsp;for our staff with a PPT sign.&nbsp;He&nbsp;will take you to the Plaza San Francisco, Cusco.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>The trip on&nbsp;the van&nbsp;from Ollantaytambo to Plaza de San Francisco is 2 hours</li>\r\n  <li>Travel by&nbsp;van&nbsp;from Poroy to&nbsp;San Francisco Plaza is&nbsp;30 minutes</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Once you arrive at the Plaza San Francisco&nbsp;our staff will be waiting   for you to separate you and send in pre-paid taxis to your respective   hotels.</p>\r\n<h3>Entrance fees to Machu Picchu</h3>\r\n<p>Machu Picchu now has two&nbsp;hours&nbsp;to visit: morning or afternoon.&nbsp;Your   ticket will be&nbsp;for a single&nbsp;entry,&nbsp;in the morning, once your time is   done, the&nbsp;guards will ask&nbsp;you&nbsp;to&nbsp;leave.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Morning turn: 6AM &ndash; 12PM</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Afternoon turn: 12PM &ndash; 5:30 PM</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong>&nbsp;If you have tickets to&nbsp;climb to Huayna Picchu   or Machu Picchu Mountain, you will have additional time until 2:30   PM.&nbsp;And you can re-enter for a single time as long as it is within the   time of re-entry (05 hours from the first entry)</p>\r\n<p>If you want&nbsp;to&nbsp;spend all day at Machu Picchu, we can add a ticket&nbsp;for   the&nbsp;afternoon&nbsp;group&nbsp;to your reservation for $ 50 per person.</p>\r\n<h3>Huayna Picchu / Machu Picchu Mountain</h3>\r\n<p>Machu Picchu is more beautiful when viewed from above, so it is very   popular to hike one of the mountains next to the ruins after your guided   tour.</p>\r\n<p>Huayna Picchu is the most popular and must be booked in advance &hellip; it   sells very fast.&nbsp;This hike takes approximately&nbsp;50&nbsp;minutes to the top   and&nbsp;40&nbsp;minutes downhill to the bottom.&nbsp;There are 2 schedules or groups   to enter this mountain.&nbsp;The first group&nbsp;is 8-p am and&nbsp;the second&nbsp;is 10   am to 11 am.&nbsp;Again, this refers to when you can start your hike and   normally we reserve the second&nbsp;option&nbsp;so you can first enjoy your tour   with your guide&nbsp;in Machu Picchu.&nbsp;This walk will be&nbsp;done&nbsp;on your own, but   your guide will show you where to start.</p>\r\n<p>The Machu Picchu mountain is a little longer and less popular.&nbsp;It   takes&nbsp;2&nbsp;hours to reach the top&nbsp;and 1.5&nbsp;hours to reach the bottom.&nbsp;There   are also 2 visiting hours: from 7-8 am and from 9 am to 10 am and we   usually buy&nbsp;for the second group.</p>\r\n<h3>Health Concerns</h3>\r\n<p>It is important that you be honest with your guide about any health   problems you may suffer.&nbsp;Although the guides are not medical   professionals, they are trained in first aid.&nbsp;We also work with a clinic   in Cusco that can help our team.</p>\r\n<p>You are responsible for evaluating if a trek is suitable for you.&nbsp;You   should consult your doctor to confirm your physical condition to travel   and participate in any planned activity.&nbsp;You should seek advice from   your doctor about vaccinations and medical precautions.&nbsp;Peru Private   Tours will&nbsp;not provide medical advice.&nbsp;It is your responsibility to   assess the risks and requirements of each aspect of the Tour based on   your own circumstances, limitations, fitness level and medical   requirements.</p>\r\n<p>If during the trek you get sick of extreme altitude or any other   illness that not allows you to continuing with the journey, but you want   to visit Machu Picchu by train, we will work with you to coordinate   this trip.&nbsp;This will be a new trip and may involve additional costs.&nbsp;We   will use as much of the logistics purchased from the original route to   keep rates low.</p>\r\n<p>If you experience problems while walking and cannot continue, a   porter will escort you to the nearest road and wait while a car comes to   pick you up and take you to the nearest health clinic.</p>\r\n<h3>Group trips</h3>\r\n<p>Group tours are made up of different types of people, with different   walking skills and ages.&nbsp;By accepting a group trip, you understand that   some people may be slower or faster than you.&nbsp;Everyone can make their   own pace for the walk, the guide will work through the group to spend   time with everyone.&nbsp;Groups can request some modifications to the tour   and&nbsp;the&nbsp;guide will work with everyone to make the best decision for the   group.</p>\r\n<h3>Strikes</h3>\r\n<p>Unfortunately, strikes are very common in Peru and can cause many   interruptions in our Tours.&nbsp;Roads are often blocked, trains stopped.&nbsp;We   will do everything possible to operate your Tour, even before the&nbsp;start   date.&nbsp;Some tours may&nbsp;be canceled under these circumstances.&nbsp;Our   Operations Department will coordinate with you in this situation.&nbsp;Your   safety is always our main concern and will determine how we decide.</p>\r\n<h3>Lost Items</h3>\r\n<p>You are responsible for your personal items throughout the Tour.&nbsp;Be   diligent about where&nbsp;you&nbsp;leave your stuff and remember&nbsp;to&nbsp;remove all   items from our vans,&nbsp;tents, restaurant, etc.&nbsp;Do not leave anything   involuntary while walking.&nbsp;Other hikers or teams can pick it up without   knowing to whom it belongs.</p>\r\n<h3>Weather</h3>\r\n<p>The climate in Cusco and Machu Picchu&nbsp;is unpredictable.&nbsp;In general,   the dry season in&nbsp;Cusco&nbsp;is from April to October, but this does not   prevent the rain from falling in June or the sun coming out in December,   just prepare for any weather condition.&nbsp;No matter which month you take   the hike or excursion, or which tour you are on, make sure you have   adequate clothing that includes a waterproof jacket, pants, poncho and   waterproof gloves.</p>\r\n<p>Also be prepared for&nbsp;four seasons in a day.&nbsp;Many of the excursions   through the Andes involve many microclimates and you will have to be   prepared for all seasons.&nbsp;The layers are always key because they are   easy to adjust to different temperatures.&nbsp;And the nights will always be   cold, so get ready with a warm jacket.</p>\r\n<h3>Altitude sickness</h3>\r\n<p>As soon as the&nbsp;people reserve the trip to&nbsp;Peru, specifically   to&nbsp;Cusco, they begin to wonder about&nbsp;altitude sickness.&nbsp;High altitudes   contains less oxygen than at sea level and forces your body to work   harder to get the oxygen it needs.&nbsp;For few days at high altitude your   body adjusts to the least&nbsp;amount of oxygen in the air.</p>\r\n<p>The&nbsp;first symptoms of altitude sickness&nbsp;may be;&nbsp;headache,   fatigue,&nbsp;followed by&nbsp;loss of appetite, nausea or vomit, dizziness,   trouble sleeping, difficulty breathing during exercise.&nbsp;If any of these   effects worsen, contact our office and we will help you get to a doctor.</p>\r\n<p>Most of the time, these symptoms will be mild.&nbsp;We always recommend   easy activities and walk&nbsp;slowly, allowing your body to adapt.&nbsp;Drink   plenty of fluids such as water or coca tea.&nbsp;Coca tea&nbsp;has been used since   ancient times to help prevent&nbsp;altitude&nbsp;sickness.&nbsp;The leaves&nbsp;of the coca   plant&nbsp;contain alkaloids that help carry oxygen to the blood, helping   your body avoid the effects of altitude sickness.&nbsp;Avoid drinking a lot   of alcohol and coffee because it will make you urinate more often and   you will become dehydrated.&nbsp;Avoid smoking,&nbsp;Smoking makes it difficult   for your body to get oxygen.&nbsp;Avoid sleeping pills.&nbsp;They can cause   shallow breathing at night, which makes it difficult for your body to   absorb oxygen while you sleep.</p>\r\n<p>Many people prefer to visit the doctor to give them a treatment with   pills even before traveling to avoid problems during their stay.&nbsp;Your   doctor&nbsp;may prescribe medications, such   as&nbsp;acetazolamide&nbsp;and&nbsp;dexamethasone, to&nbsp;help&nbsp;prevent altitude   sickness.&nbsp;Start the medicine two days before reaching a high   altitude.&nbsp;Continue taking it while you are at high altitude.</p>\r\n<h3>Travel insurance</h3>\r\n<p>To protect your travel investment, we recommend buying&nbsp;travel   insurance.&nbsp;Getting travel insurance before leaving home is highly   recommended and very easy.&nbsp;There are many insurance companies depending   on your country of origin and at different prices&nbsp;according to your time   of stay, take some time to review them and hire the one that best suits   you.&nbsp;This is an excellent way to&nbsp;protect yourself while visiting Peru.</p>\r\n<h3>Community</h3>\r\n<p>At&nbsp;Peru Private Tours (PPT)&nbsp;we are proud&nbsp;of the work we do for our   community. This is&nbsp;the&nbsp;main&nbsp;objective&nbsp;for our company.&nbsp;We are   working&nbsp;directly with the villages to help them meet the needs of their   families.&nbsp;We support the children of the villages by giving them&nbsp;school   supplies,&nbsp;books&nbsp;and clothes.</p>\r\n<p>We buy all our food from farmers and local markets and serve the   freshest ingredients.&nbsp;We offer&nbsp;constant training&nbsp;for all our team:   guides, porters, chefs and drivers.&nbsp;We are a family born in the Andes   and we want to work with them and for them.&nbsp;That is why once&nbsp;a year we   bring our porters and their families to&nbsp;Machu&nbsp;Picchu.&nbsp;We want our team   to know the world wonder, since they work tirelessly at the doors of   this place without ever visiting it and&nbsp;showing them this place is our   greatest honor.</p>', '', 'salkantay-trek-5-days-4-nights', 0, '', 0, 0, 0.00, 0, '5 days / 4 nights', 0, 0, 0, '<button class=\"wtrvl-checkout_button\" id=\"wetravel_button_widget\" data-env=\"https://www.wetravel.com\" data-version=\"v0.3\" data-uid=\"1162090\" data-uuid=\"88356623\" href=\"https://www.wetravel.com/checkout_embed?uuid=88356623\" style=\"background-color:#33ae3f;color:#ffffff;border: 0px;border-radius: 5px;font-family: \'Poppins\', sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size: 14px;-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;text-transform: capitalize;padding: 13px 24px;text-decoration: none;text-align: center;line-height: 14px;display: inline-block; cursor: pointer;\">Book Now</button><link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Poppins\" rel=\"stylesheet\"><script src=\"https://cdn.wetravel.com/widgets/embed_checkout.js\"></script>', 7, 4);

